{"title_page": "Saint Helena Airport", "text_new": "{{short description|Airport in the British Overseas Territory of Saint Helena}}\n{{EngvarB|date=October 2013}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2019}}\n{{Infobox airport\n| name = a few hundred million of taxpayers nicely spunked on a white elephant. Well done dfid!\n| nativename = \n| image = St Helena Airport logo.svg\n| image-width = 200\n| image2 = First Comair Boeing 737-800 flight to Saint Helena Airport (191).jpg\n| image2-width =  250\n| IATA = HLE\n| ICAO = FHSH\n| WMO = 61901\n| type = Public\n| owner = Saint Helena Government\n| operator = St Helena Airport Limited\n| location = [[Longwood, Saint Helena|Longwood]], [[Saint Helena, Ascension and Tristan da Cunha]]\n| opened = June 2016\n| hub = \n| elevation-f = 1017\n| elevation-m = \n| coordinates = {{coord|15|57|33|S|5|38|45|W|region:SH-HL|display=inline,title}}\n| website = [http://www.sthelenaairport.com sthelenaairport.com]\n| pushpin_map = South Atlantic\n| pushpin_mapsize = \n| pushpin_map_alt = \n| pushpin_map_caption = Location of St Helena Airport\n| pushpin_relief = \n| pushpin_image = South Atlantic Ocean laea relief location map.jpg\n| pushpin_label = HLE\n| pushpin_label_position = bottom\n| pushpin_mark = \n| pushpin_marksize = \n| r1-number = 02/20\n| r1-length-f = \n| r1-length-m = 1950\n| r1-surface = Concrete\n| metric-rwy = yes\n| stat-year = 2018\n| stat1-header = Passengers\n| stat1-data = 7649 <ref>{{Cite web |url=http://sartma.com/art_14816.html |title=St Helena : VISITORS TO ST HELENA HIGHLIGHTS IN 2018 |access-date=2 February 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190202100736/http://sartma.com/art_14816.html |archive-date=2 February 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n| footnotes = Sources: AIP St Helena,<ref name=\"aip_fhsh_adc\" /> St Helena Government<ref name=\"IM\">{{cite web|url=http://www.flytosthelena.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/06/St-Helena-Air-Services-Information-Memorandum.pdf|title=St Helena Government \u2013 Information Memorandum|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304082601/http://www.flytosthelena.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/06/St-Helena-Air-Services-Information-Memorandum.pdf|archive-date=4 March 2016}}</ref>\n}}\n\n'''Saint Helena Airport''' {{Airport codes|HLE|FHSH}} is an [[international airport]] on [[Saint Helena]], a remote island in the south [[Atlantic Ocean]], in the [[British Overseas Territories|British Overseas Territory]] of [[Saint Helena, Ascension and Tristan da Cunha|Saint Helena, Ascension, and Tristan da Cunha.]]\n\nThe construction of the runway was finished in 2015 and the airport opened in 2016.  The inaugural scheduled flight was delayed but general aviation, charter, and medical evacuation flights were able to serve the airport from May 2016.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.sainthelena.gov.sh/cancellation-of-notice-to-airmen/ |title=Cancellation of Notice To Airmen \u00ab St Helena |publisher=Sainthelena.gov.sh |date=1 July 2016 |access-date=25 July 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161026174632/http://www.sainthelena.gov.sh/cancellation-of-notice-to-airmen/ |archive-date=26 October 2016 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://sainthelenaisland.info/flyyourselfhere.htm |title=Saint Helena Island Info: All about St Helena, in the South Atlantic Ocean \u2022 Fly Yourself Here |publisher=Sainthelenaisland.info |access-date=25 July 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170325082913/http://sainthelenaisland.info/flyyourselfhere.htm |archive-date=25 March 2017 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nThe airport began scheduled commercial services on 14 October 2017, when the South African carrier [[Airlink]] inaugurated a weekly service from [[O. R. Tambo International Airport]] in [[Johannesburg]], [[South Africa]], via [[Walvis Bay Airport]], [[Namibia]], using an [[Embraer E-Jet family|Embraer E190-100IGW]],<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.sainthelena.gov.sh/st-helena-prepares-for-inaugural-flight/|title=ST HELENA PREPARES FOR INAUGURAL FLIGHT|date=10 October 2017|work=St Helena|access-date=14 October 2017|language=en-US|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171014182516/http://www.sainthelena.gov.sh/st-helena-prepares-for-inaugural-flight/|archive-date=14 October 2017|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Pillay|first1=Kavitha|title=#FindYourEscape: Airlink flights to St Helena from SA now on sale|url=http://www.traveller24.com/News/Flights/findyourescape-airlink-flights-to-st-helena-from-sa-now-on-sale-20170922|access-date=23 September 2017|publisher=traveller24.com|date=22 September 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170923193715/http://www.traveller24.com/News/Flights/findyourescape-airlink-flights-to-st-helena-from-sa-now-on-sale-20170922|archive-date=23 September 2017|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite press release |url=https://flyairlink.com/news/airlinks-embraer-e190-ejets-commence-commercial-services |title=Airlink's Emmbraer E190 E-Jets Commence Commercial Services |publisher=Flyairlink.com |date=3 August 2017 |access-date=23 September 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170824092419/https://flyairlink.com/news/airlinks-embraer-e190-ejets-commence-commercial-services |archive-date=24 August 2017 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.sainthelena.gov.sh/sa-airlink-to-provide-scheduled-air-services-to-st-helena-and-ascension-island/ |title=Sa Airlink To Provide Scheduled Air Services To St Helena And Ascension Island \u00ab St Helena |publisher=Sainthelena.gov.sh |date=21 July 2017 |access-date=23 September 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170825223035/http://www.sainthelena.gov.sh/sa-airlink-to-provide-scheduled-air-services-to-st-helena-and-ascension-island/ |archive-date=25 August 2017 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name=bbc20171014>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-africa-41620003|title=First flight lands on remote St Helena|date=14 October 2017|via=www.bbc.com|access-date=21 June 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180620011451/https://www.bbc.com/news/world-africa-41620003|archive-date=20 June 2018|url-status=live|work=BBC News}}</ref> about one and a half years after the originally expected inauguration date, and with a smaller-sized aircraft, because of [[wind shear]] problems affecting the airport.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ch-aviation.com/portal/news/51502-st-helena-issues-second-rfp-for-scheduled-services|title=St. Helena issues second RFP for scheduled services|publisher=ch-aviation.com|access-date=25 July 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170227182926/http://www.ch-aviation.com/portal/news/51502-st-helena-issues-second-rfp-for-scheduled-services|archive-date=27 February 2017|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"AIRPORT OPENING CEREMONY POSTPONED\">[http://www.sainthelenaaccess.com/news/2016/04/27/airport-opening-ceremony-postponed/ AIRPORT OPENING CEREMONY POSTPONED] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160726092953/http://www.sainthelenaaccess.com/news/2016/04/27/airport-opening-ceremony-postponed/ |date=26 July 2016 }} (St Helena Government 26 April 2016)</ref><ref name=\"bbcnews\">[https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-36490496 bbc.com \u2013 St Helena airport delay 'to increase cost to UK government'] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180627020030/https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-36490496 |date=27 June 2018 }} 9 May 2016</ref> Additionally, monthly charter flights operate between [[Ascension Island]] and Saint Helena.\n\n==History==\n===Background===\nSaint Helena is more than {{convert|2000|km|mi|-2}} from the nearest major landmass.  Prior to the opening of the airport, the island was only reachable by sea, making it one of the most remote populated places on earth, measured as travel time from major cities. Sea journeys used to take five days from [[Cape Town]], with departures once every three weeks.\n\nThe first consideration of an airport on St Helena was made in 1943 by the [[South African Air Force]], which undertook a survey on [[Prosperous Bay Plain]] from October 1943 until January 1944, but concluded that, while technically feasible, an airport was not a practical proposition.<ref name=\"consultation_annex_a\">{{cite web |url=http://www.dfid.gov.uk/documents/consultations/sthelena/consult-sthele-annexes-apr09.pdf |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110202192044/http://www.dfid.gov.uk/Documents/consultations/sthelena/consult-sthele-annexes-apr09.pdf |url-status=dead |archive-date=2 February 2011 |title=DFID Consultation Document \u2013 Annex A \u2013 Summary of cost/benefit analysis and financial costs |publisher=DFID |date=16 April 2009 |page=12 }}</ref>\nFrom the 1960s, there was an idea{{by whom|date=April 2016}} to build an airport on the Island. In 1999, this was taken up by the island government.\n\nIt was suggested that an airport would extend the United Kingdom's capabilities to carry out airborne missions in the South Atlantic region, such as [[maritime patrol]]s in accordance with international fishing agreements (e.g., [[International Commission for the Conservation of Atlantic Tunas]]), counter-piracy missions along important trade routes, and also [[airlift]] operations notably into Southern Africa.{{citation needed|date=May 2017}}\n\nAccording to analysts,{{who|date=May 2017}} the UK government's decision to finally go ahead with the airport, after long delays, seems to be driven in part by concerns over a continuing tense standoff with Argentina in the [[Falkland Islands sovereignty dispute]]. The island is about {{convert|3812|mi}} from the Falklands \u2013 seven hours and 40 minutes' flight time. But, analysts say that was nevertheless an improvement over the present state of isolation from the UK for both St Helena and the Falklands.<ref name=\"upi.com\">{{cite web |url=http://www.upi.com/Business_News/Security-Industry/2011/11/07/St-Helena-airport-a-key-Falklands-link/UPI-78911320686806/ |title=St. Helena airport a key Falklands link |date=7 November 2011 |publisher=United Press International, Inc. |access-date=8 August 2012 |work=news article |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120202081633/http://www.upi.com/Business_News/Security-Industry/2011/11/07/St-Helena-airport-a-key-Falklands-link/UPI-78911320686806/ |archive-date=2 February 2012 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nThe following possible benefits were also factors in the decision-making process:\n* Air access would allow St Helena to develop its tourism sector.{{Citation needed|date=July 2017}}\n* The new wharf in Rupert's Bay could allow regularly passing cruise ships to land passengers at the island and bring tourists if sized appropriately. The lack of a protected landing facility represents a limitation on the development of cruise tourism. In unfavourable sea conditions, landing is hazardous and potential revenue is lost as many cruise ships refuse to allow passengers to land in such circumstances. In addition, because there is no protected landing facility, many cruise companies do not incorporate St Helena into their itineraries. The sea is roughest in summer which marks the peak of the cruise season.<ref>[http://www.sainthelena.gov.sh/data/files/non_technical_summary.pdf \"''Jamestown, St Helena Wharf Improvements, Project EIA: Phase 2, Final Report''\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111103165325/http://www.sainthelena.gov.sh/data/files/non_technical_summary.pdf |date=3 November 2011 }} by the Government of St Helena, 8 August 2011</ref>\n* Medical evacuations to South Africa for treatment of serious cases of illness would be sped up significantly: it may take up to one month until transport to South Africa by RMS ''St Helena'' becomes available.{{Citation needed|date=July 2017}}\n* The availability of heavy construction equipment would facilitate [[alternative energy]] projects, such as the construction of larger wind turbines, a [[tidal power plant]] or a dam with a hydro-power station in one of St Helena's valleys.<ref>[http://www.sainthelenaaccess.com/application/documents/Environmental-Statement/Volume_2_Technical_Summary/ES_Vol_2_Chap%2017_Combined%20Effects.pdf St Helena Airport Environmental Statement \u2013 Volume 2] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120426081417/http://www.sainthelenaaccess.com/application/documents/Environmental-Statement/Volume_2_Technical_Summary/ES_Vol_2_Chap%2017_Combined%20Effects.pdf |date=26 April 2012 }} by Faber Maunsell AECOM, p. 17-3</ref> Limitations in cargo size of ''[[RMS St Helena (1989)|RMS St Helena]]'' and the unavailability of a large crane prohibit construction of larger wind turbines.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=OXiTOjFj8MI#t=0m15s |title=Interview with Craig Penwarden, Renewable Energy Engineer at Saint Helena Government |access-date=28 November 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120523004935/http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=OXiTOjFj8MI#t=0m15s |archive-date=23 May 2012 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n[[File:View out over Prosperous Bay Plain, St Helena Island, c1985. Peter Neaum. - panoramio.jpg|thumb|View over Prosperous Bay Plain in the 1980s.]]\nIn contrast to the projected benefits, there were concerns that the proposed construction on the Prosperous Bay Plain would be detrimental to the local environment.  Specifically, Prosperous Bay Plain was one of the few remaining sites on Saint Helena that held [[Wildlife of St Helena|significant ecological diversity]].  According to a 2004 review by Atkins Management Consultants, the survival of numerous [[endemism|endemic species]] critically depended on preservation and protection of the location.  It was also an important{{according to whom|date=August 2015}} nesting site for the [[Saint Helena plover|wirebird]], Saint Helena's national bird which is listed as [[vulnerable species|vulnerable]]. Although the St Helena Leisure Corporation (Shelco) was a major force pushing for the airport's construction, its co-founder Sir Nigel Thompson was a former chairman of the environmental charity [[Campaign to Protect Rural England]].<ref name = propertyweek /><ref>Robin Stummer and Daniel Howden: [http://www.ezilon.com/information/article_11885.shtml \"The Battle for St Helena\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070927005814/http://www.ezilon.com/information/article_11885.shtml |date=27 September 2007 }}. ''Ezilon Infobase'', 20 October 2005. Retrieved 28 August 2007.</ref><ref>{{WWF ecoregion|name=St. Helena scrub and woodlands|id=at0720}} Retrieved 28 August 2007.</ref>\n\n=== Bidding process ===\nAfter a long period of rumour and consultation, in March 2005 the British government announced plans to construct an airport in St Helena, expected to be completed by 2010 and funded by the [[Department for International Development]] (DfID).\n\nAccording to ''[[Private Eye]]'' magazine, all of the companies tendering for the job of building and running the airport had by late September 2006 withdrawn from bidding for the project. The local Access Office explained that it seemed the bidders considered the DfID was unhelpful by not providing the possibility of on-site investigations in order to complete a detailed design before providing a fixed price for the project. According to the DfID's Director for Overseas Territories, his department remained committed to an airport for St Helena.<ref>\"Departure Delayed\". ''Private Eye'', No. 1167, 15\u201328 September 2006.</ref>\n\nDfID restarted the procurement process to identify a suitable [[Project delivery method|Design, Build and Operate]] (DBO) contractor in October 2006. Capability Statements were received by DfID in March 2007 and four bidders were pre-approved for the DBO contract and a further three applicants have been pre-approved for the Air Service Provider contract. The applicants for the DBO visited the island for six months from June 2007 before submitting their final proposals, and by January 2008 DfID was down to a shortlist of two bidders.\n\nThere were delays by the British government,<ref name=\"consultation_annex_a\"/> which went up to [[Prime Minister of the United Kingdom|Prime Minister]] [[Gordon Brown]] who insisted on personally reviewing the paperwork.<ref>{{cite news |url= https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2008/sep/26/gordonbrown.labourconference |title= Salvaged with a kiss? Maybe, but Brown's woes run deep |first= Martin |last= Kettle |newspaper= The Guardian |date= 26 September 2008 |access-date= 13 December 2016 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20170312152236/https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2008/sep/26/gordonbrown.labourconference |archive-date= 12 March 2017 |url-status= live }}</ref> An approved bidder was appointed in 2008, the Italian company [[Impregilo]]. The project was suspended in November 2008, because of financial pressures brought on by the [[financial crisis of 2007\u20132010]].\n\nIt was reported in ''[[The Guardian]]'' on 10 December 2008 that UK Secretary of State for International Development [[Douglas Alexander]] had announced a \"pause in negotiations over the St Helena airport contract\",<ref name = guardian>Owen Bowcott: \"[https://www.theguardian.com/travel/2008/dec/10/st-helena-airport-travel-tourism] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160305184647/http://www.theguardian.com/travel/2008/dec/10/st-helena-airport-travel-tourism |date=5 March 2016 }}\". ''[[The Guardian]]'', 10 December 2008. Retrieved 2008-DEC-10.</ref> apparently related to the 2008 economic downturn.\n\nThe St. Helena Leisure Corporation (Shelco) was set up by [[Arup Group Limited|Arup]]'s Sir Nigel Thompson and [[Berwin Leighton Paisner]]'s Robert Jones, who planned to construct luxury resorts and a hotel to be run by [[Oberoi Hotels & Resorts]] in conjunction with the airport. Though real estate was to be sold before construction had started, the proposal was turned down by the local government and the DfID.<ref name = propertyweek>David Lawson: \"[http://www.propertyweek.com/story.asp?storyCode=3056937 Island in the Sun] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070927201509/http://www.propertyweek.com/story.asp?storyCode=3056937 |date=27 September 2007 }}\". ''[[Property Week]]'', 30 September 2005. Retrieved 29 August 2007.</ref>\n\nThe cost of airport was reported to be \u00a3285.5 million for DfID in April 2016.<ref name=\"bbcnews\" />\n\n===Airport construction===\nApproximately \u00a3202 million was funded for design and construction by South African engineering group Basil Read (Pty) Ltd. The UK government also granted additional funds of up to \u00a310 million in shared-risk contingency, and \u00a335.1 million for 10 years of operation by South African airport operator Lanseria Airport. According to the St Helena government, this was 20% less in real terms from the 2008 price, taking into account inflation and the value of the pound. The airport would be the largest single investment ever made in the island.<ref name=\"Airport Approved\"/>\n\nHowever, no final contracts had been signed by January 2009 and as construction had not commenced, the [[Governor of Saint Helena, Ascension and Tristan da Cunha|island's governor]], [[Andrew Gurr (governor)|Andrew Gurr]], travelled to London in an attempt to speed up the process. On 22 July 2010 the British government agreed to assist in payment for the new airport.<ref>{{cite news |url= https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/worldnews/africaandindianocean/sainthelena/7905386/Britain-to-pay-for-St-Helena-airstrip-backed-by-Lord-Ashcroft.html |title= Britain to pay for St Helena airstrip backed by Lord Ashcroft |newspaper= [[The Daily Telegraph|The Telegraph]] |date= 22 July 2010 |access-date= 2 April 2018 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20121114175810/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/worldnews/africaandindianocean/sainthelena/7905386/Britain-to-pay-for-St-Helena-airstrip-backed-by-Lord-Ashcroft.html |archive-date= 14 November 2012 |url-status= live }}</ref> On 3 November 2011 Governor [[Mark Andrew Capes|Mark Capes]] announced construction contracts had been signed.<ref name=\"Airport Approved\">{{cite news |url= http://www.news.co.sh/Newspapers/SHH%2020111104.pdf |title= Airport Approved |newspaper= The St Helena Herald |volume= XI |number= 28 |date= 4 November 2011 |page= 4 }}{{Dead link|date=August 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\n[[File:Prosperous Bay Plain Airport (16512903591).jpg|thumbnail|right|Construction on [[Prosperous Bay Plain]], February 2015]]\nOn 4 November 2011 Basil Read was awarded the contract to construct an airport on St Helena Island.<ref name=\"basilread.co.za\"/> The first representatives of Basil Read visited the island on Saturday, 19 November 2011 for initial investigations and discussions.<ref>[http://www.sainthelena.gov.sh/news.php/448/basil-read-team-progression-with-airport-developments \"''Basil Read Team \u2013 Progression with Airport Developments''\"] {{webarchive|url=https://archive.is/20120805115952/http://www.sainthelena.gov.sh/news.php/448/basil-read-team-progression-with-airport-developments |date=5 August 2012 }} St Helena Government Public Relations / Information Office, Press Release, 24 November 2011</ref> Following a second team's visit during December 2011 Basil Read's project manager settled on the island and the first St Helenian citizen was employed.<ref name=\"news.co.sh\"/>\n\nBasil Read CEO Heyns in November 2011 said the design phase would begin immediately and anticipated that construction could begin in May 2012, which at peak would employ some 300 people of whom as many locals as possible should be involved.<ref>[http://www.saint.fm/Independent/20111021.pdf \"''Airport News''\"] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130510171912/http://www.saint.fm/Independent/20111021.pdf |date=10 May 2013 }} St Helena Independent, Volume VI, Issue 49, 21 October 2011, p. 2</ref> Construction is said to take place over a 48-month period.<ref name=\"engineeringnews.co.za\"/>\n\nPreparation works began in early 2012 in Rupert's Valley on the west coast, which included establishing storage facilities, a temporary fuel farm and the design and construction of a temporary wharf.<ref name=\"Basil Read Team Arrives' 2011, p.4\">[http://www.news.co.sh/Newspapers/SHH%2020111209.pdf \"''Second Basil Read Team Arrives''\"]{{dead link|date=April 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }} The St Helena Herald, Volume XI Number 33, 9 December 2011, p.4</ref> A new jetty was built at Rupert's Bay to enable the landing of supplies and construction vehicles.\n\nOnly four weeks after the approval for the airport to be constructed and years before operations would start, Geo. Robson & Co. (Conveyors) Ltd. had already completed and shipped a [[baggage carousel]] for the airport. The company stated that with a {{convert|12|m|adj=on}} perimeter it was one of the smallest baggage carousels they had ever manufactured.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hub-4.com/news/4013/robson-ships-to-the-south-atlantic|title=Robson Ships to the South Atlantic|publisher=HUB|date=1 December 2011|access-date=30 December 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120426081614/http://www.hub-4.com/news/4013/robson-ships-to-the-south-atlantic|archive-date=26 April 2012|url-status=live}}</ref> Until the airport opened it was planned for use at St Helena's harbour to deliver baggage to passengers arriving by RMS ''St Helena''.{{Citation needed|date=July 2017}}\n\n[[File:St Helena Airport Terminal (16331626258).jpg|thumb|right|Construction of the airport terminal and air traffic control tower.]]\nLogistics of the airport's construction were critical, because of the island's isolated location and the lack of construction equipment, which would require everything such as extremely heavy duty equipment and materials to be shipped in, thus resulting in a huge and unique logistics operation.<ref name=\"news.co.sh\">[http://www.news.co.sh/Newspapers/SHH%2020111223.pdf \"''Basil Read's second team Visits and first St Helenian employed''\", St Helena Herald, Volume XI no. 35, 23 December 2011, p. 5]{{dead link|date=April 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> Due to the limited landing infrastructure, with no breakwater or mooring facilities at the sea front, new harbour facilities capable of handling construction equipment and fuel supplies were constructed at Rupert's Bay.<ref>[http://www.sainthelenaaccess.com/application/documents/Feasibility/01_Main_Report_Final.pdf \"''St Helena Access Feasibility Study''\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120426081359/http://www.sainthelenaaccess.com/application/documents/Feasibility/01_Main_Report_Final.pdf |date=26 April 2012 }} St Helena Government, Department for International Development, January 2005, p. 17</ref> Fuel transfers between Rupert's Bay and the aerodrome, connected by a {{convert|14|km|4=0|adj=on}} haul road, were assumed to be by road tanker for 20 years, after which a capital allowance was made for enlargement of the bulk fuel storage and the installation of a fuel transfer pipeline.<ref name=\"sainthelenaaccess.com\"/>\n\nBasil Read sourced its own ship, a [[roll-on/roll-off]] vessel<ref name=\"engineeringnews.co.za\">[http://www.engineeringnews.co.za/article/basil-read-wins-r27bn-contract-to-build-st-helena-first-airport-2011-11-03 \"''Basil Read wins R2.7bn contract to build St Helena's first airport ''\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111207182100/http://www.engineeringnews.co.za/article/basil-read-wins-r27bn-contract-to-build-st-helena-first-airport-2011-11-03 |date=7 December 2011 }} Engineering News, 3 November 2011</ref> called ''NP Glory 4'' flying the Thai flag,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.marinetraffic.com/ais/shipdetails.aspx?MMSI=567321000 |title=N P GLORY 4 |author=MarineTraffic.com |publisher=MarineTraffic.com |work=database |access-date=7 November 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120719005230/http://www.marinetraffic.com/ais/shipdetails.aspx?MMSI=567321000 |archive-date=19 July 2012 |url-status=dead  }}</ref> which docked for the first time at St Helena on 11 July 2012 and subsequently provided regular supplies to the island, including cargo and personnel for the project.<ref name=\"Basil Read Team Arrives' 2011, p.4\"/><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.shbc.sh/L3_news_120711_np_glory_lands.html |title=NP GLORY 4 MAKES HISTORY, DOCKING AT ST HELENA |author=Sharon Henry |publisher=St The St Helena Broadcasting (Guarantee) Corporation Ltd. |work=news article |accessdate=7 November 2012}}</ref> The company also considered developing a temporary runway to enable the use of a [[Lockheed C-130 Hercules|C-130 Hercules]]-type aircraft to facilitate quicker access to the site within 18 months of the beginning of construction,<ref name=\"engineeringnews.co.za\"/> but this was not done.\n\nIn June 2013 the 100,000th truckload of fill went into Dry Gut, a gorge which had to be raised by almost {{convert|100|m|ft}} in order to create an embankment that would finally carry parts of the runway. This was equivalent to nearly 19% of the total of 8 million cubic metres required. Basil Read's calculations showed that a further 430,000 truckloads of material would be needed to complete the fill.\n\nIn September 2013, workers employed by Basil Read went on [[Strike action|strike]] in a dispute over working conditions and wages - it was the island's [[Trade unions in Saint Helena|first strike in half a century]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://en.mercopress.com/2013/09/05/labour-dispute-stops-the-construction-of-the-st-helena-airport-in-mid-atlantic|title=Labour dispute stops the construction of the St Helena airport in mid-Atlantic|website=MercoPress|language=en|access-date=16 October 2019}}</ref>\n\nBy the summer of 2015, the Dry Gut fill project was completed and the new runway built.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sainthelenaaccess.com/news/wp-content/uploads/2014/06/St-Helena-Airport-update-No-48.pdf|title=St Helena Airport update no 48|access-date=15 July 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140725013946/http://www.sainthelenaaccess.com/news/wp-content/uploads/2014/06/St-Helena-Airport-update-No-48.pdf|archive-date=25 July 2014|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n===Airport certification and opening===\n[[Avia Solutions Group]] was appointed to support the St Helena Government (SHG) and the UK [[Department for International Development]] (DFID) in reaching a contract with an air service provider to provide services to the island.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.flytosthelena.com/ |access-date=11 May 2014 |website=Fly to St Helena |title=homepage |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140512222650/http://www.flytosthelena.com/ |archive-date=12 May 2014 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nCalibration flights at the airport began in mid-September 2015. A [[Beechcraft King Air 200]], leased from TAB Charters in South Africa, landed on 15 September 2015 in order to perform tests of the airport navigation systems.<ref>{{cite news |url= http://independent.saint.fm/wp-content/uploads/2015/09/St-Helena-Independent-20150918.pdf |title= A Landing to be Remembered |page= 6 |work= Saint Helena Independent|date= 18 September 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Remote St Helena island welcomes first flight|url=https://www.theguardian.com/travel/2015/sep/17/first-plane-lands-st-helena-airport-atlantic-ocean-south-africa|access-date=13 December 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160429050906/http://www.theguardian.com/travel/2015/sep/17/first-plane-lands-st-helena-airport-atlantic-ocean-south-africa|archive-date=29 April 2016|url-status=live|newspaper=The Guardian|date=17 September 2015|last1=Weaver|first1=Emma}}</ref> UK-based Flight Calibration Services undertook the flights and flew from [[Lanseria International Airport]], in [[Johannesburg]], flying via [[Namibia]] and [[Angola]]. The aircraft was on site for approximately one week to undertake the calibration flights.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://en.mercopress.com/2015/09/12/first-landing-ever-in-st-helena-airport-scheduled-for-next-week-as-part-of-calibration-flights|title=First landing ever in St Helena airport scheduled for next week as part of calibration flights|access-date=14 September 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150915015421/http://en.mercopress.com/2015/09/12/first-landing-ever-in-st-helena-airport-scheduled-for-next-week-as-part-of-calibration-flights|archive-date=15 September 2015|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOpening was originally scheduled for February 2016 but that was postponed a number of times because of air traffic control related issues.<ref name=nov15delay>{{cite web|url=http://www.sainthelenaaccess.com/news/2015/11/06/airport-board-grants-additional-time-to-achieve-operational-readiness/|title=AIRPORT BOARD GRANTS ADDITIONAL TIME TO ACHIEVE OPERATIONAL READINESS : Saint Helena Airport Project|website=www.sainthelenaaccess.com|access-date=19 November 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160221140342/http://www.sainthelenaaccess.com/news/2015/11/06/airport-board-grants-additional-time-to-achieve-operational-readiness/|archive-date=21 February 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref> In November 2015, a delay of the opening from February to May 2016 was announced.<ref name=nov15delay/> This was needed \"in order to fine tune the operational readiness of the airport\".\n\nDue to uncertainties concerning weather conditions and, in particular the amount of turbulence on the approaches from [[Katabatic wind|fallwind]]s resulting from the elevated location and the surrounding bluffs, it was recommended that a charter aircraft should perform approaches to and departures from the intended runway.<ref>[http://www.sainthelenaaccess.com/application/documents/Feasibility/01_Main_Report_Final.pdf \"''St Helena Access Feasibility Study''\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120426081359/http://www.sainthelenaaccess.com/application/documents/Feasibility/01_Main_Report_Final.pdf |date=26 April 2012 }} St Helena Government, Department for International Development, January 2005, p. 117</ref> By April 2016 such flights had taken place, and they were not positive, causing a delay in traffic start.{{Citation needed|date=July 2017}}\n\n[[File:First Comair Boeing 737-800 flight to Saint Helena Airport (79).jpg|thumb|right|The [[Boeing 737-800]] implementation flight landing at the airport.]]\nThe first\u2014and {{As of|2017|July|lc=y}} only\u2014large (above 100 seats) passenger jet landed on 18 April 2016, a [[Boeing 737-800]] operated by [[Comair (South Africa)|Comair]]. It was an implementation flight to test the route, ground operations and handling, ahead of commencement of scheduled services.<ref>{{cite news |url= https://www.flightglobal.com/news/articles/pictures-comair-737-arrives-at-new-st-helena-airpor-424388/ |title= Pictures : Comair 737 arrives at new St Helena airport |publisher= [[flightglobal]] |date= 20 April 2016 |access-date= 20 April 2016 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20160420162943/https://www.flightglobal.com/news/articles/pictures-comair-737-arrives-at-new-st-helena-airpor-424388/ |archive-date= 20 April 2016 |url-status= live }}</ref> The landing was not straightforward, with the aircraft only successfully landing on its third approach (the first approach was a planned [[Go-around]], because of the lack of experience with this airport).<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/business/video/2016/sep/22/british-airways-flight-struggles-to-land-on-st-helena-runway-video |title=British Airways flight struggles to land on St Helena runway \u2013 video &#124; Business |work=The Guardian|date=22 September 2016 |access-date=25 July 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170728201449/https://www.theguardian.com/business/video/2016/sep/22/british-airways-flight-struggles-to-land-on-st-helena-runway-video |archive-date=28 July 2017 |url-status=live }}</ref> On 26 April 2016, a further delay to the opening, without a specified end date, was announced by the St. Helena Government because of concerns regarding [[wind shear]], after the problematic landing by the Comair 737-800 intended for regular flights.<ref name=\"AIRPORT OPENING CEREMONY POSTPONED\"/> Only southbound landings (runway 20) have wind shear problems, not northbound.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sainthelenaaccess.com/news/2016/06/06/maintaining-access-to-st-helena-ascension/|title=MAINTAINING ACCESS TO ST HELENA & ASCENSION : Saint Helena Airport Project|website=www.sainthelenaaccess.com|access-date=11 June 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170729001524/http://www.sainthelenaaccess.com/news/2016/06/06/maintaining-access-to-st-helena-ascension/|archive-date=29 July 2017|url-status=dead}}</ref> There is a need to define measurement methods for the wind shear in order to understand when landing can be done, and when to cancel flights. The late postponement caused extra cost, for example contracted employees and contracted airlines that cannot operate, hotels that were built, and also the need to extend the use of the RMS ''St Helena'', which originally was due to be retired after the airport opened.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.atlanticstarairlines.com/#!air-access-project/ca4p|title=The Air Access Project|publisher=Atlantic Star Airlines|access-date=12 January 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150106222237/http://www.atlanticstarairlines.com/#!air-access-project/ca4p|archive-date=6 January 2015|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://en.mercopress.com/2015/05/23/on-st-helena-day-21-may-2016-begins-air-link-of-the-island-with-south-africa |title=On St Helena Day, 21 May 2016, begins air link of the island with South Africa \u2014 MercoPress |publisher=En.mercopress.com |date=23 May 2015 |access-date=25 July 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150524135307/http://en.mercopress.com/2015/05/23/on-st-helena-day-21-may-2016-begins-air-link-of-the-island-with-south-africa |archive-date=24 May 2015 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=RMS Sailing Schedule extended until February 2018 - RMS St Helena|url=http://rms-st-helena.com/2016/12/15/rms-sailing-schedule-extended-february-2018/|website=RMS St Helena|access-date=15 October 2017|date=15 December 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171007021623/http://rms-st-helena.com/2016/12/15/rms-sailing-schedule-extended-february-2018/|archive-date=7 October 2017|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nFollowing an inspection in April 2016, on 10 May, UK-based Air Safety Support International (ASSI), a subsidiary company of the [[Civil Aviation Authority]] responsible for aviation safety in Overseas Territories, issued an Aerodrome Certificate to St Helena Airport. This safety certificate indicated that airport infrastructure, aviation security measures and air traffic control service complied with international aviation safety and security standards.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sainthelenaaccess.com/news/2016/05/11/st-helena-airport-certified/|title=ST HELENA AIRPORT CERTIFIED : Saint Helena Airport Project|website=www.sainthelenaaccess.com|access-date=15 May 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170729001815/http://www.sainthelenaaccess.com/news/2016/05/11/st-helena-airport-certified/|archive-date=29 July 2017|url-status=dead}}</ref> ASSI did not allow the airport to go into commercial operation, however, due to concerns over operational readiness of monitoring and clearing issues that include wind shear and turbulence.<ref>[http://traveller24.news24.com/News/Flights/st-helena-airport-step-closer-to-operating-as-final-rms-journey-on-the-horizon-20160512 St Helena Airport step closer to operating as final RMS journey on the horizon] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160513105819/http://traveller24.news24.com/News/Flights/st-helena-airport-step-closer-to-operating-as-final-rms-journey-on-the-horizon-20160512 |date=13 May 2016 }}, [[News24|Traveller24]], 12 May 2016</ref>\n\nThe airport opened in June 2016, but restrictions for large aircraft remained due to dangerous [[wind shear]]. The airport's advocates hope that it will bring growth to the island's economy through tourism, leading to financial self-sustainability and an end to UK budgetary aid.<ref name=\"Airport Approved\"/>\n\nA new safety certificate was delivered on 26 October 2016 by Air Safety Support International.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://en.mercopress.com/2016/10/27/milestone-for-st-helena-airport-certification-for-aviation-safety-and-security-standards|title=Milestone for St Helena Airport: certification for aviation safety and security standards|website=MercoPress|access-date=27 October 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161027192407/http://en.mercopress.com/2016/10/27/milestone-for-st-helena-airport-certification-for-aviation-safety-and-security-standards|archive-date=27 October 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> After the bankruptcy of the company [[Basil Read]] which built and operated the airport, the Saint Helena government owned company took over the operations, for which it got a new safety certificate on 5 October 2018.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://sthelenaairport.com/news/st-helena-airport-re-opens-5-october-2018/ |title=St Helena Airport re-opens - 5 October 2018 |access-date=9 October 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181009172028/http://sthelenaairport.com/news/st-helena-airport-re-opens-5-october-2018/ |archive-date=9 October 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n===Early air traffic history===\nSince the airport opened, {{As of|2017|4|alt=through to early April 2017}}, 32 private aircraft have landed at the airport.  These flights were mostly for either business passengers or medical evacuation purposes.  The aircraft involved were smaller and lighter than the Boeing 737 and usually landed in the opposite direction on the runway from that taken by the 737-800 implementation flight in the southbound direction.  The opposite, northbound, direction has an approach which is generally less turbulent but can only be used by lighter aircraft.<ref name=Newsweek2017>{{cite news |last=Mahr |first=Krista |url=http://www.newsweek.com/st-helena-windy-airport-tourists-one-worlds-most-remote-islands-589707 |title=How a Windy Airport Could Ruin Plans to Bring Tourists to One of the World's Most Remote Islands |publisher=Newsweek.com |date=25 April 2017 |access-date=25 July 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170501042246/http://www.newsweek.com/st-helena-windy-airport-tourists-one-worlds-most-remote-islands-589707 |archive-date=1 May 2017 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nThe first helicopter to use the airport was an [[AgustaWestland AW159 Wildcat|AgustaWestland Wildcat HMA.2]] of 201 Flight [[825 Naval Air Squadron]] attached to the [[Type 23 frigate]] {{HMS|Lancaster|F229|6}} on 14 October 2015.<ref name=\"WL\">{{cite web|url=http://www.janes.com/article/54622/wildcat-loose-dsei15d4|title=Wildcat loose|publisher=Janes|accessdate=23 October 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.westerngazette.co.uk/Wildcat-maritime-attack-helicopter-takes-seas/story-26238365-detail/story.html|title=Wildcat maritime attack helicopter takes to the seas|work=Western Gazette|access-date=23 October 2015|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150904083618/http://www.westerngazette.co.uk/Wildcat-maritime-attack-helicopter-takes-seas/story-26238365-detail/story.html|archive-date=4 September 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.royalnavy.mod.uk/news-and-latest-activity/news/2015/october/23/151023-wildcat-first-helicopter-at-st-helena-airport|title=Wildcat becomes first helicopter to land at St Helena Airport|publisher=Royal Navy|access-date=23 October 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151024234832/http://www.royalnavy.mod.uk/news-and-latest-activity/news/2015/october/23/151023-wildcat-first-helicopter-at-st-helena-airport|archive-date=24 October 2015|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title = Wildcat makes history on St Helena|url = https://navynews.co.uk/archive/news/item/13485|website = navynews.co.uk|access-date = 15 December 2015|archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20151222081533/https://navynews.co.uk/archive/news/item/13485|archive-date = 22 December 2015|url-status = live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.sainthelena.gov.sh/first-ever-rotary-wing-aircraft-lands-at-st-helena-airport/ |title=Anonymous, \"FIRST EVER ROTARY-WING AIRCRAFT LANDS AT ST HELENA AIRPORT,\" sainthelena.gov.sh, October 15, 2015. |access-date=15 October 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171016014723/http://www.sainthelena.gov.sh/first-ever-rotary-wing-aircraft-lands-at-st-helena-airport/ |archive-date=16 October 2017 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nAn important reason to build the airport was availability for medical emergency evacuation. On 3 June 2016 the first ambulance flight took place, for a baby and his mother.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sainthelenaaccess.com/news/2016/06/07/first-ever-medevac-flight-critically-ill-saint-transferred-to-cape-town/|title=FIRST EVER MEDEVAC FLIGHT \u2013 CRITICALLY ILL SAINT TRANSFERRED TO CAPE TOWN : Saint Helena Airport Project|website=www.sainthelenaaccess.com|access-date=11 June 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160917192453/http://www.sainthelenaaccess.com/news/2016/06/07/first-ever-medevac-flight-critically-ill-saint-transferred-to-cape-town/|archive-date=17 September 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nThere are no aircraft dedicated to calibration flights, but occasionally such flights have taken place. On Friday 21 October 2016, an [[Avro RJ100]] jet airliner sponsored by [[Atlantic Star Airlines]] landed on St Helena Airport, with 13 non-commercial passengers on board, as part of a delivery to Chile. Both pilots were from the [[Faroe Islands]] and had experience from there with landing in windy conditions.<ref name=\"THE MONTSERRAT REPORTER NEWSPAPER\">[https://www.themontserratreporter.com/is-atlantic-star-the-solution-to-st-helena-airport-wind-shear/ Is Atlantic Star The Solution To St Helena Airport Wind Shear?'] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161024030539/https://www.themontserratreporter.com/is-atlantic-star-the-solution-to-st-helena-airport-wind-shear/ |date=24 October 2016 }} 22 October 2016.</ref> An [[Embraer E-Jet family|Embraer ERJ-190-100]] operated by Embraer Aviation flew from Brazil and made a number of landings and starts on St Helena on 30 November and 1 December 2016.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sainthelenaaccess.com/news/2016/11/28/embraer-trial-flight-confirmed-large-passenger-aircraft-to-land-on-tuesday/|title=EMBRAER TRIAL FLIGHT CONFIRMED \u2013 LARGE PASSENGER AIRCRAFT TO LAND ON TUESDAY : Saint Helena Airport Project|website=www.sainthelenaaccess.com|access-date=3 December 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161220034335/http://www.sainthelenaaccess.com/news/2016/11/28/embraer-trial-flight-confirmed-large-passenger-aircraft-to-land-on-tuesday/|archive-date=20 December 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=kypMTPJ-KKU|title=Long landing of Embraer E190 at St Helena Airport on 1st Dec 2016|last=Bob St Helena|date=3 December 2016|via=YouTube|access-date=3 December 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161220065619/https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=kypMTPJ-KKU|archive-date=20 December 2016|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn 18 December 2016 a [[Royal Air Force]] [[C-130J Hercules]] landed at St Helena, the first fixed-wing military aircraft to land on the island.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://whatthesaintsdidnext.com/2016/12/18/raf-c-130-hercules-first-military-flight-lands-at-st-helena-airport/ |title=C130 Hercules at St Helena Airport: First Military Flight Landing |publisher=Whatthesaintsdidnext.com |date=18 December 2016 |accessdate=25 July 2017}}</ref> A [[South African Air Force]] C-130 visited the airport twice in July 2017.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.defenceweb.co.za/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=48705 |title=SAAF C-130BZ lands at St Helena, now back in SA |publisher=DefenceWeb.co.za |date=27 July 2017 |access-date=28 July 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170728202942/http://www.defenceweb.co.za/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=48705 |archive-date=28 July 2017 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n===Establishing commercial air service===\nPrior to the opening of the airport, it was decided that St Helena would have an [[Open skies|open skies policy]]; this allows any airline operator who meets all the required standards to fly in and out of St Helena.<ref name=\"TSHI20131018b\">{{cite news | title = Atlantic Star \u2013 The Only Plane in the St Helena Sky | page = 9 | newspaper = The St Helena Independent | location = Jamestown | volume = 8 | author = Vince Thompson | issue = 44 | date = 18 October 2013 | url = http://www.saint.fm/the-independent/ | access-date = 20 March 2015 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20171206201911/http://www.saint.fm/the-independent/ | archive-date = 6 December 2017 | url-status = live }}</ref> Projections for commercial flight costs were also drawn up and the St Helena Government expected that a return economy flight from St Helena to South Africa would cost around \u00a3600. Assuming that an off-peak economy seat from South Africa to the UK would be available for approximately \u00a3700, return tickets for flights via South Africa to the UK would take the total price to around \u00a31,300.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.sainthelenaaccess.com/faqs/ |title=Frequently Asked Questions |author=Air Access Office |website=St Helena Airport Project |publisher=St Helena Government |access-date=12 January 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131127035157/http://sainthelenaaccess.com/faqs/ |archive-date=27 November 2013 |url-status=dead  }}</ref>\n\nDue to the runway length and the distance to [[South Africa]] (3,700&nbsp;km to Johannesburg), a [[Boeing 737-76N|Boeing 737-700]] flying to [[Johannesburg]] serving St Helena would not be able to use its full seat and cargo capacity. Only flights to and from Namibian and Angolan destinations would allow using a Boeing 737-700 near its full load capacity. This was under the condition that both directions of the runway were available so tailwind landings could be avoided. The other planned destination, [[London]], requires a fuel stop in [[Gambia]], at almost the same distance as Johannesburg.  However, if [[RAF Ascension Island|Wideawake Airfield]] on [[Ascension Island]] was open for commercial non-military flights, it could be listed as an alternate aerodrome; as it is only 1,300&nbsp;km from St Helena this would mean that the load capacity of an inbound Boeing 737-700 could be increased as smaller fuel reserves would be required, since the alternate aerodrome could be used in case of problems at St. Helena.{{citation needed|date=April 2017}}\n\nIt is believed{{by whom|date=May 2017}} that reductions in ticket prices could be obtained by using spare payload capacity on flights to and from St Helena to carry air freight (e.g., agricultural products, coffee, fish).<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.sainthelenaaccess.com/application/documents/Feasibility/03_Appendices_Final_Vol_2_v2.pdf |title=St Helena Access Feasibility Study |page=3 |publisher=WS Atkins plc |author=WS Atkins plc |date=October 2004 |access-date=14 January 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150924093623/http://www.sainthelenaaccess.com/application/documents/Feasibility/03_Appendices_Final_Vol_2_v2.pdf |archive-date=24 September 2015 |url-status=dead  }}</ref> At 70% [[passenger load factor]] a B737-800 operating, on an average day, into St Helena would have a spare payload capacity of some {{convert|4000|kg}}. The extra income possible per in-bound flight from cargo could be as high as the income equivalent of 19 passengers, giving an effective load factor of 88% and could reduce ticket prices.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.sainthelenaaccess.com/application/documents/Feasibility/03_Appendices_Final_Vol_2_v2.pdf |title=St Helena Access Feasibility Study |page=4 |publisher=WS Atkins plc |author=WS Atkins plc |date=October 2004 |access-date=14 January 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150924093623/http://www.sainthelenaaccess.com/application/documents/Feasibility/03_Appendices_Final_Vol_2_v2.pdf |archive-date=24 September 2015 |url-status=dead  }}</ref>\n\nOn 16 March 2015 it was announced that SHG and DFID had appointed [[Comair (South Africa)|Comair Limited]] as the preferred bidder for the provision of air services to St Helena.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sainthelena.gov.sh/air-services-to-st-helena-2/|title=AIR SERVICES TO ST HELENA|date=16 March 2015|access-date=19 March 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150320215723/http://www.sainthelena.gov.sh/air-services-to-st-helena-2/|archive-date=20 March 2015|url-status=live}}</ref> Comair was proposing a weekly flight between [[Johannesburg Airport]] and St Helena using a [[Boeing 737-800]] aircraft, which has a flight time from Johannesburg to St Helena of about four and a half hours. Reaction to the Comair announcement on St Helena was largely negative,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.saint.fm/the-independent/|title=The St Helena Independent - Saint FM|access-date=20 March 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171206201911/http://www.saint.fm/the-independent/|archive-date=6 December 2017|url-status=live|date=13 August 2014}}</ref> with stories of luggage loss and crime in Johannesburg, and the fact that many of St Helena's residents have personal links with Cape Town.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://sartma.com/art_12365.html|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150412175008/http://sartma.com/art_12365.html|url-status=dead|archive-date=12 April 2015|title=Falkland Islands Current News Articles by SARTMA.com|date=12 April 2015}}</ref>\n\nOn 9 October 2015, Governor Mark Capes indicated that once a month there would be a flight from St Helena to Ascension Island provided by Comair.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.sainthelena.gov.sh/ascension-air-service-to-and-from-st-helena/ |title=ASCENSION AIR SERVICE TO AND FROM ST HELENA |publisher=St Helena Government |date=9 October 2015 |access-date=21 October 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151010075426/http://www.sainthelena.gov.sh/ascension-air-service-to-and-from-st-helena/ |archive-date=10 October 2015 |url-status=live }}</ref> The [[Ascension Island]] Government also announced a connection between the two islands. The connection was to be flown by [[Comair (South Africa)|Comair]] using a Boeing 737-800. The flight would have taken about two hours to [[RAF Ascension Island|Wideawake Airfield]]. Comair's air services between St Helena Airport and [[OR Tambo International Airport]] in Johannesburg were scheduled to commence in late May 2016, to coincide with the official opening of the airport on 21 May 2016. These dates were postponed because of the problems with [[wind shear]]; however, Comair did operate a few test flights which concluded in the windshear risk, mainly for aircraft of that size and larger.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.sainthelenaaccess.com/news/2015/10/09/ascension-air-service-to-and-from-st-helena/ |title=ASCENSION AIR SERVICE TO AND FROM ST HELENA : Saint Helena Airport Project |publisher=Sainthelenaaccess.com |date=9 October 2015 |access-date=25 July 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151029201909/http://www.sainthelenaaccess.com/news/2015/10/09/ascension-air-service-to-and-from-st-helena/ |archive-date=29 October 2015 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n[[Atlantic Star Airlines]] (operated by [[TUI Airlines Netherlands]]) had announced an intention to operate charter flights from [[Gatwick Airport|London-Gatwick]] via [[Banjul International Airport|Gambia]] (possibly starting May 2016)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.atlanticstarairlines.com/#!Atlantic-Star-Airlines-shares-news-of-delay-to-opening-date-of-StHelena-Airport/c10mv/563e5cbf0cf275e9c59c7d6e|title=Best value flights to St.Helena - Atlantic Star Airlines|website=Best value flights to St.Helena - Atlantic Star Airlines|access-date=12 January 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150106222237/http://www.atlanticstarairlines.com/#!Atlantic-Star-Airlines-shares-news-of-delay-to-opening-date-of-StHelena-Airport/c10mv/563e5cbf0cf275e9c59c7d6e|archive-date=6 January 2015|url-status=live}}</ref> using a [[Boeing 737-800]], an aircraft requiring a fairly long runway. This leaves [[Lubango Airport]] in [[Angola]], at a distance of {{convert|1300|mi|km}} as the next best diversion option for which every inbound aircraft must carry enough fuel reserve, limiting its load capacity.\n\nIn response to the wind shear problems, in June 2016 the Governor, [[Lisa Phillips (civil servant)|Lisa Phillips]], noted that restricting flight operations to runway 02, that is northbound landings and southbound starts on St Helena's single operating surface, might be a suitable interim solution.  While runway 02 does not suffer from a significant wind shear problem, restricting landings to one direction would prevent large aircraft from calling at St Helena.  Only permitting landings in one direction would mean that aircraft must to be able to land in tailwind.  Consequently, large aircraft, like the 737-800, could not be used because, in a tailwind, they would need a longer runway than St Helena provides.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sainthelenaaccess.com/news/2016/06/15/st-helena-airport-statement-from-governor-lisa-phillips/|title=ST HELENA AIRPORT \u2013 STATEMENT FROM GOVERNOR LISA PHILLIPS : Saint Helena Airport Project|website=www.sainthelenaaccess.com|access-date=22 June 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160701002815/http://www.sainthelenaaccess.com/news/2016/06/15/st-helena-airport-statement-from-governor-lisa-phillips/|archive-date=1 July 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref> If runway 20 is used, it will have severe wind restrictions.\n\nA debate about the project was held by the [[House of Lords]] in London on 17 October 2016. When asked by [[George Foulkes, Baron Foulkes of Cumnock|Lord Foulkes]] when the government expected commercial flights would start at the airport, the Minister of State, Department for International Development [[Michael Bates, Baron Bates|Lord Bates]] said, \"scheduled commercial flights will begin when the conditions are considered safe to do so and the St Helena Government are able to contract an airline with the right aircraft and regulatory approval.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.atlanticstarairlines.com/single-post/2016/10/17/Question-raised-today-in-the-House-of-Lords|title=Best value flights to St.Helena - Atlantic Star Airlines|website=Best value flights to St.Helena - Atlantic Star Airlines|access-date=27 October 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161027194421/http://www.atlanticstarairlines.com/single-post/2016/10/17/Question-raised-today-in-the-House-of-Lords|archive-date=27 October 2016|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn December 2016, the Saint Helena government issued a tender for an airline to establish a scheduled commercial service, using the less turbulent northbound landing direction only.  Atlantic Star Airlines has entered a bid on a proposed plan to base two aircraft at Saint Helena.  They would carry up to 60 passengers on round-trip flights from Saint Helena to the international airport in [[Accra#Aviation|Accra]], the capital of Ghana.<ref name=Newsweek2017/> On 5 February 2017 there was a deadline for airlines to submit application bids for the provision of air services to St Helena under the new requirements, and there were a number of bids.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sainthelena.gov.sh/air-services-to-st-helena/|title=AIR SERVICES TO ST HELENA|date=6 February 2017|access-date=15 May 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170729002529/http://www.sainthelena.gov.sh/air-services-to-st-helena/|archive-date=29 July 2017|url-status=live}}</ref>\n[[File:Airlink BAe 146-200 Volpati.jpg|thumb|An Airlink [[Avro RJ85]] flew the first charter passengers to and from St. Helena on 3 May 2017]]\nOn 3 May 2017, the first commercial charter flight with paying passengers took place. [[SA Airlink]] operated the flight from Cape Town, using an [[Avro RJ85]] aircraft with 60 passengers on board. It refueled in [[Yuri Gagarin Airport|Mo\u00e7\u00e2medes (Angola)]] when going to St Helena and in [[Hosea Kutako International Airport|Windhoek]] when going to Cape Town.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sainthelena.gov.sh/historic-arrival-of-charter-flight/|title=HISTORIC ARRIVAL OF CHARTER FLIGHT|date=3 May 2017|access-date=3 May 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170504171800/http://www.sainthelena.gov.sh/historic-arrival-of-charter-flight/|archive-date=4 May 2017|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ch-aviation.com/portal/news/55705-st-helena-sees-maiden-commercial-pax-flight|title=St. Helena sees maiden commercial pax flight|access-date=10 June 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170504124921/https://www.ch-aviation.com/portal/news/55705-st-helena-sees-maiden-commercial-pax-flight|archive-date=4 May 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> Technical problems with RMS ''St Helena'' meant that the island was isolated for at least two months, so the flight was needed.<ref>{{cite news |author=Oliver Smith |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/travel/news/st-helena-airport-first-flight-finally-lands/ |title=First flight finally lands at world's most 'useless' airport |work=Telegraph|date=8 May 2017 |access-date=25 July 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180515175500/https://www.telegraph.co.uk/travel/news/st-helena-airport-first-flight-finally-lands/ |archive-date=15 May 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nOn 9 June 2017 [[Airlink]] won the bid to operate scheduled flights to St Helena Airport.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.moneyweb.co.za/news-fast-news/sa-airlink-chosen-as-bidder-for-commercial-air-services-to-st-helena/|title=SA Airlink wins bid for commercial air services to St Helena|date=9 June 2017|access-date=10 June 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170609151204/https://www.moneyweb.co.za/news-fast-news/sa-airlink-chosen-as-bidder-for-commercial-air-services-to-st-helena/|archive-date=9 June 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> On 22 July 2017 it was announced the airline would operate weekly flights to [[Johannesburg]] via [[Hosea Kutako International Airport|Windhoek]] in [[Namibia]], with a monthly link to [[Ascension Island]]. The flights will be on [[Embraer E190]] aircraft filling a maximum of only 76 of the 99 seats due to runway limitations related to the [[wind shear]] issues.<ref name=\"sainthelena1\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.sainthelena.gov.sh/wp-content/uploads/2017/07/Air-Services-to-St-Helena-QandAs-21-July-2017.pdf |title=Archived copy |access-date=22 July 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170729002201/http://www.sainthelena.gov.sh/wp-content/uploads/2017/07/Air-Services-to-St-Helena-QandAs-21-July-2017.pdf |archive-date=29 July 2017 |url-status=dead  }}</ref><ref name=\":1\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/travel/news-and-advice/st-helena-flights-most-useless-airport-south-atlantic-johannesburg-airlink-windshear-a7858581.html|title=The world's 'most useless airport' is finally getting its first scheduled flight|date=25 July 2017|work=The Independent|access-date=27 July 2017|language=en-GB|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171122204305/http://www.independent.co.uk/travel/news-and-advice/st-helena-flights-most-useless-airport-south-atlantic-johannesburg-airlink-windshear-a7858581.html|archive-date=22 November 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> [[Airlink]] conducted a successful proving flight on 23 August 2017<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.sainthelena.gov.sh/airlink-completes-successful-proving-flight-to-st-helena/|title=AIRLINK COMPLETES SUCCESSFUL PROVING FLIGHT TO ST HELENA|date=22 August 2017|work=St Helena|access-date=14 October 2017|language=en-US|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171014133826/http://www.sainthelena.gov.sh/airlink-completes-successful-proving-flight-to-st-helena/|archive-date=14 October 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> and commenced passenger flights on 14 October 2017.<ref name=\":0\" /> The first scheduled flight landed on 14 October 2017 around 14:00 UTC without any problems, although it was slightly delayed.  The flight used the southbound direction, the one with wind shear problems, but the wind was fairly calm.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.facebook.com/photo.php?fbid=10154779647856470&set=pcb.852690421571482&type=3&theater&ifg=1|title=Tina Wagner|website=www.facebook.com}}</ref> Airlink was after some time denied letting passengers embark and disembark in Windhoek, because Airlink was not given [[Freedoms of the air#Fifth freedom|right to carry passengers between Namibia and foreign countries]]. From April 2019 Airlink refuels in [[Walvis Bay Airport|Walvis Bay]] instead, giving right to have 98 passengers because of shorter distance, having in mind that no connections are allowed in Namibia anyway.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.traveller24.com/Flights/11-seats-added-to-airlink-flight-between-jozi-and-st-helena-island-heres-why-20190306 |title=11 seats added to Airlink flight between Jozi and St Helena Island - here's why |access-date=6 March 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190306235253/https://www.traveller24.com/Flights/11-seats-added-to-airlink-flight-between-jozi-and-st-helena-island-heres-why-20190306 |archive-date=6 March 2019 |url-status=live |date=6 March 2019 }}</ref> The flights still (2019) stop in Windhoek or Walvis Bay for refuel westbound, but fly nonstop to Johannesburg if there is not too much upwind.<ref name=traffic-rights-scuttle>{{Cite web |url=https://www.ch-aviation.com/portal/news/64402-traffic-rights-scuttle-airlinks-cape-town-st-helena-plans |title=Traffic rights scuttle Airlink's Cape Town-St Helena plans |access-date=13 February 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180214142135/https://www.ch-aviation.com/portal/news/64402-traffic-rights-scuttle-airlinks-cape-town-st-helena-plans |archive-date=14 February 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nOn Saturday 18 November 2017 [[Airlink]] started a monthly charter operation to [[RAF Ascension Island|Ascension Island]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.ascension-island.gov.ac/government/travel-shipping/flights/airlink/|title=Airlink|date=5 October 2017|work=Ascension Island Government|access-date=28 January 2018|language=en-GB|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171014183603/http://www.ascension-island.gov.ac/government/travel-shipping/flights/airlink/|archive-date=14 October 2017|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nAfter half a year of operation it was found that the regularity was better than expected with only one day of flights delayed until another day, and that ticket demand was higher than expected.<ref>{{Cite web | url=https://www.airlineratings.com/news/remote-st-helena-airport-shrugs-off-worlds-useless-tag/ | title=Remote St Helena airport shrugs off 'world's most useless' tag| date=27 April 2018}}</ref> The government announced in May 2018 that a second weekly flight will be performed during the southern summer season of December 2018 to April 2019, as well as two more flights to Ascension during the Christmas/New year period.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.sainthelena.gov.sh/additional-flights-to-st-helena-and-ascension/ |title=ADDITIONAL FLIGHTS TO ST HELENA AND ASCENSION |access-date=6 May 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180507003455/http://www.sainthelena.gov.sh/additional-flights-to-st-helena-and-ascension/ |archive-date=7 May 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref> During December 2019 to February 2020 flights went to and from Cape Town, the traditional link to Saint Helena during the boat era.<ref>[https://edition.cnn.com/travel/article/saint-helena-atlantic-us-flights/index.html New flights open up Napoleon's hidden Atlantic island to international visitors]</ref>\n\nThe southern autumn and winter means higher challenges with low clouds and stormy weather. The flights planned for 14 July 2018 were delayed a full week because of weather,<ref>[http://www.sainthelena.gov.sh/airlink-flight-postponed/ AIRLINK FLIGHT POSTPONED](sainthelena.gov.sh) or {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180717212708/http://www.sainthelena.gov.sh/airlink-flight-postponed/ |date=17 July 2018 }} (webcache.googleusercontent.com)</ref> and the schedule of August 2018 was also heavily disrupted.\n\nBeginning March 2020, only residents, citizens or other permitted people were allowed to enter the island, due to the [[COVID-19]] pandemic, and all had to stay isolated for two weeks.<ref>[http://sthelenaairport.com/news/new-restrictions-entry-air-st-helena-17-march-2020/ New restrictions on entry by air to St Helena - 17 March 2020]</ref> This and restrictions in South Africa caused cancellation of all flights to Saint Helena and Ascension from 25 March to at least 18 April.<ref>https://simpleflying.com/st-helena-cut-off/?fbclid=IwAR2MpfwuAUdwQqtwxAPuuRR6DYQnhEERKrrBpkc1LCyd3TAZSfnEl9_oBuo St Helena Cut Off From The World As Flights Grounded]</ref> The M/V Helena freight ship still goes and [[Medical evacuation|medical air evacuation]] is also possible.\n\n==Airlines and destinations==\n{{Airport-dest-list\n|[[Airlink]] | [[O. R. Tambo International Airport|Johannesburg\u2013O.R. Tambo]]<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.routesonline.com/news/38/airlineroute/278625/sa-airlink-plans-st-helena-service-increase-in-nw18/ |title=SA Airlink plans St. Helena service increase in NW18 |access-date=15 May 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180515191441/https://www.routesonline.com/news/38/airlineroute/278625/sa-airlink-plans-st-helena-service-increase-in-nw18/ |archive-date=15 May 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref><br/>'''Seasonal:''' [[Cape Town International Airport|Cape Town]]<ref>https://edition.cnn.com/travel/article/saint-helena-atlantic-us-flights/index.html</ref> <br/>'''Charter:''' [[RAF Ascension Island|Ascension Island]]<ref name=\"ascension-island.gov.ac\">{{cite web|title=Airlink-Ascension Island Government|url=http://www.ascension-island.gov.ac/government/travel-shipping/flights/airlink/|website=Ascension Island Government|access-date=15 October 2017|date=5 October 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171014183603/http://www.ascension-island.gov.ac/government/travel-shipping/flights/airlink/|archive-date=14 October 2017|url-status=live}}</ref>\n}}\n\n==Aerodrome characteristics, equipment and facilities==\n{{Location mark\n| type = thumb\n| image = Saint Helena Airport location.svg\n | caption =Location of the airport on St Helena\n| width=240\n| label=\n| label-size=90\n| background = #DDDD44\n| position=bottom\n| y%  = 50.00\n| x% = 80\n| mark=Cercle rouge 50%.svg\n| mark_width=40\n| float=right\n}}\nThe airport has been built on [[Prosperous Bay Plain]], on the east side of Saint Helena, entailing a concrete runway length of {{convert|1950|m|ft|0}}<ref name=\"atnsDL\">{{cite web|url=http://www.atns.com/downloads/FHSH%20AD%202-13.pdf|title=FHSH 2-15|access-date=13 January 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170116160048/http://www.atns.com/downloads/FHSH%20AD%202-13.pdf|archive-date=16 January 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> with taxiway and apron, an approximately {{convert|8|e6m3|abbr=off|adj=on}} rockfill embankment through which a {{convert|750|m|ft|adj=on}} long reinforced concrete culvert was proposed but contractor Basil Read got approval to use an open channel instead. This was approved by the St Helena Government, together with an airport terminal building of {{convert|3500|m2}} and support infrastructure, air traffic control and safety, bulk fuel installation for {{convert|6|e6l|e6impgal+e6usgal|abbr=off|spell=in}} of diesel and aviation fuel, a {{convert|14|km|mi|0|adj=on}} airport access road from Rupert's Bay to the airport, and all related logistics.<ref name=\"basilread.co.za\">[http://www.basilread.co.za/basil-read-awarded-contract-to-construct-airpor-on-st-helena-island/ \"''Basil Read awarded contract to construct airport on St Helena Island''\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120117034017/http://www.basilread.co.za/basil-read-awarded-contract-to-construct-airpor-on-st-helena-island/ |date=17 January 2012 }} Basil Read company website, 4 November 2011, retrieved 2011-DEC-24</ref> The airport has a LDA (landing distance available) of {{convert|1535|m|ft|0}} for the northbound runway direction (02) and {{convert|1550|m|ft|0}} for the wind shear-affected southbound runway direction (20).<ref name=\"atnsDL\"/>\n\n===Aircraft compatibility===\nThe airport by design can accommodate up to two<ref>[http://www.sainthelenaaccess.com/application/documents/Application-Drawings/5048976-CI-01-1001.pdf \"''Application Drawings, CI-01-1001 \u2013 General Runway Layout''\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120426081338/http://www.sainthelenaaccess.com/application/documents/Application-Drawings/5048976-CI-01-1001.pdf |date=26 April 2012 }} Airport Development Application, 2004</ref> twin-engined passenger aircraft up to the size of the [[Airbus A319]], [[Boeing 737]], and the [[Boeing 757-200]]. Following a decision to build a shorter runway of 1,550 metres the planned use of [[Boeing 737-824|Boeing 737-800]] aircraft had been ruled out. Instead the airport was to be designed to receive [[Boeing 737-76N|Boeing 737-700]] aircraft.<ref>{{cite news | last = Olsson | first = Mikael | title = Editorial | page = 2 | newspaper = The St Helena Independent | location = Jamestown | volume = VII | issue = 10 | date = 20 January 2012 | url = http://www.independent.co.sh/20120120.pdf | access-date = 21 January 2012 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20120504074246/http://www.independent.co.sh/20120120.pdf | archive-date = 4 May 2012 | url-status = dead | df = dmy-all }}</ref> However, on 17 July 2012, the St Helena Government and Basil Read agreed to a change to the runway design, which including widening the embankment over an additional {{convert|40|m|ft}} at the southern end, paving an additional {{convert|100|m|ft}} of the runway with concrete, providing larger turning circles at the runway ends, and increasing the size of the [[Airport apron|apron]].<ref name=\"SHG_23072012\">{{cite web |url=http://www.sainthelenaaccess.com/news/wp-content/uploads/2012/08/St-Helena-Airport-update-No13.pdf |title=FIRST PROJECT VARIATION ORDER SIGNED \u2013 Additional Runway Works to Allow for Future Expansion |publisher=St Helena Government Access Office |date=23 July 2012 |work=press release |issue=13 |access-date=7 August 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130418061504/http://www.sainthelenaaccess.com/news/wp-content/uploads/2012/08/St-Helena-Airport-update-No13.pdf |archive-date=18 April 2013 |url-status=dead  }}</ref> As a result of [[wind shear]] issues discovered during commissioning of the airport, and the resulting need to land with a [[tailwind]], even further restrictions on the aircraft have been shown to be needed.  [[Airlink]] decided to use a Brazilian [[Embraer E190]] which is more compatible than larger aircraft with tailwind landings. However it still cannot use the full seat and cargo capacity.<ref name=\"sainthelena1\" /><ref name=\":1\" />\n\nIn contrast to the 2011 reference design for the airport it would now have a full {{convert|240|m|ft|adj=on}} [[Runway safety area|runway end safety area]] (RESA) at the southern end of the runway instead of the planned [[Engineered materials arrestor system|engineered materials arresting system]] (EMAS). The intention was to add an EMAS designed for Boeing 737-800 later butting onto the southern end of the paved runway to increase the declarable [[Landing Distance Available|landing distance available]] (LDA) to {{convert|1650|m|ft}},<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.sainthelenaaccess.com/news/wp-content/uploads/2012/08/St-Helena-Airport-update-No-13.pdf |title=St Helena Airport Update |issue=13 |date=12 July 2012 |author=St Helena Government |access-date=18 June 2012 |work=press release |publisher=St Helena Government |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140104204019/http://www.sainthelenaaccess.com/news/wp-content/uploads/2012/08/St-Helena-Airport-update-No-13.pdf |archive-date=4 January 2014 |url-status=dead  }}</ref> to allow the operation of larger aircraft such as the [[Boeing 737-824|Boeing 737-800]] and [[Airbus A320 family|Airbus A320]].<ref name=\"SHG_23072012\"/><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.sainthelena.gov.sh/news.php/624/additional-runway-works-to-allow-for-future-expansion |archive-url=https://archive.is/20121224214715/http://www.sainthelena.gov.sh/news.php/624/additional-runway-works-to-allow-for-future-expansion |url-status=dead |archive-date=24 December 2012 |title=Additional runway works to allow for future expansion |author=St Helena Government |date=23 July 2012 |work=press release |publisher=St Helena Government |access-date=24 July 2012 }}</ref>\n\nThe additional earthworks and concrete increased duration of construction by 12 weeks so works were expected to be completed by 25 February 2016.<ref name=\"SHG_23072012\"/> Extending the embankment once the airport was operational would have involved prohibitive costs as heavy equipment would have needed to be brought back to the island and huge quantities of rock from another site to be moved, while material excavated from Prosperous Bay Plain was used to fill Dry Gut.<ref name=\"SHG_23072012\"/>\n\nIn June 2013 the St Helena government announced it was again assessing changes to the design of the runway to cater for operations of a wider range of aircraft, in particular the [[Lockheed C-130 Hercules]] and the [[Boeing 757|Boeing 757-200]], the latter enabling direct flights to Europe, crucial for the island's tourism plans.<ref>{{cite news | last = Pipe | first = Simon | title = Doubt over eco-resort as Shelco seeks direct flights to Europe | newspaper = St Helena Online | location = Jamestown | date = 8 November 2012 | url = http://sthelenaonline.org/2012/11/08/doubt-over-eco-resort-as-shelco-seeks-direct-flights-to-europe/ | url-status = dead | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20131029193329/http://sthelenaonline.org/2012/11/08/doubt-over-eco-resort-as-shelco-seeks-direct-flights-to-europe/ | archive-date = 29 October 2013 | df = dmy-all }}</ref><ref name=\"SHO20130614\">{{cite news | last = Pipe | first = Simon | title = No flights from London? Woah, I'm going to Barbados\u2026 | newspaper = St Helena Online | location = Jamestown | date = 14 June 2013 | url = http://sthelenaonline.org/2013/06/14/no-flights-from-london-woah-im-going-to-barbados// | url-status = dead | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20131030032342/http://sthelenaonline.org/2013/06/14/no-flights-from-london-woah-im-going-to-barbados/ | archive-date = 30 October 2013 | df = dmy-all }}</ref> These are Code D aircraft requiring the addition of shoulders along both sides of the runway, a wider taxiway and apron, and a higher fire fighting capacity (ICAO rescue fire fighting service category 7).<ref name=\"SHG20130613\">{{cite news | title = Design Changes | page = 2 | newspaper = St Helena Airport Update | location = Jamestown | issue = 31 | date = 13 June 2013 | url = http://www.brshap.co.za/press/Issues/St%20Helena%20Airport%20update%20-%20No%2031.pdf | access-date = 17 June 2013 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20140104210812/http://www.brshap.co.za/press/Issues/St%20Helena%20Airport%20update%20-%20No%2031.pdf | archive-date = 4 January 2014 | url-status = live }}</ref>\n\nIn October 2013 a formal agreement was signed for the proposed design changes.<ref name=\"SHI20131206\">{{cite news | last = Olsson | first = Mikael | title = Editorial | page = 3 | newspaper = The St Helena Independent | location = Jamestown | volume = IX | issue = 1 | date = 6 December 2013 | url = http://www.saint.fm/wp-content/uploads/2013/12/20131206.pdf }}{{dead link|date=April 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> These enhancements will also make it possible for the [[Lockheed C-130 Hercules]] to operate to and from St Helena, though the runway is unlikely to be able to accommodate larger Code D aircraft, such as the [[Boeing 767]].<ref name=\"SHI20131206\" />\nThe upgrade was to be funded from cost savings on other parts of the project,<ref name=\"SHO20130614\" /> particularly by a simplified runway drainage system.<ref name=\"SHG20130613\" />\n\n===Facilities===\nThere are two main buildings,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.sainthelenaaccess.com/news/faqs/ |title=Frequently Asked Questions : Saint Helena Airport Project |publisher=Sainthelenaaccess.com |date=10 May 2016 |access-date=25 July 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170725045440/http://www.sainthelenaaccess.com/news/faqs/ |archive-date=25 July 2017 |url-status=dead  }}</ref> the terminal building, and the combined building for airport operations, e.g. air traffic control, rescue services, etc. In addition there are some smaller buildings. The terminal building has a caf\u00e9, a gift shop, a [[duty-free shop]] and a restaurant.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sainthelenaaccess.com/news/wp-content/uploads/2016/05/150505_No-73.pdf|title=First Operational Trial at St Helena Airport|access-date=20 May 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160603004730/http://www.sainthelenaaccess.com/news/wp-content/uploads/2016/05/150505_No-73.pdf|archive-date=3 June 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n===Navigation aids===\n[[File:St Helena Airport DVOR.png|thumb|Doppler VHF Omni-directional Radio Range system at St Helena Airport.]]\nThe distance from key destinations, the length of runway available, and the type of aircraft available in the region dictate that air services to St Helena must operate to the requirements of extended twin engine operations ([[ETOPS]]) which implies the provision of an instrument approach system based on an off-set [[Instrument landing system|instrument landing system localiser]] (ILS LLZ).<ref>[http://webarchive.nationalarchives.gov.uk/20090422165233/http://www.dfid.gov.uk/pubs/files/st-helena-proj-memo.pdf St Helena Access, Project Memorandum] Overseas Territories Department, Department for International Development (DFID), January 2005, p. B-6</ref><ref name=\"sainthelenaaccess.com\">[http://www.sainthelenaaccess.com/application/documents/Feasibility/01_Main_Report_Final.pdf \"''St Helena Access Feasibility Study''\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120426081359/http://www.sainthelenaaccess.com/application/documents/Feasibility/01_Main_Report_Final.pdf |date=26 April 2012 }} St Helena Government, Department for International Development, January 2005, p. 104</ref>\n\nSuch is also required by the terrain of the airport which, in commercial passenger air transport terms, is safety-critical due to its steep approaches, high elevation ({{convert|1000|ft|m|abbr=on|disp=or}} above sea level)<ref>[http://www.sainthelenaaccess.com/application/documents/Feasibility/01_Main_Report_Final.pdf \"''St Helena Access Feasibility Study''\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120426081359/http://www.sainthelenaaccess.com/application/documents/Feasibility/01_Main_Report_Final.pdf |date=26 April 2012 }} St Helena Government, Department for International Development, January 2005, p. 13</ref> and rocky outcrops. Without an instrument approach the provision of a viable air service would be considered impossible.<ref>[http://www.sainthelenaaccess.com/application/documents/Feasibility/01_Main_Report_Final.pdf \"''St Helena Access Feasibility Study''\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120426081359/http://www.sainthelenaaccess.com/application/documents/Feasibility/01_Main_Report_Final.pdf |date=26 April 2012 }} St Helena Government, Department for International Development, January 2005, p. 317</ref>\n\nBecause of the above, St Helena Airport was equipped with an [[instrument landing system]] (ILS) and a Doppler VHF Omni-directional Radio Range system ([[DVOR]]) supplied by [[Thales Group]].<ref name=\"thales\">{{cite web |url=http://www.thalesgroup.com/Press_Releases/Countries/United_Kingdom/2012/121107_Thales_wins_navigation_contract_for_St_Helena_Island%E2%80%99s_first_airport/ |title=Thales wins navigation contract for St Helena Island's first airport |publisher=Thales Group |work=press release |date=7 November 2012 |access-date=9 November 2012 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121122003132/http://www.thalesgroup.com/Press_Releases/Countries/United_Kingdom/2012/121107_Thales_wins_navigation_contract_for_St_Helena_Island%E2%80%99s_first_airport/ |archive-date=22 November 2012  }}</ref> Further to that [[Honeywell Aerospace]] supplied a ''SmartPath'' [[ground-based augmentation system]] (GBAS), a technology that augments [[Global Positioning System|global positioning system]] (GPS) signals to make them suitable for precision approach and landing. It overcomes many of the limitations of [[instrument landing system]]s (ILS) traditionally used by airports to guide aircraft as they approach the runway.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://aerospace.honeywell.com/about/media-resources/newsroom/honeywell-to-provide-aircraft-landing-assurance-at-st-helena-airport#sthash.T8oGLCNq.dpuf |title=Honeywell to provide aircraft landing assurance at St Helena's first airport |date=3 April 2014 |publisher=Honeywell International Inc. |work=press release |access-date=11 May 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150406142720/https://aerospace.honeywell.com/about/media-resources/newsroom/honeywell-to-provide-aircraft-landing-assurance-at-st-helena-airport#sthash.T8oGLCNq.dpuf |archive-date=6 April 2015 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[Transport on Saint Helena]]\n*[[Economy of Saint Helena]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em|refs=\n\n<ref name=\"aip_fhsh_adc\">{{cite web|title=Aerdrome Chart \u2013 ICAO: St Helena. St Helena Airport|url=http://www.atns.com/downloads/FHSH%20AD%202-11.pdf|website=AIP Saint Helena|access-date=6 April 2016|date=28 April 2016|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160616084743/http://www.atns.com/downloads/FHSH%20AD%202-11.pdf|archive-date=16 June 2016}}</ref>\n\n}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category-inline|Saint Helena Airport}}\n* [http://flytosthelenaairport.com/ Saint Helena Access official website]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20060712090648/http://www.shelco.sh/ Shelco website]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20090326173143/http://www.dfid.gov.uk/pubs/files/st-helena-proj-memo.pdf  DFID Website on air access]\n* [https://www.google.com/maps/contrib/105239076880675861601/photos Photospheres from inside the terminal] (Google maps)\n{{Saint Helena, Ascension and Tristan da Cunha}}\n{{Airports in the United Kingdom and the British Crown Dependencies}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Airports in Saint Helena]]\n[[Category:Airports established in 2016]]\n[[Category:2016 establishments in Africa]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Airport in the British Overseas Territory of Saint Helena}}\n{{EngvarB|date=October 2013}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2019}}\n{{Infobox airport\n| name = Saint Helena Airport\n| nativename = \n| image = St Helena Airport logo.svg\n| image-width = 200\n| image2 = First Comair Boeing 737-800 flight to Saint Helena Airport (191).jpg\n| image2-width =  250\n| IATA = HLE\n| ICAO = FHSH\n| WMO = 61901\n| type = Public\n| owner = Saint Helena Government\n| operator = St Helena Airport Limited\n| location = [[Longwood, Saint Helena|Longwood]], [[Saint Helena, Ascension and Tristan da Cunha]]\n| opened = June 2016\n| hub = \n| elevation-f = 1017\n| elevation-m = \n| coordinates = {{coord|15|57|33|S|5|38|45|W|region:SH-HL|display=inline,title}}\n| website = [http://www.sthelenaairport.com sthelenaairport.com]\n| pushpin_map = South Atlantic\n| pushpin_mapsize = \n| pushpin_map_alt = \n| pushpin_map_caption = Location of St Helena Airport\n| pushpin_relief = \n| pushpin_image = South Atlantic Ocean laea relief location map.jpg\n| pushpin_label = HLE\n| pushpin_label_position = bottom\n| pushpin_mark = \n| pushpin_marksize = \n| r1-number = 02/20\n| r1-length-f = \n| r1-length-m = 1950\n| r1-surface = Concrete\n| metric-rwy = yes\n| stat-year = 2018\n| stat1-header = Passengers\n| stat1-data = 7649 <ref>{{Cite web |url=http://sartma.com/art_14816.html |title=St Helena : VISITORS TO ST HELENA HIGHLIGHTS IN 2018 |access-date=2 February 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190202100736/http://sartma.com/art_14816.html |archive-date=2 February 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n| footnotes = Sources: AIP St Helena,<ref name=\"aip_fhsh_adc\" /> St Helena Government<ref name=\"IM\">{{cite web|url=http://www.flytosthelena.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/06/St-Helena-Air-Services-Information-Memorandum.pdf|title=St Helena Government \u2013 Information Memorandum|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304082601/http://www.flytosthelena.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/06/St-Helena-Air-Services-Information-Memorandum.pdf|archive-date=4 March 2016}}</ref>\n}}\n\n'''Saint Helena Airport''' {{Airport codes|HLE|FHSH}} is an [[international airport]] on [[Saint Helena]], a remote island in the south [[Atlantic Ocean]], in the [[British Overseas Territories|British Overseas Territory]] of [[Saint Helena, Ascension and Tristan da Cunha|Saint Helena, Ascension, and Tristan da Cunha.]]\n\nThe construction of the runway was finished in 2015 and the airport opened in 2016.  The inaugural scheduled flight was delayed but general aviation, charter, and medical evacuation flights were able to serve the airport from May 2016.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.sainthelena.gov.sh/cancellation-of-notice-to-airmen/ |title=Cancellation of Notice To Airmen \u00ab St Helena |publisher=Sainthelena.gov.sh |date=1 July 2016 |access-date=25 July 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161026174632/http://www.sainthelena.gov.sh/cancellation-of-notice-to-airmen/ |archive-date=26 October 2016 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://sainthelenaisland.info/flyyourselfhere.htm |title=Saint Helena Island Info: All about St Helena, in the South Atlantic Ocean \u2022 Fly Yourself Here |publisher=Sainthelenaisland.info |access-date=25 July 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170325082913/http://sainthelenaisland.info/flyyourselfhere.htm |archive-date=25 March 2017 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nThe airport began scheduled commercial services on 14 October 2017, when the South African carrier [[Airlink]] inaugurated a weekly service from [[O. R. Tambo International Airport]] in [[Johannesburg]], [[South Africa]], via [[Walvis Bay Airport]], [[Namibia]], using an [[Embraer E-Jet family|Embraer E190-100IGW]],<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.sainthelena.gov.sh/st-helena-prepares-for-inaugural-flight/|title=ST HELENA PREPARES FOR INAUGURAL FLIGHT|date=10 October 2017|work=St Helena|access-date=14 October 2017|language=en-US|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171014182516/http://www.sainthelena.gov.sh/st-helena-prepares-for-inaugural-flight/|archive-date=14 October 2017|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Pillay|first1=Kavitha|title=#FindYourEscape: Airlink flights to St Helena from SA now on sale|url=http://www.traveller24.com/News/Flights/findyourescape-airlink-flights-to-st-helena-from-sa-now-on-sale-20170922|access-date=23 September 2017|publisher=traveller24.com|date=22 September 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170923193715/http://www.traveller24.com/News/Flights/findyourescape-airlink-flights-to-st-helena-from-sa-now-on-sale-20170922|archive-date=23 September 2017|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite press release |url=https://flyairlink.com/news/airlinks-embraer-e190-ejets-commence-commercial-services |title=Airlink's Emmbraer E190 E-Jets Commence Commercial Services |publisher=Flyairlink.com |date=3 August 2017 |access-date=23 September 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170824092419/https://flyairlink.com/news/airlinks-embraer-e190-ejets-commence-commercial-services |archive-date=24 August 2017 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.sainthelena.gov.sh/sa-airlink-to-provide-scheduled-air-services-to-st-helena-and-ascension-island/ |title=Sa Airlink To Provide Scheduled Air Services To St Helena And Ascension Island \u00ab St Helena |publisher=Sainthelena.gov.sh |date=21 July 2017 |access-date=23 September 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170825223035/http://www.sainthelena.gov.sh/sa-airlink-to-provide-scheduled-air-services-to-st-helena-and-ascension-island/ |archive-date=25 August 2017 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name=bbc20171014>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-africa-41620003|title=First flight lands on remote St Helena|date=14 October 2017|via=www.bbc.com|access-date=21 June 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180620011451/https://www.bbc.com/news/world-africa-41620003|archive-date=20 June 2018|url-status=live|work=BBC News}}</ref> about one and a half years after the originally expected inauguration date, and with a smaller-sized aircraft, because of [[wind shear]] problems affecting the airport.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ch-aviation.com/portal/news/51502-st-helena-issues-second-rfp-for-scheduled-services|title=St. Helena issues second RFP for scheduled services|publisher=ch-aviation.com|access-date=25 July 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170227182926/http://www.ch-aviation.com/portal/news/51502-st-helena-issues-second-rfp-for-scheduled-services|archive-date=27 February 2017|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"AIRPORT OPENING CEREMONY POSTPONED\">[http://www.sainthelenaaccess.com/news/2016/04/27/airport-opening-ceremony-postponed/ AIRPORT OPENING CEREMONY POSTPONED] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160726092953/http://www.sainthelenaaccess.com/news/2016/04/27/airport-opening-ceremony-postponed/ |date=26 July 2016 }} (St Helena Government 26 April 2016)</ref><ref name=\"bbcnews\">[https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-36490496 bbc.com \u2013 St Helena airport delay 'to increase cost to UK government'] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180627020030/https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-36490496 |date=27 June 2018 }} 9 May 2016</ref> Additionally, monthly charter flights operate between [[Ascension Island]] and Saint Helena.\n\n==History==\n===Background===\nSaint Helena is more than {{convert|2000|km|mi|-2}} from the nearest major landmass.  Prior to the opening of the airport, the island was only reachable by sea, making it one of the most remote populated places on earth, measured as travel time from major cities. Sea journeys used to take five days from [[Cape Town]], with departures once every three weeks.\n\nThe first consideration of an airport on St Helena was made in 1943 by the [[South African Air Force]], which undertook a survey on [[Prosperous Bay Plain]] from October 1943 until January 1944, but concluded that, while technically feasible, an airport was not a practical proposition.<ref name=\"consultation_annex_a\">{{cite web |url=http://www.dfid.gov.uk/documents/consultations/sthelena/consult-sthele-annexes-apr09.pdf |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110202192044/http://www.dfid.gov.uk/Documents/consultations/sthelena/consult-sthele-annexes-apr09.pdf |url-status=dead |archive-date=2 February 2011 |title=DFID Consultation Document \u2013 Annex A \u2013 Summary of cost/benefit analysis and financial costs |publisher=DFID |date=16 April 2009 |page=12 }}</ref>\nFrom the 1960s, there was an idea{{by whom|date=April 2016}} to build an airport on the Island. In 1999, this was taken up by the island government.\n\nIt was suggested that an airport would extend the United Kingdom's capabilities to carry out airborne missions in the South Atlantic region, such as [[maritime patrol]]s in accordance with international fishing agreements (e.g., [[International Commission for the Conservation of Atlantic Tunas]]), counter-piracy missions along important trade routes, and also [[airlift]] operations notably into Southern Africa.{{citation needed|date=May 2017}}\n\nAccording to analysts,{{who|date=May 2017}} the UK government's decision to finally go ahead with the airport, after long delays, seems to be driven in part by concerns over a continuing tense standoff with Argentina in the [[Falkland Islands sovereignty dispute]]. The island is about {{convert|3812|mi}} from the Falklands \u2013 seven hours and 40 minutes' flight time. But, analysts say that was nevertheless an improvement over the present state of isolation from the UK for both St Helena and the Falklands.<ref name=\"upi.com\">{{cite web |url=http://www.upi.com/Business_News/Security-Industry/2011/11/07/St-Helena-airport-a-key-Falklands-link/UPI-78911320686806/ |title=St. Helena airport a key Falklands link |date=7 November 2011 |publisher=United Press International, Inc. |access-date=8 August 2012 |work=news article |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120202081633/http://www.upi.com/Business_News/Security-Industry/2011/11/07/St-Helena-airport-a-key-Falklands-link/UPI-78911320686806/ |archive-date=2 February 2012 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nThe following possible benefits were also factors in the decision-making process:\n* Air access would allow St Helena to develop its tourism sector.{{Citation needed|date=July 2017}}\n* The new wharf in Rupert's Bay could allow regularly passing cruise ships to land passengers at the island and bring tourists if sized appropriately. The lack of a protected landing facility represents a limitation on the development of cruise tourism. In unfavourable sea conditions, landing is hazardous and potential revenue is lost as many cruise ships refuse to allow passengers to land in such circumstances. In addition, because there is no protected landing facility, many cruise companies do not incorporate St Helena into their itineraries. The sea is roughest in summer which marks the peak of the cruise season.<ref>[http://www.sainthelena.gov.sh/data/files/non_technical_summary.pdf \"''Jamestown, St Helena Wharf Improvements, Project EIA: Phase 2, Final Report''\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111103165325/http://www.sainthelena.gov.sh/data/files/non_technical_summary.pdf |date=3 November 2011 }} by the Government of St Helena, 8 August 2011</ref>\n* Medical evacuations to South Africa for treatment of serious cases of illness would be sped up significantly: it may take up to one month until transport to South Africa by RMS ''St Helena'' becomes available.{{Citation needed|date=July 2017}}\n* The availability of heavy construction equipment would facilitate [[alternative energy]] projects, such as the construction of larger wind turbines, a [[tidal power plant]] or a dam with a hydro-power station in one of St Helena's valleys.<ref>[http://www.sainthelenaaccess.com/application/documents/Environmental-Statement/Volume_2_Technical_Summary/ES_Vol_2_Chap%2017_Combined%20Effects.pdf St Helena Airport Environmental Statement \u2013 Volume 2] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120426081417/http://www.sainthelenaaccess.com/application/documents/Environmental-Statement/Volume_2_Technical_Summary/ES_Vol_2_Chap%2017_Combined%20Effects.pdf |date=26 April 2012 }} by Faber Maunsell AECOM, p. 17-3</ref> Limitations in cargo size of ''[[RMS St Helena (1989)|RMS St Helena]]'' and the unavailability of a large crane prohibit construction of larger wind turbines.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=OXiTOjFj8MI#t=0m15s |title=Interview with Craig Penwarden, Renewable Energy Engineer at Saint Helena Government |access-date=28 November 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120523004935/http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=OXiTOjFj8MI#t=0m15s |archive-date=23 May 2012 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n[[File:View out over Prosperous Bay Plain, St Helena Island, c1985. Peter Neaum. - panoramio.jpg|thumb|View over Prosperous Bay Plain in the 1980s.]]\nIn contrast to the projected benefits, there were concerns that the proposed construction on the Prosperous Bay Plain would be detrimental to the local environment.  Specifically, Prosperous Bay Plain was one of the few remaining sites on Saint Helena that held [[Wildlife of St Helena|significant ecological diversity]].  According to a 2004 review by Atkins Management Consultants, the survival of numerous [[endemism|endemic species]] critically depended on preservation and protection of the location.  It was also an important{{according to whom|date=August 2015}} nesting site for the [[Saint Helena plover|wirebird]], Saint Helena's national bird which is listed as [[vulnerable species|vulnerable]]. Although the St Helena Leisure Corporation (Shelco) was a major force pushing for the airport's construction, its co-founder Sir Nigel Thompson was a former chairman of the environmental charity [[Campaign to Protect Rural England]].<ref name = propertyweek /><ref>Robin Stummer and Daniel Howden: [http://www.ezilon.com/information/article_11885.shtml \"The Battle for St Helena\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070927005814/http://www.ezilon.com/information/article_11885.shtml |date=27 September 2007 }}. ''Ezilon Infobase'', 20 October 2005. Retrieved 28 August 2007.</ref><ref>{{WWF ecoregion|name=St. Helena scrub and woodlands|id=at0720}} Retrieved 28 August 2007.</ref>\n\n=== Bidding process ===\nAfter a long period of rumour and consultation, in March 2005 the British government announced plans to construct an airport in St Helena, expected to be completed by 2010 and funded by the [[Department for International Development]] (DfID).\n\nAccording to ''[[Private Eye]]'' magazine, all of the companies tendering for the job of building and running the airport had by late September 2006 withdrawn from bidding for the project. The local Access Office explained that it seemed the bidders considered the DfID was unhelpful by not providing the possibility of on-site investigations in order to complete a detailed design before providing a fixed price for the project. According to the DfID's Director for Overseas Territories, his department remained committed to an airport for St Helena.<ref>\"Departure Delayed\". ''Private Eye'', No. 1167, 15\u201328 September 2006.</ref>\n\nDfID restarted the procurement process to identify a suitable [[Project delivery method|Design, Build and Operate]] (DBO) contractor in October 2006. Capability Statements were received by DfID in March 2007 and four bidders were pre-approved for the DBO contract and a further three applicants have been pre-approved for the Air Service Provider contract. The applicants for the DBO visited the island for six months from June 2007 before submitting their final proposals, and by January 2008 DfID was down to a shortlist of two bidders.\n\nThere were delays by the British government,<ref name=\"consultation_annex_a\"/> which went up to [[Prime Minister of the United Kingdom|Prime Minister]] [[Gordon Brown]] who insisted on personally reviewing the paperwork.<ref>{{cite news |url= https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2008/sep/26/gordonbrown.labourconference |title= Salvaged with a kiss? Maybe, but Brown's woes run deep |first= Martin |last= Kettle |newspaper= The Guardian |date= 26 September 2008 |access-date= 13 December 2016 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20170312152236/https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2008/sep/26/gordonbrown.labourconference |archive-date= 12 March 2017 |url-status= live }}</ref> An approved bidder was appointed in 2008, the Italian company [[Impregilo]]. The project was suspended in November 2008, because of financial pressures brought on by the [[financial crisis of 2007\u20132010]].\n\nIt was reported in ''[[The Guardian]]'' on 10 December 2008 that UK Secretary of State for International Development [[Douglas Alexander]] had announced a \"pause in negotiations over the St Helena airport contract\",<ref name = guardian>Owen Bowcott: \"[https://www.theguardian.com/travel/2008/dec/10/st-helena-airport-travel-tourism] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160305184647/http://www.theguardian.com/travel/2008/dec/10/st-helena-airport-travel-tourism |date=5 March 2016 }}\". ''[[The Guardian]]'', 10 December 2008. Retrieved 2008-DEC-10.</ref> apparently related to the 2008 economic downturn.\n\nThe St. Helena Leisure Corporation (Shelco) was set up by [[Arup Group Limited|Arup]]'s Sir Nigel Thompson and [[Berwin Leighton Paisner]]'s Robert Jones, who planned to construct luxury resorts and a hotel to be run by [[Oberoi Hotels & Resorts]] in conjunction with the airport. Though real estate was to be sold before construction had started, the proposal was turned down by the local government and the DfID.<ref name = propertyweek>David Lawson: \"[http://www.propertyweek.com/story.asp?storyCode=3056937 Island in the Sun] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070927201509/http://www.propertyweek.com/story.asp?storyCode=3056937 |date=27 September 2007 }}\". ''[[Property Week]]'', 30 September 2005. Retrieved 29 August 2007.</ref>\n\nThe cost of airport was reported to be \u00a3285.5 million for DfID in April 2016.<ref name=\"bbcnews\" />\n\n===Airport construction===\nApproximately \u00a3202 million was funded for design and construction by South African engineering group Basil Read (Pty) Ltd. The UK government also granted additional funds of up to \u00a310 million in shared-risk contingency, and \u00a335.1 million for 10 years of operation by South African airport operator Lanseria Airport. According to the St Helena government, this was 20% less in real terms from the 2008 price, taking into account inflation and the value of the pound. The airport would be the largest single investment ever made in the island.<ref name=\"Airport Approved\"/>\n\nHowever, no final contracts had been signed by January 2009 and as construction had not commenced, the [[Governor of Saint Helena, Ascension and Tristan da Cunha|island's governor]], [[Andrew Gurr (governor)|Andrew Gurr]], travelled to London in an attempt to speed up the process. On 22 July 2010 the British government agreed to assist in payment for the new airport.<ref>{{cite news |url= https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/worldnews/africaandindianocean/sainthelena/7905386/Britain-to-pay-for-St-Helena-airstrip-backed-by-Lord-Ashcroft.html |title= Britain to pay for St Helena airstrip backed by Lord Ashcroft |newspaper= [[The Daily Telegraph|The Telegraph]] |date= 22 July 2010 |access-date= 2 April 2018 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20121114175810/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/worldnews/africaandindianocean/sainthelena/7905386/Britain-to-pay-for-St-Helena-airstrip-backed-by-Lord-Ashcroft.html |archive-date= 14 November 2012 |url-status= live }}</ref> On 3 November 2011 Governor [[Mark Andrew Capes|Mark Capes]] announced construction contracts had been signed.<ref name=\"Airport Approved\">{{cite news |url= http://www.news.co.sh/Newspapers/SHH%2020111104.pdf |title= Airport Approved |newspaper= The St Helena Herald |volume= XI |number= 28 |date= 4 November 2011 |page= 4 }}{{Dead link|date=August 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\n[[File:Prosperous Bay Plain Airport (16512903591).jpg|thumbnail|right|Construction on [[Prosperous Bay Plain]], February 2015]]\nOn 4 November 2011 Basil Read was awarded the contract to construct an airport on St Helena Island.<ref name=\"basilread.co.za\"/> The first representatives of Basil Read visited the island on Saturday, 19 November 2011 for initial investigations and discussions.<ref>[http://www.sainthelena.gov.sh/news.php/448/basil-read-team-progression-with-airport-developments \"''Basil Read Team \u2013 Progression with Airport Developments''\"] {{webarchive|url=https://archive.is/20120805115952/http://www.sainthelena.gov.sh/news.php/448/basil-read-team-progression-with-airport-developments |date=5 August 2012 }} St Helena Government Public Relations / Information Office, Press Release, 24 November 2011</ref> Following a second team's visit during December 2011 Basil Read's project manager settled on the island and the first St Helenian citizen was employed.<ref name=\"news.co.sh\"/>\n\nBasil Read CEO Heyns in November 2011 said the design phase would begin immediately and anticipated that construction could begin in May 2012, which at peak would employ some 300 people of whom as many locals as possible should be involved.<ref>[http://www.saint.fm/Independent/20111021.pdf \"''Airport News''\"] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130510171912/http://www.saint.fm/Independent/20111021.pdf |date=10 May 2013 }} St Helena Independent, Volume VI, Issue 49, 21 October 2011, p. 2</ref> Construction is said to take place over a 48-month period.<ref name=\"engineeringnews.co.za\"/>\n\nPreparation works began in early 2012 in Rupert's Valley on the west coast, which included establishing storage facilities, a temporary fuel farm and the design and construction of a temporary wharf.<ref name=\"Basil Read Team Arrives' 2011, p.4\">[http://www.news.co.sh/Newspapers/SHH%2020111209.pdf \"''Second Basil Read Team Arrives''\"]{{dead link|date=April 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }} The St Helena Herald, Volume XI Number 33, 9 December 2011, p.4</ref> A new jetty was built at Rupert's Bay to enable the landing of supplies and construction vehicles.\n\nOnly four weeks after the approval for the airport to be constructed and years before operations would start, Geo. Robson & Co. (Conveyors) Ltd. had already completed and shipped a [[baggage carousel]] for the airport. The company stated that with a {{convert|12|m|adj=on}} perimeter it was one of the smallest baggage carousels they had ever manufactured.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hub-4.com/news/4013/robson-ships-to-the-south-atlantic|title=Robson Ships to the South Atlantic|publisher=HUB|date=1 December 2011|access-date=30 December 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120426081614/http://www.hub-4.com/news/4013/robson-ships-to-the-south-atlantic|archive-date=26 April 2012|url-status=live}}</ref> Until the airport opened it was planned for use at St Helena's harbour to deliver baggage to passengers arriving by RMS ''St Helena''.{{Citation needed|date=July 2017}}\n\n[[File:St Helena Airport Terminal (16331626258).jpg|thumb|right|Construction of the airport terminal and air traffic control tower.]]\nLogistics of the airport's construction were critical, because of the island's isolated location and the lack of construction equipment, which would require everything such as extremely heavy duty equipment and materials to be shipped in, thus resulting in a huge and unique logistics operation.<ref name=\"news.co.sh\">[http://www.news.co.sh/Newspapers/SHH%2020111223.pdf \"''Basil Read's second team Visits and first St Helenian employed''\", St Helena Herald, Volume XI no. 35, 23 December 2011, p. 5]{{dead link|date=April 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> Due to the limited landing infrastructure, with no breakwater or mooring facilities at the sea front, new harbour facilities capable of handling construction equipment and fuel supplies were constructed at Rupert's Bay.<ref>[http://www.sainthelenaaccess.com/application/documents/Feasibility/01_Main_Report_Final.pdf \"''St Helena Access Feasibility Study''\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120426081359/http://www.sainthelenaaccess.com/application/documents/Feasibility/01_Main_Report_Final.pdf |date=26 April 2012 }} St Helena Government, Department for International Development, January 2005, p. 17</ref> Fuel transfers between Rupert's Bay and the aerodrome, connected by a {{convert|14|km|4=0|adj=on}} haul road, were assumed to be by road tanker for 20 years, after which a capital allowance was made for enlargement of the bulk fuel storage and the installation of a fuel transfer pipeline.<ref name=\"sainthelenaaccess.com\"/>\n\nBasil Read sourced its own ship, a [[roll-on/roll-off]] vessel<ref name=\"engineeringnews.co.za\">[http://www.engineeringnews.co.za/article/basil-read-wins-r27bn-contract-to-build-st-helena-first-airport-2011-11-03 \"''Basil Read wins R2.7bn contract to build St Helena's first airport ''\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111207182100/http://www.engineeringnews.co.za/article/basil-read-wins-r27bn-contract-to-build-st-helena-first-airport-2011-11-03 |date=7 December 2011 }} Engineering News, 3 November 2011</ref> called ''NP Glory 4'' flying the Thai flag,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.marinetraffic.com/ais/shipdetails.aspx?MMSI=567321000 |title=N P GLORY 4 |author=MarineTraffic.com |publisher=MarineTraffic.com |work=database |access-date=7 November 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120719005230/http://www.marinetraffic.com/ais/shipdetails.aspx?MMSI=567321000 |archive-date=19 July 2012 |url-status=dead  }}</ref> which docked for the first time at St Helena on 11 July 2012 and subsequently provided regular supplies to the island, including cargo and personnel for the project.<ref name=\"Basil Read Team Arrives' 2011, p.4\"/><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.shbc.sh/L3_news_120711_np_glory_lands.html |title=NP GLORY 4 MAKES HISTORY, DOCKING AT ST HELENA |author=Sharon Henry |publisher=St The St Helena Broadcasting (Guarantee) Corporation Ltd. |work=news article |accessdate=7 November 2012}}</ref> The company also considered developing a temporary runway to enable the use of a [[Lockheed C-130 Hercules|C-130 Hercules]]-type aircraft to facilitate quicker access to the site within 18 months of the beginning of construction,<ref name=\"engineeringnews.co.za\"/> but this was not done.\n\nIn June 2013 the 100,000th truckload of fill went into Dry Gut, a gorge which had to be raised by almost {{convert|100|m|ft}} in order to create an embankment that would finally carry parts of the runway. This was equivalent to nearly 19% of the total of 8 million cubic metres required. Basil Read's calculations showed that a further 430,000 truckloads of material would be needed to complete the fill.\n\nIn September 2013, workers employed by Basil Read went on [[Strike action|strike]] in a dispute over working conditions and wages - it was the island's [[Trade unions in Saint Helena|first strike in half a century]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://en.mercopress.com/2013/09/05/labour-dispute-stops-the-construction-of-the-st-helena-airport-in-mid-atlantic|title=Labour dispute stops the construction of the St Helena airport in mid-Atlantic|website=MercoPress|language=en|access-date=16 October 2019}}</ref>\n\nBy the summer of 2015, the Dry Gut fill project was completed and the new runway built.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sainthelenaaccess.com/news/wp-content/uploads/2014/06/St-Helena-Airport-update-No-48.pdf|title=St Helena Airport update no 48|access-date=15 July 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140725013946/http://www.sainthelenaaccess.com/news/wp-content/uploads/2014/06/St-Helena-Airport-update-No-48.pdf|archive-date=25 July 2014|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n===Airport certification and opening===\n[[Avia Solutions Group]] was appointed to support the St Helena Government (SHG) and the UK [[Department for International Development]] (DFID) in reaching a contract with an air service provider to provide services to the island.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.flytosthelena.com/ |access-date=11 May 2014 |website=Fly to St Helena |title=homepage |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140512222650/http://www.flytosthelena.com/ |archive-date=12 May 2014 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nCalibration flights at the airport began in mid-September 2015. A [[Beechcraft King Air 200]], leased from TAB Charters in South Africa, landed on 15 September 2015 in order to perform tests of the airport navigation systems.<ref>{{cite news |url= http://independent.saint.fm/wp-content/uploads/2015/09/St-Helena-Independent-20150918.pdf |title= A Landing to be Remembered |page= 6 |work= Saint Helena Independent|date= 18 September 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Remote St Helena island welcomes first flight|url=https://www.theguardian.com/travel/2015/sep/17/first-plane-lands-st-helena-airport-atlantic-ocean-south-africa|access-date=13 December 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160429050906/http://www.theguardian.com/travel/2015/sep/17/first-plane-lands-st-helena-airport-atlantic-ocean-south-africa|archive-date=29 April 2016|url-status=live|newspaper=The Guardian|date=17 September 2015|last1=Weaver|first1=Emma}}</ref> UK-based Flight Calibration Services undertook the flights and flew from [[Lanseria International Airport]], in [[Johannesburg]], flying via [[Namibia]] and [[Angola]]. The aircraft was on site for approximately one week to undertake the calibration flights.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://en.mercopress.com/2015/09/12/first-landing-ever-in-st-helena-airport-scheduled-for-next-week-as-part-of-calibration-flights|title=First landing ever in St Helena airport scheduled for next week as part of calibration flights|access-date=14 September 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150915015421/http://en.mercopress.com/2015/09/12/first-landing-ever-in-st-helena-airport-scheduled-for-next-week-as-part-of-calibration-flights|archive-date=15 September 2015|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOpening was originally scheduled for February 2016 but that was postponed a number of times because of air traffic control related issues.<ref name=nov15delay>{{cite web|url=http://www.sainthelenaaccess.com/news/2015/11/06/airport-board-grants-additional-time-to-achieve-operational-readiness/|title=AIRPORT BOARD GRANTS ADDITIONAL TIME TO ACHIEVE OPERATIONAL READINESS : Saint Helena Airport Project|website=www.sainthelenaaccess.com|access-date=19 November 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160221140342/http://www.sainthelenaaccess.com/news/2015/11/06/airport-board-grants-additional-time-to-achieve-operational-readiness/|archive-date=21 February 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref> In November 2015, a delay of the opening from February to May 2016 was announced.<ref name=nov15delay/> This was needed \"in order to fine tune the operational readiness of the airport\".\n\nDue to uncertainties concerning weather conditions and, in particular the amount of turbulence on the approaches from [[Katabatic wind|fallwind]]s resulting from the elevated location and the surrounding bluffs, it was recommended that a charter aircraft should perform approaches to and departures from the intended runway.<ref>[http://www.sainthelenaaccess.com/application/documents/Feasibility/01_Main_Report_Final.pdf \"''St Helena Access Feasibility Study''\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120426081359/http://www.sainthelenaaccess.com/application/documents/Feasibility/01_Main_Report_Final.pdf |date=26 April 2012 }} St Helena Government, Department for International Development, January 2005, p. 117</ref> By April 2016 such flights had taken place, and they were not positive, causing a delay in traffic start.{{Citation needed|date=July 2017}}\n\n[[File:First Comair Boeing 737-800 flight to Saint Helena Airport (79).jpg|thumb|right|The [[Boeing 737-800]] implementation flight landing at the airport.]]\nThe first\u2014and {{As of|2017|July|lc=y}} only\u2014large (above 100 seats) passenger jet landed on 18 April 2016, a [[Boeing 737-800]] operated by [[Comair (South Africa)|Comair]]. It was an implementation flight to test the route, ground operations and handling, ahead of commencement of scheduled services.<ref>{{cite news |url= https://www.flightglobal.com/news/articles/pictures-comair-737-arrives-at-new-st-helena-airpor-424388/ |title= Pictures : Comair 737 arrives at new St Helena airport |publisher= [[flightglobal]] |date= 20 April 2016 |access-date= 20 April 2016 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20160420162943/https://www.flightglobal.com/news/articles/pictures-comair-737-arrives-at-new-st-helena-airpor-424388/ |archive-date= 20 April 2016 |url-status= live }}</ref> The landing was not straightforward, with the aircraft only successfully landing on its third approach (the first approach was a planned [[Go-around]], because of the lack of experience with this airport).<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/business/video/2016/sep/22/british-airways-flight-struggles-to-land-on-st-helena-runway-video |title=British Airways flight struggles to land on St Helena runway \u2013 video &#124; Business |work=The Guardian|date=22 September 2016 |access-date=25 July 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170728201449/https://www.theguardian.com/business/video/2016/sep/22/british-airways-flight-struggles-to-land-on-st-helena-runway-video |archive-date=28 July 2017 |url-status=live }}</ref> On 26 April 2016, a further delay to the opening, without a specified end date, was announced by the St. Helena Government because of concerns regarding [[wind shear]], after the problematic landing by the Comair 737-800 intended for regular flights.<ref name=\"AIRPORT OPENING CEREMONY POSTPONED\"/> Only southbound landings (runway 20) have wind shear problems, not northbound.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sainthelenaaccess.com/news/2016/06/06/maintaining-access-to-st-helena-ascension/|title=MAINTAINING ACCESS TO ST HELENA & ASCENSION : Saint Helena Airport Project|website=www.sainthelenaaccess.com|access-date=11 June 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170729001524/http://www.sainthelenaaccess.com/news/2016/06/06/maintaining-access-to-st-helena-ascension/|archive-date=29 July 2017|url-status=dead}}</ref> There is a need to define measurement methods for the wind shear in order to understand when landing can be done, and when to cancel flights. The late postponement caused extra cost, for example contracted employees and contracted airlines that cannot operate, hotels that were built, and also the need to extend the use of the RMS ''St Helena'', which originally was due to be retired after the airport opened.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.atlanticstarairlines.com/#!air-access-project/ca4p|title=The Air Access Project|publisher=Atlantic Star Airlines|access-date=12 January 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150106222237/http://www.atlanticstarairlines.com/#!air-access-project/ca4p|archive-date=6 January 2015|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://en.mercopress.com/2015/05/23/on-st-helena-day-21-may-2016-begins-air-link-of-the-island-with-south-africa |title=On St Helena Day, 21 May 2016, begins air link of the island with South Africa \u2014 MercoPress |publisher=En.mercopress.com |date=23 May 2015 |access-date=25 July 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150524135307/http://en.mercopress.com/2015/05/23/on-st-helena-day-21-may-2016-begins-air-link-of-the-island-with-south-africa |archive-date=24 May 2015 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=RMS Sailing Schedule extended until February 2018 - RMS St Helena|url=http://rms-st-helena.com/2016/12/15/rms-sailing-schedule-extended-february-2018/|website=RMS St Helena|access-date=15 October 2017|date=15 December 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171007021623/http://rms-st-helena.com/2016/12/15/rms-sailing-schedule-extended-february-2018/|archive-date=7 October 2017|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nFollowing an inspection in April 2016, on 10 May, UK-based Air Safety Support International (ASSI), a subsidiary company of the [[Civil Aviation Authority]] responsible for aviation safety in Overseas Territories, issued an Aerodrome Certificate to St Helena Airport. This safety certificate indicated that airport infrastructure, aviation security measures and air traffic control service complied with international aviation safety and security standards.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sainthelenaaccess.com/news/2016/05/11/st-helena-airport-certified/|title=ST HELENA AIRPORT CERTIFIED : Saint Helena Airport Project|website=www.sainthelenaaccess.com|access-date=15 May 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170729001815/http://www.sainthelenaaccess.com/news/2016/05/11/st-helena-airport-certified/|archive-date=29 July 2017|url-status=dead}}</ref> ASSI did not allow the airport to go into commercial operation, however, due to concerns over operational readiness of monitoring and clearing issues that include wind shear and turbulence.<ref>[http://traveller24.news24.com/News/Flights/st-helena-airport-step-closer-to-operating-as-final-rms-journey-on-the-horizon-20160512 St Helena Airport step closer to operating as final RMS journey on the horizon] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160513105819/http://traveller24.news24.com/News/Flights/st-helena-airport-step-closer-to-operating-as-final-rms-journey-on-the-horizon-20160512 |date=13 May 2016 }}, [[News24|Traveller24]], 12 May 2016</ref>\n\nThe airport opened in June 2016, but restrictions for large aircraft remained due to dangerous [[wind shear]]. The airport's advocates hope that it will bring growth to the island's economy through tourism, leading to financial self-sustainability and an end to UK budgetary aid.<ref name=\"Airport Approved\"/>\n\nA new safety certificate was delivered on 26 October 2016 by Air Safety Support International.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://en.mercopress.com/2016/10/27/milestone-for-st-helena-airport-certification-for-aviation-safety-and-security-standards|title=Milestone for St Helena Airport: certification for aviation safety and security standards|website=MercoPress|access-date=27 October 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161027192407/http://en.mercopress.com/2016/10/27/milestone-for-st-helena-airport-certification-for-aviation-safety-and-security-standards|archive-date=27 October 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> After the bankruptcy of the company [[Basil Read]] which built and operated the airport, the Saint Helena government owned company took over the operations, for which it got a new safety certificate on 5 October 2018.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://sthelenaairport.com/news/st-helena-airport-re-opens-5-october-2018/ |title=St Helena Airport re-opens - 5 October 2018 |access-date=9 October 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181009172028/http://sthelenaairport.com/news/st-helena-airport-re-opens-5-october-2018/ |archive-date=9 October 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n===Early air traffic history===\nSince the airport opened, {{As of|2017|4|alt=through to early April 2017}}, 32 private aircraft have landed at the airport.  These flights were mostly for either business passengers or medical evacuation purposes.  The aircraft involved were smaller and lighter than the Boeing 737 and usually landed in the opposite direction on the runway from that taken by the 737-800 implementation flight in the southbound direction.  The opposite, northbound, direction has an approach which is generally less turbulent but can only be used by lighter aircraft.<ref name=Newsweek2017>{{cite news |last=Mahr |first=Krista |url=http://www.newsweek.com/st-helena-windy-airport-tourists-one-worlds-most-remote-islands-589707 |title=How a Windy Airport Could Ruin Plans to Bring Tourists to One of the World's Most Remote Islands |publisher=Newsweek.com |date=25 April 2017 |access-date=25 July 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170501042246/http://www.newsweek.com/st-helena-windy-airport-tourists-one-worlds-most-remote-islands-589707 |archive-date=1 May 2017 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nThe first helicopter to use the airport was an [[AgustaWestland AW159 Wildcat|AgustaWestland Wildcat HMA.2]] of 201 Flight [[825 Naval Air Squadron]] attached to the [[Type 23 frigate]] {{HMS|Lancaster|F229|6}} on 14 October 2015.<ref name=\"WL\">{{cite web|url=http://www.janes.com/article/54622/wildcat-loose-dsei15d4|title=Wildcat loose|publisher=Janes|accessdate=23 October 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.westerngazette.co.uk/Wildcat-maritime-attack-helicopter-takes-seas/story-26238365-detail/story.html|title=Wildcat maritime attack helicopter takes to the seas|work=Western Gazette|access-date=23 October 2015|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150904083618/http://www.westerngazette.co.uk/Wildcat-maritime-attack-helicopter-takes-seas/story-26238365-detail/story.html|archive-date=4 September 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.royalnavy.mod.uk/news-and-latest-activity/news/2015/october/23/151023-wildcat-first-helicopter-at-st-helena-airport|title=Wildcat becomes first helicopter to land at St Helena Airport|publisher=Royal Navy|access-date=23 October 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151024234832/http://www.royalnavy.mod.uk/news-and-latest-activity/news/2015/october/23/151023-wildcat-first-helicopter-at-st-helena-airport|archive-date=24 October 2015|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title = Wildcat makes history on St Helena|url = https://navynews.co.uk/archive/news/item/13485|website = navynews.co.uk|access-date = 15 December 2015|archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20151222081533/https://navynews.co.uk/archive/news/item/13485|archive-date = 22 December 2015|url-status = live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.sainthelena.gov.sh/first-ever-rotary-wing-aircraft-lands-at-st-helena-airport/ |title=Anonymous, \"FIRST EVER ROTARY-WING AIRCRAFT LANDS AT ST HELENA AIRPORT,\" sainthelena.gov.sh, October 15, 2015. |access-date=15 October 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171016014723/http://www.sainthelena.gov.sh/first-ever-rotary-wing-aircraft-lands-at-st-helena-airport/ |archive-date=16 October 2017 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nAn important reason to build the airport was availability for medical emergency evacuation. On 3 June 2016 the first ambulance flight took place, for a baby and his mother.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sainthelenaaccess.com/news/2016/06/07/first-ever-medevac-flight-critically-ill-saint-transferred-to-cape-town/|title=FIRST EVER MEDEVAC FLIGHT \u2013 CRITICALLY ILL SAINT TRANSFERRED TO CAPE TOWN : Saint Helena Airport Project|website=www.sainthelenaaccess.com|access-date=11 June 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160917192453/http://www.sainthelenaaccess.com/news/2016/06/07/first-ever-medevac-flight-critically-ill-saint-transferred-to-cape-town/|archive-date=17 September 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nThere are no aircraft dedicated to calibration flights, but occasionally such flights have taken place. On Friday 21 October 2016, an [[Avro RJ100]] jet airliner sponsored by [[Atlantic Star Airlines]] landed on St Helena Airport, with 13 non-commercial passengers on board, as part of a delivery to Chile. Both pilots were from the [[Faroe Islands]] and had experience from there with landing in windy conditions.<ref name=\"THE MONTSERRAT REPORTER NEWSPAPER\">[https://www.themontserratreporter.com/is-atlantic-star-the-solution-to-st-helena-airport-wind-shear/ Is Atlantic Star The Solution To St Helena Airport Wind Shear?'] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161024030539/https://www.themontserratreporter.com/is-atlantic-star-the-solution-to-st-helena-airport-wind-shear/ |date=24 October 2016 }} 22 October 2016.</ref> An [[Embraer E-Jet family|Embraer ERJ-190-100]] operated by Embraer Aviation flew from Brazil and made a number of landings and starts on St Helena on 30 November and 1 December 2016.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sainthelenaaccess.com/news/2016/11/28/embraer-trial-flight-confirmed-large-passenger-aircraft-to-land-on-tuesday/|title=EMBRAER TRIAL FLIGHT CONFIRMED \u2013 LARGE PASSENGER AIRCRAFT TO LAND ON TUESDAY : Saint Helena Airport Project|website=www.sainthelenaaccess.com|access-date=3 December 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161220034335/http://www.sainthelenaaccess.com/news/2016/11/28/embraer-trial-flight-confirmed-large-passenger-aircraft-to-land-on-tuesday/|archive-date=20 December 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=kypMTPJ-KKU|title=Long landing of Embraer E190 at St Helena Airport on 1st Dec 2016|last=Bob St Helena|date=3 December 2016|via=YouTube|access-date=3 December 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161220065619/https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=kypMTPJ-KKU|archive-date=20 December 2016|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn 18 December 2016 a [[Royal Air Force]] [[C-130J Hercules]] landed at St Helena, the first fixed-wing military aircraft to land on the island.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://whatthesaintsdidnext.com/2016/12/18/raf-c-130-hercules-first-military-flight-lands-at-st-helena-airport/ |title=C130 Hercules at St Helena Airport: First Military Flight Landing |publisher=Whatthesaintsdidnext.com |date=18 December 2016 |accessdate=25 July 2017}}</ref> A [[South African Air Force]] C-130 visited the airport twice in July 2017.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.defenceweb.co.za/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=48705 |title=SAAF C-130BZ lands at St Helena, now back in SA |publisher=DefenceWeb.co.za |date=27 July 2017 |access-date=28 July 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170728202942/http://www.defenceweb.co.za/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=48705 |archive-date=28 July 2017 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n===Establishing commercial air service===\nPrior to the opening of the airport, it was decided that St Helena would have an [[Open skies|open skies policy]]; this allows any airline operator who meets all the required standards to fly in and out of St Helena.<ref name=\"TSHI20131018b\">{{cite news | title = Atlantic Star \u2013 The Only Plane in the St Helena Sky | page = 9 | newspaper = The St Helena Independent | location = Jamestown | volume = 8 | author = Vince Thompson | issue = 44 | date = 18 October 2013 | url = http://www.saint.fm/the-independent/ | access-date = 20 March 2015 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20171206201911/http://www.saint.fm/the-independent/ | archive-date = 6 December 2017 | url-status = live }}</ref> Projections for commercial flight costs were also drawn up and the St Helena Government expected that a return economy flight from St Helena to South Africa would cost around \u00a3600. Assuming that an off-peak economy seat from South Africa to the UK would be available for approximately \u00a3700, return tickets for flights via South Africa to the UK would take the total price to around \u00a31,300.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.sainthelenaaccess.com/faqs/ |title=Frequently Asked Questions |author=Air Access Office |website=St Helena Airport Project |publisher=St Helena Government |access-date=12 January 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131127035157/http://sainthelenaaccess.com/faqs/ |archive-date=27 November 2013 |url-status=dead  }}</ref>\n\nDue to the runway length and the distance to [[South Africa]] (3,700&nbsp;km to Johannesburg), a [[Boeing 737-76N|Boeing 737-700]] flying to [[Johannesburg]] serving St Helena would not be able to use its full seat and cargo capacity. Only flights to and from Namibian and Angolan destinations would allow using a Boeing 737-700 near its full load capacity. This was under the condition that both directions of the runway were available so tailwind landings could be avoided. The other planned destination, [[London]], requires a fuel stop in [[Gambia]], at almost the same distance as Johannesburg.  However, if [[RAF Ascension Island|Wideawake Airfield]] on [[Ascension Island]] was open for commercial non-military flights, it could be listed as an alternate aerodrome; as it is only 1,300&nbsp;km from St Helena this would mean that the load capacity of an inbound Boeing 737-700 could be increased as smaller fuel reserves would be required, since the alternate aerodrome could be used in case of problems at St. Helena.{{citation needed|date=April 2017}}\n\nIt is believed{{by whom|date=May 2017}} that reductions in ticket prices could be obtained by using spare payload capacity on flights to and from St Helena to carry air freight (e.g., agricultural products, coffee, fish).<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.sainthelenaaccess.com/application/documents/Feasibility/03_Appendices_Final_Vol_2_v2.pdf |title=St Helena Access Feasibility Study |page=3 |publisher=WS Atkins plc |author=WS Atkins plc |date=October 2004 |access-date=14 January 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150924093623/http://www.sainthelenaaccess.com/application/documents/Feasibility/03_Appendices_Final_Vol_2_v2.pdf |archive-date=24 September 2015 |url-status=dead  }}</ref> At 70% [[passenger load factor]] a B737-800 operating, on an average day, into St Helena would have a spare payload capacity of some {{convert|4000|kg}}. The extra income possible per in-bound flight from cargo could be as high as the income equivalent of 19 passengers, giving an effective load factor of 88% and could reduce ticket prices.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.sainthelenaaccess.com/application/documents/Feasibility/03_Appendices_Final_Vol_2_v2.pdf |title=St Helena Access Feasibility Study |page=4 |publisher=WS Atkins plc |author=WS Atkins plc |date=October 2004 |access-date=14 January 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150924093623/http://www.sainthelenaaccess.com/application/documents/Feasibility/03_Appendices_Final_Vol_2_v2.pdf |archive-date=24 September 2015 |url-status=dead  }}</ref>\n\nOn 16 March 2015 it was announced that SHG and DFID had appointed [[Comair (South Africa)|Comair Limited]] as the preferred bidder for the provision of air services to St Helena.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sainthelena.gov.sh/air-services-to-st-helena-2/|title=AIR SERVICES TO ST HELENA|date=16 March 2015|access-date=19 March 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150320215723/http://www.sainthelena.gov.sh/air-services-to-st-helena-2/|archive-date=20 March 2015|url-status=live}}</ref> Comair was proposing a weekly flight between [[Johannesburg Airport]] and St Helena using a [[Boeing 737-800]] aircraft, which has a flight time from Johannesburg to St Helena of about four and a half hours. Reaction to the Comair announcement on St Helena was largely negative,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.saint.fm/the-independent/|title=The St Helena Independent - Saint FM|access-date=20 March 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171206201911/http://www.saint.fm/the-independent/|archive-date=6 December 2017|url-status=live|date=13 August 2014}}</ref> with stories of luggage loss and crime in Johannesburg, and the fact that many of St Helena's residents have personal links with Cape Town.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://sartma.com/art_12365.html|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150412175008/http://sartma.com/art_12365.html|url-status=dead|archive-date=12 April 2015|title=Falkland Islands Current News Articles by SARTMA.com|date=12 April 2015}}</ref>\n\nOn 9 October 2015, Governor Mark Capes indicated that once a month there would be a flight from St Helena to Ascension Island provided by Comair.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.sainthelena.gov.sh/ascension-air-service-to-and-from-st-helena/ |title=ASCENSION AIR SERVICE TO AND FROM ST HELENA |publisher=St Helena Government |date=9 October 2015 |access-date=21 October 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151010075426/http://www.sainthelena.gov.sh/ascension-air-service-to-and-from-st-helena/ |archive-date=10 October 2015 |url-status=live }}</ref> The [[Ascension Island]] Government also announced a connection between the two islands. The connection was to be flown by [[Comair (South Africa)|Comair]] using a Boeing 737-800. The flight would have taken about two hours to [[RAF Ascension Island|Wideawake Airfield]]. Comair's air services between St Helena Airport and [[OR Tambo International Airport]] in Johannesburg were scheduled to commence in late May 2016, to coincide with the official opening of the airport on 21 May 2016. These dates were postponed because of the problems with [[wind shear]]; however, Comair did operate a few test flights which concluded in the windshear risk, mainly for aircraft of that size and larger.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.sainthelenaaccess.com/news/2015/10/09/ascension-air-service-to-and-from-st-helena/ |title=ASCENSION AIR SERVICE TO AND FROM ST HELENA : Saint Helena Airport Project |publisher=Sainthelenaaccess.com |date=9 October 2015 |access-date=25 July 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151029201909/http://www.sainthelenaaccess.com/news/2015/10/09/ascension-air-service-to-and-from-st-helena/ |archive-date=29 October 2015 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n[[Atlantic Star Airlines]] (operated by [[TUI Airlines Netherlands]]) had announced an intention to operate charter flights from [[Gatwick Airport|London-Gatwick]] via [[Banjul International Airport|Gambia]] (possibly starting May 2016)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.atlanticstarairlines.com/#!Atlantic-Star-Airlines-shares-news-of-delay-to-opening-date-of-StHelena-Airport/c10mv/563e5cbf0cf275e9c59c7d6e|title=Best value flights to St.Helena - Atlantic Star Airlines|website=Best value flights to St.Helena - Atlantic Star Airlines|access-date=12 January 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150106222237/http://www.atlanticstarairlines.com/#!Atlantic-Star-Airlines-shares-news-of-delay-to-opening-date-of-StHelena-Airport/c10mv/563e5cbf0cf275e9c59c7d6e|archive-date=6 January 2015|url-status=live}}</ref> using a [[Boeing 737-800]], an aircraft requiring a fairly long runway. This leaves [[Lubango Airport]] in [[Angola]], at a distance of {{convert|1300|mi|km}} as the next best diversion option for which every inbound aircraft must carry enough fuel reserve, limiting its load capacity.\n\nIn response to the wind shear problems, in June 2016 the Governor, [[Lisa Phillips (civil servant)|Lisa Phillips]], noted that restricting flight operations to runway 02, that is northbound landings and southbound starts on St Helena's single operating surface, might be a suitable interim solution.  While runway 02 does not suffer from a significant wind shear problem, restricting landings to one direction would prevent large aircraft from calling at St Helena.  Only permitting landings in one direction would mean that aircraft must to be able to land in tailwind.  Consequently, large aircraft, like the 737-800, could not be used because, in a tailwind, they would need a longer runway than St Helena provides.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sainthelenaaccess.com/news/2016/06/15/st-helena-airport-statement-from-governor-lisa-phillips/|title=ST HELENA AIRPORT \u2013 STATEMENT FROM GOVERNOR LISA PHILLIPS : Saint Helena Airport Project|website=www.sainthelenaaccess.com|access-date=22 June 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160701002815/http://www.sainthelenaaccess.com/news/2016/06/15/st-helena-airport-statement-from-governor-lisa-phillips/|archive-date=1 July 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref> If runway 20 is used, it will have severe wind restrictions.\n\nA debate about the project was held by the [[House of Lords]] in London on 17 October 2016. When asked by [[George Foulkes, Baron Foulkes of Cumnock|Lord Foulkes]] when the government expected commercial flights would start at the airport, the Minister of State, Department for International Development [[Michael Bates, Baron Bates|Lord Bates]] said, \"scheduled commercial flights will begin when the conditions are considered safe to do so and the St Helena Government are able to contract an airline with the right aircraft and regulatory approval.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.atlanticstarairlines.com/single-post/2016/10/17/Question-raised-today-in-the-House-of-Lords|title=Best value flights to St.Helena - Atlantic Star Airlines|website=Best value flights to St.Helena - Atlantic Star Airlines|access-date=27 October 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161027194421/http://www.atlanticstarairlines.com/single-post/2016/10/17/Question-raised-today-in-the-House-of-Lords|archive-date=27 October 2016|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn December 2016, the Saint Helena government issued a tender for an airline to establish a scheduled commercial service, using the less turbulent northbound landing direction only.  Atlantic Star Airlines has entered a bid on a proposed plan to base two aircraft at Saint Helena.  They would carry up to 60 passengers on round-trip flights from Saint Helena to the international airport in [[Accra#Aviation|Accra]], the capital of Ghana.<ref name=Newsweek2017/> On 5 February 2017 there was a deadline for airlines to submit application bids for the provision of air services to St Helena under the new requirements, and there were a number of bids.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sainthelena.gov.sh/air-services-to-st-helena/|title=AIR SERVICES TO ST HELENA|date=6 February 2017|access-date=15 May 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170729002529/http://www.sainthelena.gov.sh/air-services-to-st-helena/|archive-date=29 July 2017|url-status=live}}</ref>\n[[File:Airlink BAe 146-200 Volpati.jpg|thumb|An Airlink [[Avro RJ85]] flew the first charter passengers to and from St. Helena on 3 May 2017]]\nOn 3 May 2017, the first commercial charter flight with paying passengers took place. [[SA Airlink]] operated the flight from Cape Town, using an [[Avro RJ85]] aircraft with 60 passengers on board. It refueled in [[Yuri Gagarin Airport|Mo\u00e7\u00e2medes (Angola)]] when going to St Helena and in [[Hosea Kutako International Airport|Windhoek]] when going to Cape Town.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sainthelena.gov.sh/historic-arrival-of-charter-flight/|title=HISTORIC ARRIVAL OF CHARTER FLIGHT|date=3 May 2017|access-date=3 May 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170504171800/http://www.sainthelena.gov.sh/historic-arrival-of-charter-flight/|archive-date=4 May 2017|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ch-aviation.com/portal/news/55705-st-helena-sees-maiden-commercial-pax-flight|title=St. Helena sees maiden commercial pax flight|access-date=10 June 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170504124921/https://www.ch-aviation.com/portal/news/55705-st-helena-sees-maiden-commercial-pax-flight|archive-date=4 May 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> Technical problems with RMS ''St Helena'' meant that the island was isolated for at least two months, so the flight was needed.<ref>{{cite news |author=Oliver Smith |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/travel/news/st-helena-airport-first-flight-finally-lands/ |title=First flight finally lands at world's most 'useless' airport |work=Telegraph|date=8 May 2017 |access-date=25 July 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180515175500/https://www.telegraph.co.uk/travel/news/st-helena-airport-first-flight-finally-lands/ |archive-date=15 May 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nOn 9 June 2017 [[Airlink]] won the bid to operate scheduled flights to St Helena Airport.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.moneyweb.co.za/news-fast-news/sa-airlink-chosen-as-bidder-for-commercial-air-services-to-st-helena/|title=SA Airlink wins bid for commercial air services to St Helena|date=9 June 2017|access-date=10 June 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170609151204/https://www.moneyweb.co.za/news-fast-news/sa-airlink-chosen-as-bidder-for-commercial-air-services-to-st-helena/|archive-date=9 June 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> On 22 July 2017 it was announced the airline would operate weekly flights to [[Johannesburg]] via [[Hosea Kutako International Airport|Windhoek]] in [[Namibia]], with a monthly link to [[Ascension Island]]. The flights will be on [[Embraer E190]] aircraft filling a maximum of only 76 of the 99 seats due to runway limitations related to the [[wind shear]] issues.<ref name=\"sainthelena1\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.sainthelena.gov.sh/wp-content/uploads/2017/07/Air-Services-to-St-Helena-QandAs-21-July-2017.pdf |title=Archived copy |access-date=22 July 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170729002201/http://www.sainthelena.gov.sh/wp-content/uploads/2017/07/Air-Services-to-St-Helena-QandAs-21-July-2017.pdf |archive-date=29 July 2017 |url-status=dead  }}</ref><ref name=\":1\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/travel/news-and-advice/st-helena-flights-most-useless-airport-south-atlantic-johannesburg-airlink-windshear-a7858581.html|title=The world's 'most useless airport' is finally getting its first scheduled flight|date=25 July 2017|work=The Independent|access-date=27 July 2017|language=en-GB|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171122204305/http://www.independent.co.uk/travel/news-and-advice/st-helena-flights-most-useless-airport-south-atlantic-johannesburg-airlink-windshear-a7858581.html|archive-date=22 November 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> [[Airlink]] conducted a successful proving flight on 23 August 2017<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.sainthelena.gov.sh/airlink-completes-successful-proving-flight-to-st-helena/|title=AIRLINK COMPLETES SUCCESSFUL PROVING FLIGHT TO ST HELENA|date=22 August 2017|work=St Helena|access-date=14 October 2017|language=en-US|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171014133826/http://www.sainthelena.gov.sh/airlink-completes-successful-proving-flight-to-st-helena/|archive-date=14 October 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> and commenced passenger flights on 14 October 2017.<ref name=\":0\" /> The first scheduled flight landed on 14 October 2017 around 14:00 UTC without any problems, although it was slightly delayed.  The flight used the southbound direction, the one with wind shear problems, but the wind was fairly calm.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.facebook.com/photo.php?fbid=10154779647856470&set=pcb.852690421571482&type=3&theater&ifg=1|title=Tina Wagner|website=www.facebook.com}}</ref> Airlink was after some time denied letting passengers embark and disembark in Windhoek, because Airlink was not given [[Freedoms of the air#Fifth freedom|right to carry passengers between Namibia and foreign countries]]. From April 2019 Airlink refuels in [[Walvis Bay Airport|Walvis Bay]] instead, giving right to have 98 passengers because of shorter distance, having in mind that no connections are allowed in Namibia anyway.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.traveller24.com/Flights/11-seats-added-to-airlink-flight-between-jozi-and-st-helena-island-heres-why-20190306 |title=11 seats added to Airlink flight between Jozi and St Helena Island - here's why |access-date=6 March 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190306235253/https://www.traveller24.com/Flights/11-seats-added-to-airlink-flight-between-jozi-and-st-helena-island-heres-why-20190306 |archive-date=6 March 2019 |url-status=live |date=6 March 2019 }}</ref> The flights still (2019) stop in Windhoek or Walvis Bay for refuel westbound, but fly nonstop to Johannesburg if there is not too much upwind.<ref name=traffic-rights-scuttle>{{Cite web |url=https://www.ch-aviation.com/portal/news/64402-traffic-rights-scuttle-airlinks-cape-town-st-helena-plans |title=Traffic rights scuttle Airlink's Cape Town-St Helena plans |access-date=13 February 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180214142135/https://www.ch-aviation.com/portal/news/64402-traffic-rights-scuttle-airlinks-cape-town-st-helena-plans |archive-date=14 February 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nOn Saturday 18 November 2017 [[Airlink]] started a monthly charter operation to [[RAF Ascension Island|Ascension Island]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.ascension-island.gov.ac/government/travel-shipping/flights/airlink/|title=Airlink|date=5 October 2017|work=Ascension Island Government|access-date=28 January 2018|language=en-GB|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171014183603/http://www.ascension-island.gov.ac/government/travel-shipping/flights/airlink/|archive-date=14 October 2017|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nAfter half a year of operation it was found that the regularity was better than expected with only one day of flights delayed until another day, and that ticket demand was higher than expected.<ref>{{Cite web | url=https://www.airlineratings.com/news/remote-st-helena-airport-shrugs-off-worlds-useless-tag/ | title=Remote St Helena airport shrugs off 'world's most useless' tag| date=27 April 2018}}</ref> The government announced in May 2018 that a second weekly flight will be performed during the southern summer season of December 2018 to April 2019, as well as two more flights to Ascension during the Christmas/New year period.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.sainthelena.gov.sh/additional-flights-to-st-helena-and-ascension/ |title=ADDITIONAL FLIGHTS TO ST HELENA AND ASCENSION |access-date=6 May 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180507003455/http://www.sainthelena.gov.sh/additional-flights-to-st-helena-and-ascension/ |archive-date=7 May 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref> During December 2019 to February 2020 flights went to and from Cape Town, the traditional link to Saint Helena during the boat era.<ref>[https://edition.cnn.com/travel/article/saint-helena-atlantic-us-flights/index.html New flights open up Napoleon's hidden Atlantic island to international visitors]</ref>\n\nThe southern autumn and winter means higher challenges with low clouds and stormy weather. The flights planned for 14 July 2018 were delayed a full week because of weather,<ref>[http://www.sainthelena.gov.sh/airlink-flight-postponed/ AIRLINK FLIGHT POSTPONED](sainthelena.gov.sh) or {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180717212708/http://www.sainthelena.gov.sh/airlink-flight-postponed/ |date=17 July 2018 }} (webcache.googleusercontent.com)</ref> and the schedule of August 2018 was also heavily disrupted.\n\nBeginning March 2020, only residents, citizens or other permitted people were allowed to enter the island, due to the [[COVID-19]] pandemic, and all had to stay isolated for two weeks.<ref>[http://sthelenaairport.com/news/new-restrictions-entry-air-st-helena-17-march-2020/ New restrictions on entry by air to St Helena - 17 March 2020]</ref> This and restrictions in South Africa caused cancellation of all flights to Saint Helena and Ascension from 25 March to at least 18 April.<ref>https://simpleflying.com/st-helena-cut-off/?fbclid=IwAR2MpfwuAUdwQqtwxAPuuRR6DYQnhEERKrrBpkc1LCyd3TAZSfnEl9_oBuo St Helena Cut Off From The World As Flights Grounded]</ref> The M/V Helena freight ship still goes and [[Medical evacuation|medical air evacuation]] is also possible.\n\n==Airlines and destinations==\n{{Airport-dest-list\n|[[Airlink]] | [[O. R. Tambo International Airport|Johannesburg\u2013O.R. Tambo]]<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.routesonline.com/news/38/airlineroute/278625/sa-airlink-plans-st-helena-service-increase-in-nw18/ |title=SA Airlink plans St. Helena service increase in NW18 |access-date=15 May 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180515191441/https://www.routesonline.com/news/38/airlineroute/278625/sa-airlink-plans-st-helena-service-increase-in-nw18/ |archive-date=15 May 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref><br/>'''Seasonal:''' [[Cape Town International Airport|Cape Town]]<ref>https://edition.cnn.com/travel/article/saint-helena-atlantic-us-flights/index.html</ref> <br/>'''Charter:''' [[RAF Ascension Island|Ascension Island]]<ref name=\"ascension-island.gov.ac\">{{cite web|title=Airlink-Ascension Island Government|url=http://www.ascension-island.gov.ac/government/travel-shipping/flights/airlink/|website=Ascension Island Government|access-date=15 October 2017|date=5 October 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171014183603/http://www.ascension-island.gov.ac/government/travel-shipping/flights/airlink/|archive-date=14 October 2017|url-status=live}}</ref>\n}}\n\n==Aerodrome characteristics, equipment and facilities==\n{{Location mark\n| type = thumb\n| image = Saint Helena Airport location.svg\n | caption =Location of the airport on St Helena\n| width=240\n| label=\n| label-size=90\n| background = #DDDD44\n| position=bottom\n| y%  = 50.00\n| x% = 80\n| mark=Cercle rouge 50%.svg\n| mark_width=40\n| float=right\n}}\nThe airport has been built on [[Prosperous Bay Plain]], on the east side of Saint Helena, entailing a concrete runway length of {{convert|1950|m|ft|0}}<ref name=\"atnsDL\">{{cite web|url=http://www.atns.com/downloads/FHSH%20AD%202-13.pdf|title=FHSH 2-15|access-date=13 January 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170116160048/http://www.atns.com/downloads/FHSH%20AD%202-13.pdf|archive-date=16 January 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> with taxiway and apron, an approximately {{convert|8|e6m3|abbr=off|adj=on}} rockfill embankment through which a {{convert|750|m|ft|adj=on}} long reinforced concrete culvert was proposed but contractor Basil Read got approval to use an open channel instead. This was approved by the St Helena Government, together with an airport terminal building of {{convert|3500|m2}} and support infrastructure, air traffic control and safety, bulk fuel installation for {{convert|6|e6l|e6impgal+e6usgal|abbr=off|spell=in}} of diesel and aviation fuel, a {{convert|14|km|mi|0|adj=on}} airport access road from Rupert's Bay to the airport, and all related logistics.<ref name=\"basilread.co.za\">[http://www.basilread.co.za/basil-read-awarded-contract-to-construct-airpor-on-st-helena-island/ \"''Basil Read awarded contract to construct airport on St Helena Island''\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120117034017/http://www.basilread.co.za/basil-read-awarded-contract-to-construct-airpor-on-st-helena-island/ |date=17 January 2012 }} Basil Read company website, 4 November 2011, retrieved 2011-DEC-24</ref> The airport has a LDA (landing distance available) of {{convert|1535|m|ft|0}} for the northbound runway direction (02) and {{convert|1550|m|ft|0}} for the wind shear-affected southbound runway direction (20).<ref name=\"atnsDL\"/>\n\n===Aircraft compatibility===\nThe airport by design can accommodate up to two<ref>[http://www.sainthelenaaccess.com/application/documents/Application-Drawings/5048976-CI-01-1001.pdf \"''Application Drawings, CI-01-1001 \u2013 General Runway Layout''\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120426081338/http://www.sainthelenaaccess.com/application/documents/Application-Drawings/5048976-CI-01-1001.pdf |date=26 April 2012 }} Airport Development Application, 2004</ref> twin-engined passenger aircraft up to the size of the [[Airbus A319]], [[Boeing 737]], and the [[Boeing 757-200]]. Following a decision to build a shorter runway of 1,550 metres the planned use of [[Boeing 737-824|Boeing 737-800]] aircraft had been ruled out. Instead the airport was to be designed to receive [[Boeing 737-76N|Boeing 737-700]] aircraft.<ref>{{cite news | last = Olsson | first = Mikael | title = Editorial | page = 2 | newspaper = The St Helena Independent | location = Jamestown | volume = VII | issue = 10 | date = 20 January 2012 | url = http://www.independent.co.sh/20120120.pdf | access-date = 21 January 2012 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20120504074246/http://www.independent.co.sh/20120120.pdf | archive-date = 4 May 2012 | url-status = dead | df = dmy-all }}</ref> However, on 17 July 2012, the St Helena Government and Basil Read agreed to a change to the runway design, which including widening the embankment over an additional {{convert|40|m|ft}} at the southern end, paving an additional {{convert|100|m|ft}} of the runway with concrete, providing larger turning circles at the runway ends, and increasing the size of the [[Airport apron|apron]].<ref name=\"SHG_23072012\">{{cite web |url=http://www.sainthelenaaccess.com/news/wp-content/uploads/2012/08/St-Helena-Airport-update-No13.pdf |title=FIRST PROJECT VARIATION ORDER SIGNED \u2013 Additional Runway Works to Allow for Future Expansion |publisher=St Helena Government Access Office |date=23 July 2012 |work=press release |issue=13 |access-date=7 August 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130418061504/http://www.sainthelenaaccess.com/news/wp-content/uploads/2012/08/St-Helena-Airport-update-No13.pdf |archive-date=18 April 2013 |url-status=dead  }}</ref> As a result of [[wind shear]] issues discovered during commissioning of the airport, and the resulting need to land with a [[tailwind]], even further restrictions on the aircraft have been shown to be needed.  [[Airlink]] decided to use a Brazilian [[Embraer E190]] which is more compatible than larger aircraft with tailwind landings. However it still cannot use the full seat and cargo capacity.<ref name=\"sainthelena1\" /><ref name=\":1\" />\n\nIn contrast to the 2011 reference design for the airport it would now have a full {{convert|240|m|ft|adj=on}} [[Runway safety area|runway end safety area]] (RESA) at the southern end of the runway instead of the planned [[Engineered materials arrestor system|engineered materials arresting system]] (EMAS). The intention was to add an EMAS designed for Boeing 737-800 later butting onto the southern end of the paved runway to increase the declarable [[Landing Distance Available|landing distance available]] (LDA) to {{convert|1650|m|ft}},<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.sainthelenaaccess.com/news/wp-content/uploads/2012/08/St-Helena-Airport-update-No-13.pdf |title=St Helena Airport Update |issue=13 |date=12 July 2012 |author=St Helena Government |access-date=18 June 2012 |work=press release |publisher=St Helena Government |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140104204019/http://www.sainthelenaaccess.com/news/wp-content/uploads/2012/08/St-Helena-Airport-update-No-13.pdf |archive-date=4 January 2014 |url-status=dead  }}</ref> to allow the operation of larger aircraft such as the [[Boeing 737-824|Boeing 737-800]] and [[Airbus A320 family|Airbus A320]].<ref name=\"SHG_23072012\"/><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.sainthelena.gov.sh/news.php/624/additional-runway-works-to-allow-for-future-expansion |archive-url=https://archive.is/20121224214715/http://www.sainthelena.gov.sh/news.php/624/additional-runway-works-to-allow-for-future-expansion |url-status=dead |archive-date=24 December 2012 |title=Additional runway works to allow for future expansion |author=St Helena Government |date=23 July 2012 |work=press release |publisher=St Helena Government |access-date=24 July 2012 }}</ref>\n\nThe additional earthworks and concrete increased duration of construction by 12 weeks so works were expected to be completed by 25 February 2016.<ref name=\"SHG_23072012\"/> Extending the embankment once the airport was operational would have involved prohibitive costs as heavy equipment would have needed to be brought back to the island and huge quantities of rock from another site to be moved, while material excavated from Prosperous Bay Plain was used to fill Dry Gut.<ref name=\"SHG_23072012\"/>\n\nIn June 2013 the St Helena government announced it was again assessing changes to the design of the runway to cater for operations of a wider range of aircraft, in particular the [[Lockheed C-130 Hercules]] and the [[Boeing 757|Boeing 757-200]], the latter enabling direct flights to Europe, crucial for the island's tourism plans.<ref>{{cite news | last = Pipe | first = Simon | title = Doubt over eco-resort as Shelco seeks direct flights to Europe | newspaper = St Helena Online | location = Jamestown | date = 8 November 2012 | url = http://sthelenaonline.org/2012/11/08/doubt-over-eco-resort-as-shelco-seeks-direct-flights-to-europe/ | url-status = dead | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20131029193329/http://sthelenaonline.org/2012/11/08/doubt-over-eco-resort-as-shelco-seeks-direct-flights-to-europe/ | archive-date = 29 October 2013 | df = dmy-all }}</ref><ref name=\"SHO20130614\">{{cite news | last = Pipe | first = Simon | title = No flights from London? Woah, I'm going to Barbados\u2026 | newspaper = St Helena Online | location = Jamestown | date = 14 June 2013 | url = http://sthelenaonline.org/2013/06/14/no-flights-from-london-woah-im-going-to-barbados// | url-status = dead | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20131030032342/http://sthelenaonline.org/2013/06/14/no-flights-from-london-woah-im-going-to-barbados/ | archive-date = 30 October 2013 | df = dmy-all }}</ref> These are Code D aircraft requiring the addition of shoulders along both sides of the runway, a wider taxiway and apron, and a higher fire fighting capacity (ICAO rescue fire fighting service category 7).<ref name=\"SHG20130613\">{{cite news | title = Design Changes | page = 2 | newspaper = St Helena Airport Update | location = Jamestown | issue = 31 | date = 13 June 2013 | url = http://www.brshap.co.za/press/Issues/St%20Helena%20Airport%20update%20-%20No%2031.pdf | access-date = 17 June 2013 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20140104210812/http://www.brshap.co.za/press/Issues/St%20Helena%20Airport%20update%20-%20No%2031.pdf | archive-date = 4 January 2014 | url-status = live }}</ref>\n\nIn October 2013 a formal agreement was signed for the proposed design changes.<ref name=\"SHI20131206\">{{cite news | last = Olsson | first = Mikael | title = Editorial | page = 3 | newspaper = The St Helena Independent | location = Jamestown | volume = IX | issue = 1 | date = 6 December 2013 | url = http://www.saint.fm/wp-content/uploads/2013/12/20131206.pdf }}{{dead link|date=April 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> These enhancements will also make it possible for the [[Lockheed C-130 Hercules]] to operate to and from St Helena, though the runway is unlikely to be able to accommodate larger Code D aircraft, such as the [[Boeing 767]].<ref name=\"SHI20131206\" />\nThe upgrade was to be funded from cost savings on other parts of the project,<ref name=\"SHO20130614\" /> particularly by a simplified runway drainage system.<ref name=\"SHG20130613\" />\n\n===Facilities===\nThere are two main buildings,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.sainthelenaaccess.com/news/faqs/ |title=Frequently Asked Questions : Saint Helena Airport Project |publisher=Sainthelenaaccess.com |date=10 May 2016 |access-date=25 July 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170725045440/http://www.sainthelenaaccess.com/news/faqs/ |archive-date=25 July 2017 |url-status=dead  }}</ref> the terminal building, and the combined building for airport operations, e.g. air traffic control, rescue services, etc. In addition there are some smaller buildings. The terminal building has a caf\u00e9, a gift shop, a [[duty-free shop]] and a restaurant.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sainthelenaaccess.com/news/wp-content/uploads/2016/05/150505_No-73.pdf|title=First Operational Trial at St Helena Airport|access-date=20 May 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160603004730/http://www.sainthelenaaccess.com/news/wp-content/uploads/2016/05/150505_No-73.pdf|archive-date=3 June 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n===Navigation aids===\n[[File:St Helena Airport DVOR.png|thumb|Doppler VHF Omni-directional Radio Range system at St Helena Airport.]]\nThe distance from key destinations, the length of runway available, and the type of aircraft available in the region dictate that air services to St Helena must operate to the requirements of extended twin engine operations ([[ETOPS]]) which implies the provision of an instrument approach system based on an off-set [[Instrument landing system|instrument landing system localiser]] (ILS LLZ).<ref>[http://webarchive.nationalarchives.gov.uk/20090422165233/http://www.dfid.gov.uk/pubs/files/st-helena-proj-memo.pdf St Helena Access, Project Memorandum] Overseas Territories Department, Department for International Development (DFID), January 2005, p. B-6</ref><ref name=\"sainthelenaaccess.com\">[http://www.sainthelenaaccess.com/application/documents/Feasibility/01_Main_Report_Final.pdf \"''St Helena Access Feasibility Study''\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120426081359/http://www.sainthelenaaccess.com/application/documents/Feasibility/01_Main_Report_Final.pdf |date=26 April 2012 }} St Helena Government, Department for International Development, January 2005, p. 104</ref>\n\nSuch is also required by the terrain of the airport which, in commercial passenger air transport terms, is safety-critical due to its steep approaches, high elevation ({{convert|1000|ft|m|abbr=on|disp=or}} above sea level)<ref>[http://www.sainthelenaaccess.com/application/documents/Feasibility/01_Main_Report_Final.pdf \"''St Helena Access Feasibility Study''\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120426081359/http://www.sainthelenaaccess.com/application/documents/Feasibility/01_Main_Report_Final.pdf |date=26 April 2012 }} St Helena Government, Department for International Development, January 2005, p. 13</ref> and rocky outcrops. Without an instrument approach the provision of a viable air service would be considered impossible.<ref>[http://www.sainthelenaaccess.com/application/documents/Feasibility/01_Main_Report_Final.pdf \"''St Helena Access Feasibility Study''\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120426081359/http://www.sainthelenaaccess.com/application/documents/Feasibility/01_Main_Report_Final.pdf |date=26 April 2012 }} St Helena Government, Department for International Development, January 2005, p. 317</ref>\n\nBecause of the above, St Helena Airport was equipped with an [[instrument landing system]] (ILS) and a Doppler VHF Omni-directional Radio Range system ([[DVOR]]) supplied by [[Thales Group]].<ref name=\"thales\">{{cite web |url=http://www.thalesgroup.com/Press_Releases/Countries/United_Kingdom/2012/121107_Thales_wins_navigation_contract_for_St_Helena_Island%E2%80%99s_first_airport/ |title=Thales wins navigation contract for St Helena Island's first airport |publisher=Thales Group |work=press release |date=7 November 2012 |access-date=9 November 2012 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121122003132/http://www.thalesgroup.com/Press_Releases/Countries/United_Kingdom/2012/121107_Thales_wins_navigation_contract_for_St_Helena_Island%E2%80%99s_first_airport/ |archive-date=22 November 2012  }}</ref> Further to that [[Honeywell Aerospace]] supplied a ''SmartPath'' [[ground-based augmentation system]] (GBAS), a technology that augments [[Global Positioning System|global positioning system]] (GPS) signals to make them suitable for precision approach and landing. It overcomes many of the limitations of [[instrument landing system]]s (ILS) traditionally used by airports to guide aircraft as they approach the runway.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://aerospace.honeywell.com/about/media-resources/newsroom/honeywell-to-provide-aircraft-landing-assurance-at-st-helena-airport#sthash.T8oGLCNq.dpuf |title=Honeywell to provide aircraft landing assurance at St Helena's first airport |date=3 April 2014 |publisher=Honeywell International Inc. |work=press release |access-date=11 May 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150406142720/https://aerospace.honeywell.com/about/media-resources/newsroom/honeywell-to-provide-aircraft-landing-assurance-at-st-helena-airport#sthash.T8oGLCNq.dpuf |archive-date=6 April 2015 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[Transport on Saint Helena]]\n*[[Economy of Saint Helena]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em|refs=\n\n<ref name=\"aip_fhsh_adc\">{{cite web|title=Aerdrome Chart \u2013 ICAO: St Helena. St Helena Airport|url=http://www.atns.com/downloads/FHSH%20AD%202-11.pdf|website=AIP Saint Helena|access-date=6 April 2016|date=28 April 2016|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160616084743/http://www.atns.com/downloads/FHSH%20AD%202-11.pdf|archive-date=16 June 2016}}</ref>\n\n}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category-inline|Saint Helena Airport}}\n* [http://flytosthelenaairport.com/ Saint Helena Access official website]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20060712090648/http://www.shelco.sh/ Shelco website]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20090326173143/http://www.dfid.gov.uk/pubs/files/st-helena-proj-memo.pdf  DFID Website on air access]\n* [https://www.google.com/maps/contrib/105239076880675861601/photos Photospheres from inside the terminal] (Google maps)\n{{Saint Helena, Ascension and Tristan da Cunha}}\n{{Airports in the United Kingdom and the British Crown Dependencies}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Airports in Saint Helena]]\n[[Category:Airports established in 2016]]\n[[Category:2016 establishments in Africa]]\n", "name_user": "46.69.115.148", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Saint_Helena_Airport"}
{"title_page": "C. L. Max Nikias", "text_new": "{{Use mdy dates|date=August 2019}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| image = C. L. Max Nikias.jpg\n| alt = C.L. Max Nikias (cropped)\n| order = 11th\n| office = President of the University of Southern California\n| term_start = August 3, 2010\n| term_end = August 7, 2018\n| predecessor = [[Steven Sample]]\n| successor = [[Carol Folt]]\n| birth_name = Chrysostomos Loizos Nikias\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1952|09|30}}\n| birth_place = [[Komi Kebir]], [[Cyprus]]\n| death_date = \n| death_place = \n| alma_mater = [[National Technical University of Athens]], [[University at Buffalo]]\n| residence = \n| profession = [[Electrical engineering]], Higher education, [[Academic administration]]\n| spouse = {{marriage|Niki|1977}}\n| children = 2 daughters\n}}\n\n'''Chrysostomos Loizos \"Max\" Nikias''' ({{lang-el|\u03a7\u03c1\u03c5\u03c3\u03cc\u03c3\u03c4\u03bf\u03bc\u03bf\u03c2 \u039b\u03bf\u0390\u03b6\u03bf\u03c2 \u039d\u03b9\u03ba\u03af\u03b1\u03c2}}; born September 30, 1952) is a Cypriot-American academic, and served as the 11th [[University of Southern California]] president, a position he held from August 3, 2010,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://uscnews.usc.edu/university/c_l_max_nikias_named_11th_president_of_usc.html|title=C. L. Max Nikias Named 11th President of USC|date=March 11, 2010|publisher=USC News|accessdate=September 20, 2010|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100923014604/http://uscnews.usc.edu/university/c_l_max_nikias_named_11th_president_of_usc.html|archive-date=September 23, 2010|url-status=dead}}</ref> to August 7, 2018.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://boardoftrustees.usc.edu/message-from-board-of-trustees-chairman-rick-j-caruso-august-7-2018/|title=Message from Board of Trustees Chairman Rick J. Caruso (August 7, 2018) - Board of Trustees - USC|website=boardoftrustees.usc.edu|accessdate=August 7, 2018}}</ref> He holds the Malcolm R. Currie Chair in Technology and the Humanities and is president [[emeritus]] of the university.<ref name=\"transition\">{{cite web |url=http://universityofsoutherncalifornia.createsend1.com/t/ViewEmail/j/C9A2A4FDE384E2D72540EF23F30FEDED|title=Nikias transitions to president emeritus|date=August 7, 2018}}</ref> He had been at USC since 1991, as a professor, director of national research centers, [[dean (education)|dean]], [[provost (education)|provost]], and president. He holds faculty appointments in both electrical engineering and the classics{{Clarify|reason=Which classics?|date=August 2018}}, and teaches an undergraduate course on the culture of [[Athenian democracy]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.latimes.com/local/education/la-me-nikias-class-20160419-story.html |title=USC president's aim in teaching a classics course is to 'light a fire' for humanities|date=May 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn May 2018, 200 tenured USC professors demanded Nikias's resignation for how his administration dealt with nearly 300 incidents of sexual assault and sexual misconduct allegations against a longtime student health center gynecologist, [[George Tyndall]].<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/hundreds-of-usc-professors-call-for-presidents-ouster-1527024102|title=Hundreds of USC Professors Call for President's Ouster|last=Korn|first=Melissa|date=May 22, 2018|work=Wall Street Journal|access-date=May 23, 2018 |language=en-US |issn=0099-9660}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/05/22/us/usc-faculty-president-nikias.html |title=200 Professors Call for Ouster of U.S.C. President, Citing Lack of 'Moral Authority'|date=May 22, 2018|work=The New York Times |access-date=May 23, 2018|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/05/17/us/USC-gynecologist-young-women.html|title='Just the Grossest Thing': Women Recall Interactions With U.S.C. Doctor|date=May 17, 2018|work=The New York Times |access-date=May 23, 2018|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> He and the board of trustees agreed to an orderly transition to a new president on May 25, 2018, and he stepped down on August 7, 2018.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.insidehighered.com/news/2018/05/29/usc-president-will-step-down|title=USC president will step down|access-date=June 6, 2018|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/05/25/us/usc-nikias-tyndall.html|title=U.S.C. President Agrees to Step Down Over Scandal Involving Gynecologist|date=May 25, 2018|work=The New York Times|access-date=June 6, 2018|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> Following this, Nikias was named president emeritus and a life trustee of the university.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://alumni.usc.edu/wp-content/uploads/2018/08/BoTChair-Communication-080718.pdf |title=BoT Chair Communication 080718 |publisher=University of Southern California |year=2018 |accessdate=August 7, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Early life==\nNikias was born on the Mediterranean island of [[Cyprus]].<ref name=\"Nikias profile\">{{cite news |url=http://articles.latimes.com/2010/mar/12/local/la-me-usc-biobox12-2010mar12|title=Profile of USC's next president|date=March 12, 2010 |work=Los Angeles Times|accessdate=July 21, 2010}}</ref> There, he graduated with honors from the Famagusta Gymnasium, a school that emphasizes sciences, history, and Greco-Roman classics. He married his wife, Niki, in 1977,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.usc.edu/dept/pubrel/trojan_family/winter03/eng-3.html|title=The Climb of His Life|year=2003|publisher=Trojan Family Magazine|accessdate=April 23, 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131002131741/http://www.usc.edu/dept/pubrel/trojan_family/winter03/eng-3.html#|archive-date=October 2, 2013|url-status=dead}}</ref> and the couple have two daughters, Georgiana and Maria.<ref name=\"Nikias profile\"/> He received a degree in electrical and mechanical engineering from the [[National Technical University of Athens]] in 1977, and has an academic interest in Athenian drama and democracy.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.president.usc.edu/bio/|title=C. L. Max Nikias Biography|publisher=usc.edu|accessdate=April 23, 2013}}</ref> Nikias earned a master's degree in 1980 and a Ph.D in 1982 in electrical engineering at the [[University at Buffalo, The State University of New York|State University of New York at Buffalo]].<ref>{{cite thesis |last=Nikias |first= Chrysostomos Loizos|date= 1982|title= A new class of robust spectral estimation algorithms based on minimum covariance recursion error and their application in cardiac data analysis |degree=Ph.D. |publisher= State University of New York at Buffalo |url=http://dl.acm.org/citation.cfm?id=910320|access-date=August 21, 2016}}</ref> His predecessor as USC president, [[Steven Sample]], was likewise an electrical engineer, and served as president of SUNY-Buffalo from 1982 to 1991.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://about.usc.edu/presidentemeritus/|title=About USC \u2013 President Emeritus|accessdate=September 27, 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131002132554/http://about.usc.edu/presidentemeritus/|archive-date=October 2, 2013|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\n\n===Associate Dean and Center Director in the USC Viterbi School of Engineering (1991\u20132001)===\nNikias served as founding director of the school's Integrated Media Systems Center (IMSC) from 1996 to 2001. He led the engineering school's effort to secure the center in an intense national competition conducted by the National Science Foundation that included 116 other proposals. Nikias served as associate dean of the engineering school from 1992 to 2001. While his research work has ranged from signal processing and biomedical engineering to digital communications and military radar and sonar, he is best known for his understanding of multimedia's defining place in the future of the internet and the IMSC.\n\n===Dean of the USC Viterbi School of Engineering (2001\u20132005)===\nFrom 2001 to 2005, Nikias served as dean of the [[USC Viterbi School of Engineering]], solidifying its position as a top-tier engineering school. He directed the expansion of the school's biomedical engineering enterprise and developed its distance-learning program into one of the largest in the country at that time. He oversaw the development of the school's Tutor Hall of Engineering. He also established key partnerships with corporations, among them [[Pratt & Whitney]], [[Airbus]], [[Boeing]], [[Chevron Corporation|Chevron]], and [[Northrop Grumman]], and led a fundraising campaign that brought in more than $250 million, capped by a $52 million school-naming gift from [[Andrew Viterbi|Andrew and Erna Viterbi]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://viterbi.usc.edu/about/viterbi/viterbi_press_release.htm|title=Cell phone pioneer endows Viterbi School of Engineering |publisher=viterbi.usc.edu|accessdate=April 5, 2012}}</ref> Nikias was instrumental in supporting the Information Sciences Institute in the USC Viterbi School, and in working with faculty across the university to establish two National Science Foundation (NSF) Engineering Research Centers (ERC), as well as the Department of Homeland Security's first Research Center of Excellence at USC.\n\n===USC provost (2005\u20132010)===\nFrom June 2005 to August 2010, Nikias served as USC's provost and chief academic officer. He was instrumental in bringing USC trustee [[Steven Spielberg|Steven Spielberg's]] [[USC Shoah Foundation Institute for Visual History and Education|Shoah Foundation Institute]] and its vast video archive of 55,000 testimonies of [[The Holocaust|Holocaust]] survivors to USC.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.usc.edu/uscnews/stories/11601.html|title=USC College to House Shoah Foundation|date=September 10, 2005|publisher=usc.edu|accessdate=April 5, 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111126115711/http://www.usc.edu/uscnews/stories/11601.html|archive-date=November 26, 2011|url-status=dead}}</ref> Nikias also established the university's Edward R. Roybal Institute on Aging, Stevens Center for Innovation, [http://china.usc.edu U.S.-China Institute],<ref>[http://china.usc.edu/ShowArticle.aspx?articleID=204 Nikias announcement] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140714163127/http://china.usc.edu/ShowArticle.aspx?articleID=204# |date=July 14, 2014 }} of the creation of the USC U.S.-China Institute; [http://china.usc.edu/ShowArticle.aspx?articleID=61 Nikias introductory remarks] at inaugural USC U.S.-China Institute conference.</ref> and Levan Institute for Humanities and Ethics. He launched [https://web.archive.org/web/20100620185435/http://www.usc.edu/dept/pubrel/visionsandvoices/ Visions and Voices], USC's campus-wide arts and humanities initiative, as well as a grant program to advance scholarship in the [[humanities]] and [[social science]]s.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.usc.edu/dept/pubrel/visionsandvoices/about.php|title=Visions and Voices: The Arts and Humanities Initiative|publisher=usc.edu|accessdate=September 20, 2010|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100826150957/http://www.usc.edu/dept/pubrel/visionsandvoices/about.php#|archive-date=August 26, 2010|url-status=dead}}</ref> Nikias spearheaded the integration of the [[Keck School of Medicine of USC]]'s faculty practice plans, oversaw the transfer of [[Los Angeles County+USC Medical Center|University Hospital]] and [[USC Norris Comprehensive Cancer Center|USC Norris Cancer Hospital]] from [[Tenet Healthcare Corporation]] to the university, and recruited a new leadership team for USC's medical enterprise.\n\n===USC president (2010\u20132018)===\nAs president, Nikias wrote frequently about a range of nationally significant topics, including the value of\u2014and access to\u2014higher education;<ref>{{cite web|url=https://agenda.weforum.org/2015/01/what-will-the-future-of-education-look-like/|title=What will the future of education look like?|date=January 24, 2015|publisher=World Economic Forum|accessdate=June 18, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/opinions/why-elite-universities-should-admit-more-community-college-grads/2014/10/23/b4dda968-4986-11e4-a046-120a8a855cca_story.html|title=Why elite universities should admit more community college grads|date=October 23, 2014 |work=Washington Post|accessdate=June 18, 2015}}</ref> the future of online education;<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.president.usc.edu/online-education-revolution-hype-reality/|title=Online Education Revolution \u2013 Hype and Reality|date=October 15, 2013|publisher=usc.edu|accessdate=June 18, 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150618203420/http://www.president.usc.edu/online-education-revolution-hype-reality/|archive-date=June 18, 2015|url-status=dead}}</ref> the continued importance of the arts and humanities; the art of leadership through the classics; and the role of elite research universities, particularly as economic drivers.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.president.usc.edu/all-roads-lead-to-southern-california-2012/|title=All Roads Lead to Southern California|date=March 21, 2012|publisher=usc.edu|accessdate=June 18, 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150618203423/http://www.president.usc.edu/all-roads-lead-to-southern-california-2012/|archive-date=June 18, 2015|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nIn 2011, Nikias announced a $6 billion fundraising campaign, which\u2014at the time of its launch\u2014was the largest in the history of higher education.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://articles.latimes.com/2011/aug/28/local/la-me-usc-funds-20110828|title=USC to pursue record-breaking donation total|date=August 28, 2011|work=Los Angeles Times|accessdate=June 18, 2015}}</ref> In six and a half years, USC's campaign has already surpassed the $6 billion mark\u201418 months ahead of schedule\u2014bringing to the university, on the average, $900 million per year. The fundraising campaign has been extended for five more years until 2021.<ref>{{cite web|title=USC Is Raising Money So Fast, It Just Moved the Goalpost|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/usc-is-raising-money-so-fast-it-just-moved-the-goalpost-1487190600|accessdate=May 2, 2017}}</ref> ''The Chronicle of Higher Education'' has called Nikias a \"prodigious fundraiser.\"<ref>{{cite journal|url=http://chronicle.com/article/As-Its-Popular-President/64532/|title=As Its Popular President Retires, USC Eyes An Encore |date=March 7, 2010|journal=The Chronicle of Higher Education|accessdate=April 5, 2012|last1=Keller |first1=Josh }}</ref>\n\nNikias brought the nation's largest literary festival, the [[Los Angeles Times Festival of Books|''Los Angeles Times'' Festival of Books]], to USC.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://articles.latimes.com/2010/sep/23/local/la-me-0923-book-festival-20100923|title=Times Festival of Books will move to USC|date=September 23, 2010|work=Los Angeles Times|accessdate=June 18, 2015}}</ref> In addition, under his leadership, the university embarked on a major capital construction initiative that already includes Wallis Annenberg Hall for [[USC Annenberg School for Communication and Journalism|journalism]], the [[USC Michelson Center for Convergent Bioscience]], Dauterive Hall for social sciences, Fertitta Hall for business, the Kaufman International Dance Center, the McKay Center for athletics, Uytengsu Aquatics Center, the Engemann Student Health Center, a new [[USC School of Cinematic Arts|Cinematic Arts]] building, and the University Club at Stoops, as well as the Soto Building, Currie Residential Hall,<ref>{{cite web |url=https://news.usc.edu/103561/uscs-health-sciences-campus-getting-major-revamp/|title=Health Sciences Campus getting major revamp|date=July 5, 2016}}</ref> and Norris Consultation Center on the [[Campus of the University of Southern California#Health Sciences Campus|Health Sciences Campus]], and beautification projects for both of USC's campuses. The most prominent project, though, is the USC Village, a 1.3 million square-foot center of student residential colleges, that opened in 2017, entirely reimagining the university's landscape.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.latimes.com/local/education/la-me-usc-village-20140915-story.html|title=USC unveiling plans for $650-million housing, retail complex|date=September 15, 2014|work=Los Angeles Times|accessdate=June 18, 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn recognition of his efforts to renew USC's [[USC Trojans|athletic heritage]], ''The New York Times'' selected Nikias as one of a small number of national figures \"who make sports' little corner of the world a better place.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2010/11/25/sports/25anderson.html?_r=0|title=Moments to Savor from the Sports World|date=November 24, 2010 |work=The New York Times|accessdate=April 5, 2012}}</ref>\n\n===Research===\nOver his two-decade career as an active scholar, Nikias gained acclaim for his research in the fields of digital signal processing and communications, digital media systems, and [[biomedicine]]. Some of his other research interests have included [[radar]] and [[sonar]] technologies.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://ee.usc.edu/faculty_staff/faculty_directory/nikias.htm|title=USC Ming Hsieh Department of Electrical Engineering: Chrysostomos L. Nikias|publisher=ee.usc.edu|accessdate=September 20, 2010}}</ref> He has consulted with corporations and the [[federal government of the United States|U.S. government]]. He is the author of more than 275 journal articles and conference papers, three textbooks, and eight patents.\n\n== Transition ==\nIn May 2018, Nikias and the USC board of trustees agreed to an orderly transition to a new president, following a sex abuse scandal regarding USC's student health center's gynecologist and questions{{From whom?|date=August 2018}} about how the university handled it.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.insidehighered.com/news/2018/05/29/usc-president-will-step-down |title=USC president will step down|publisher=|accessdate=June 2, 2018}}</ref>\n\nOver 200 tenured USC professors called for the resignation of Nikias, saying that he had \"lost the moral authority to lead.\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/hundreds-of-usc-professors-call-for-presidents-ouster-1527024102|title=Hundreds of USC Professors Call for President's Ouster|last=Korn|first=Melissa|date=May 22, 2018|work=Wall Street Journal|access-date=May 22, 2018 |language=en-US|issn=0099-9660}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.latimes.com/local/lanow/la-me-ln-usc-faculty-petition-nikias-20180522-story.html|title=200 USC professors demand Nikias step down; trustees express 'full confidence' in president |last=Hamilton |first=Harriet Ryan, Sarah Parvini, Matt|website=latimes.com|access-date=May 22, 2018|date=May 22, 2018 }}</ref> There were concerns over how the university dealt with sexual misconduct allegations against a longtime student health center gynecologist George Tyndall.<ref name=\"LAT 2018-12-12\">{{cite news|url=https://www.latimes.com/local/lanow/la-me-ln-usc-business-school-dean-trustees-20181212-story.html|title=USC trustees back president's ouster of business school dean over handling of harassment cases|newspaper=[[Los Angeles Times]]|first1=Harriet |last1=Ryan|first2=Matt|last2=Hamilton|date=December 13, 2018|access-date=December 16, 2018}}</ref> The allegations are that for decades, Tyndall conducted improper pelvic exams on female students, especially students from [[China]], many of whom were seeing a gynecologist for the first time, and made sexually and racially inappropriate comments.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/05/17/us/USC-gynecologist-young-women.html|title='Just the Grossest Thing': Women Recall Interactions With U.S.C. Doctor|access-date=May 22, 2018|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.scmp.com/news/world/united-states-canada/article/3011851/secret-files-dr-george-tyndall-gynaecologist-usc|title=Secret files on doctor who 'preyed on young Asian students'|date=2019-05-26|website=South China Morning Post|language=en|access-date=2019-10-06}}</ref> \n\nIn a letter to USC's Board of Trustees, a group of faculty members wrote that they had come together to \"express our outrage and disappointment over the mounting evidence of President Nikias' failure to protect our students, our staff, and our colleagues from repeated and pervasive sexual harassment and misconduct.\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://ktla.com/2018/05/22/faculty-members-call-for-usc-president-to-step-down-in-wake-of-gynecologist-scandal/ |title=Faculty Members Call for USC President to Step Down in Wake of Gynecologist Scandal|date=May 22, 2018|work=KTLA|access-date=May 22, 2018|language=en-US}}</ref> In a letter to the USC community, Nikias expressed sympathy and compassion for the students and acknowledged the university community's distress.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://studenthealthresources.usc.edu/message-from-president-nikias-to-the-usc-community-may-18-2018/|title=Message from President Nikias to the USC Community|date=May 18, 2018}}</ref> Before agreeing to step down as president, he presented an in-depth plan for changing the campus culture, revisiting the university's core values, and restructuring the university's operations.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://actionplan.usc.edu/|title=USC Action Plan|date=May 22, 2018}}</ref>\n\nAfter Nikias stepped down in August 2018, Rick Caruso, chair of the USC board of trustees, said: \"As he has always done, Max is taking this action in what he believes to be in the best interest of the university following controversies that have arisen from the unfortunate and unacceptable acts of others. From our investigations, which are not yet completed, we have found absolutely no wrong doing on Max's part.\"<ref name=\"transition\"/>\n\n==Awards and honors==\nNikias is a member of the [[National Academy of Engineering]],<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.nae.edu/MembersSection/Directory20412/31047.aspx|title=Dr. Chrysostomos L. Nikias|website=NAE Website|accessdate=June 2, 2018}}</ref> a fellow of the [[American Academy of Arts and Sciences]],<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.amacad.org/content/news/pressReleases.aspx?pr=206|title=American Academy of Arts and Sciences Inducts 233rd Class of Members|publisher=American Academy of Arts and Sciences |accessdate=August 19, 2015}}</ref> a charter fellow of the [[National Academy of Inventors]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.academyofinventors.org/search-fellows.asp?Cursor=2&QueryItem=%25&GO=N&qSort=%25 |title=Search Fellows - National Academy of Inventors|website=www.academyofinventors.org|accessdate=June 2, 2018}}</ref> an associate member of the [[Academy of Athens (modern)|Academy of Athens]], a life fellow of the [[Institute of Electrical and Electronics Engineers]], and a fellow of the [[American Association for the Advancement of Science]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://membercentral.aaas.org/fellows|title=Archived copy|accessdate=July 20, 2014|url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140727124856/http://membercentral.aaas.org/fellows |archivedate=July 27, 2014}}</ref> Among numerous other honors, he has received the IEEE Simon Ramo Medal,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ieee.org/about/awards/bios/ramo_recipients.html|title=IEEE Simon Ramo Medal Recipients|website=www.ieee.org |accessdate=June 2, 2018}}</ref> an Academic Leadership Award from Carnegie Corporation of New York,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.latimes.com/local/education/la-me-ln-usc-award-20150924-story.html|title=USC President C. L. Max Nikias gets national award with $500,000 for campus|work=Los Angeles Times|date=September 24, 2015}}</ref> the Ellis Island Medal of Honor,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.neco.org/medal-of-honor/2016-medalists|title=2016 Ellis Island Medal of Honor Recipients|url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160608220224/http://www.neco.org/medal-of-honor/2016-medalists|archivedate=June 8, 2016}}</ref> the Woodrow Wilson Center's Award for Public Service,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.usc.edu/82758/usc-president-nikias-receives-woodrow-wilson-award-for-public-service/|title=USC President Nikias receives Woodrow Wilson Award for Public Service - USC News|website=news.usc.edu|accessdate=June 2, 2018|date=June 14, 2015}}</ref> UNICEF's Spirit of Compassion Award, as well as the [[University at Buffalo, The State University of New York|State University of New York at Buffalo's]] Distinguished Alumni Award and Clifford C. Furnas Memorial Award.<ref>{{cite web  |url=http://www.buffalo.edu/UBT/UBT-archives/volume26number3/alumni_news/achievementawards.html |title=UB Today: Alumni News |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170928060405/http://www.buffalo.edu/UBT/UBT-archives/volume26number3/alumni_news/achievementawards.html |archive-date=September 28, 2017 |accessdate=August 7, 2018}}</ref> He also received honorary doctorates from [[Hebrew Union College-Jewish Institute of Religion]];<ref>{{cite web |url=http://huc.edu/news/article/2011/cl-max-nikias-phd-president-university-of-southern-california-brreceived-honorary-doctor-of-humane-letters-from-brhebrew-union-college-jewish-institute-of-religion|title=C.L. Max Nikias, Ph.D., President, University of Southern California, :Received Honorary Doctor of Humane Letters from :Hebrew Union College-Jewish Institute of Religion |accessdate=June 2, 2018}}</ref> his alma mater, the [[National Technical University of Athens]];<ref>{{cite web |url=https://news.usc.edu/82238/nikiases-wrap-up-europe-trip-with-warm-reception-in-athens/|title=Nikiases wrap up Europe trip with warm reception in Athens - USC News|website=news.usc.edu|accessdate=June 2, 2018|date=May 30, 2015}}</ref> the [[University of Cyprus]];<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.kios.ucy.ac.cy/index.php/13-about-us/advisory-board/25-chrysostomos-l-max-nikias.html|title=Chrysostomos L. Max Nikias |publisher=KIOS CoE|accessdate=May 29, 2018}}</ref> University of Crete; University of Piraeus; and University of Strathclyde.<ref>{{cite web|title=USC President Nikias receives honorary degree from Scottish university|url=http://news.usc.edu/124374/usc-president-nikias-receives-honorary-degree-from-scottish-university/|website=USC News|date=June 27, 2017}}</ref> Nikias was awarded the Aristeia medal, the Republic of Cyprus' highest honor in the letters, arts, and sciences. In addition, he received the USC Black Alumni Association's Thomas Kilgore Service Award,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://viterbi.usc.edu/admission/professionalprograms/usc-forum-india/panelists/c-l-max-nikias.htm |title=Viterbi School of Engineering - C. L. Max Nikias |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304031311/https://viterbi.usc.edu/admission/professionalprograms/usc-forum-india/panelists/c-l-max-nikias.htm |archive-date=March 4, 2016 |accessdate=August 7, 2018}}</ref> the Los Angeles Police Museum's Jack Webb Award,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://mynewsla.com/education/2014/09/23/usc-president-honored-jack-webb-award/|title=USC President Honored With Jack Webb Award - MyNewsLA.com|date=September 23, 2014|accessdate=June 2, 2018}}</ref> and earned a commendation for cutting-edge research from the [[Governor of California|governor]] of [[California]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ccst.us/ccstinfo/board/bios/nikias.php |title=CCST Board Member C. L. Max Nikias|website=www.ccst.us |accessdate=June 2, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nNikias lived on the [[Palos Verdes]] Peninsula, an area southwest of Los Angeles, with his wife and two daughters. Following his inauguration as president of USC, he and his family moved to [[San Marino, California|San Marino]], located closer to both USC campuses.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://articles.latimes.com/2010/oct/14/local/la-me-adv-nikias-20101014|title=Many see a clean slate in Friday's inauguration of USC president|date=October 14, 2010|work=Los Angeles Times|accessdate=September 27, 2013}}</ref>\n\n==Publications==\n*Nikias, C. L and Shao, M. ''Signal processing with alpha-stable distributions and applications.'' New York: Wiley, c1995. xiii, 168 p. : ill. ; 25&nbsp;cm. {{ISBN|0-471-10647-X}}\n*Nikias, C. L. and Petropulu, A. P. ''Higher-order spectra analysis: a nonlinear signal processing framework.'' Englewood Cliffs, N.J. : PTR Prentice Hall, c1993. xxii, 537 p. : ill. ; 25&nbsp;cm. {{ISBN|0-13-678210-8}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://presidentemeritus.usc.edu USC President Emeritus biography]\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-aca}}\n{{succession box\n| before=[[Steven B. Sample]]\n| title=11th [[President of the University of Southern California]]\n| years=August 3, 2010 \u2013 August 7, 2018\n| after=[[Wanda Austin]] (interim)\n}}\n{{s-end}}\n{{USC presidents}}\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Nikias, C. L. Max}}\n[[Category:1952 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Presidents of the University of Southern California]]\n[[Category:American electrical engineers]]\n[[Category:University of Connecticut faculty]]\n[[Category:Northeastern University faculty]]\n[[Category:National Technical University of Athens alumni]]\n[[Category:University at Buffalo alumni]]\n[[Category:Fellow Members of the IEEE]]\n[[Category:People from Famagusta District]]\n[[Category:Cypriot emigrants to the United States]]\n[[Category:People from Palos Verdes, California]]\n[[Category:Engineers from California]]\n[[Category:Foreign Members of the Russian Academy of Sciences]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use mdy dates|date=August 2019}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| image = C. L. Max Nikias.jpg\n| alt = C.L. Max Nikias (cropped)\n| order = 11th\n| office = President of the University of Southern California\n| term_start = August 3, 2010\n| term_end = August 7, 2018\n| predecessor = [[Steven Sample]]\n| successor = [[Carol Folt]]\n| birth_name = Chrysostomos Loizos Nikias\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1952|09|30}}\n| birth_place = [[Komi Kebir]], [[Cyprus]]\n| death_date = \n| death_place = \n| alma_mater = [[National Technical University of Athens]], [[University at Buffalo]]\n| residence = \n| profession = [[Electrical engineering]], Higher education, [[Academic administration]]\n| spouse = {{marriage|Niki|1977}}\n| children = 2 daughters\n}}\n\n'''Chrysostomos Loizos \"Max\" Nikias''' ({{lang-el|\u03a7\u03c1\u03c5\u03c3\u03cc\u03c3\u03c4\u03bf\u03bc\u03bf\u03c2 \u039b\u03bf\u0390\u03b6\u03bf\u03c2 \u039d\u03b9\u03ba\u03af\u03b1\u03c2}}; born September 30, 1952) is a Cypriot-American academic, and served as the 11th [[University of Southern California]] president, a position he held from August 3, 2010,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://uscnews.usc.edu/university/c_l_max_nikias_named_11th_president_of_usc.html|title=C. L. Max Nikias Named 11th President of USC|date=March 11, 2010|publisher=USC News|accessdate=September 20, 2010|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100923014604/http://uscnews.usc.edu/university/c_l_max_nikias_named_11th_president_of_usc.html|archive-date=September 23, 2010|url-status=dead}}</ref> to August 7, 2018.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://boardoftrustees.usc.edu/message-from-board-of-trustees-chairman-rick-j-caruso-august-7-2018/|title=Message from Board of Trustees Chairman Rick J. Caruso (August 7, 2018) - Board of Trustees - USC|website=boardoftrustees.usc.edu|accessdate=August 7, 2018}}</ref> He holds the Malcolm R. Currie Chair in Technology and the Humanities and is president [[emeritus]] of the university.<ref name=\"transition\">{{cite web |url=http://universityofsoutherncalifornia.createsend1.com/t/ViewEmail/j/C9A2A4FDE384E2D72540EF23F30FEDED|title=Nikias transitions to president emeritus|date=August 7, 2018}}</ref> He had been at USC since 1991, as a professor, director of national research centers, [[dean (education)|dean]], [[provost (education)|provost]], and president. He holds faculty appointments in both electrical engineering and the classics{{Clarify|reason=Which classics?|date=August 2018}}, and teaches an undergraduate course on the culture of [[Athenian democracy]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.latimes.com/local/education/la-me-nikias-class-20160419-story.html |title=USC president's aim in teaching a classics course is to 'light a fire' for humanities|date=May 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn May 2018, 200 tenured USC professors demanded Nikias's resignation for how his administration dealt with nearly 300 incidents of sexual assault and sexual misconduct allegations against a longtime student health center gynecologist, [[George Tyndall]].<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/hundreds-of-usc-professors-call-for-presidents-ouster-1527024102|title=Hundreds of USC Professors Call for President's Ouster|last=Korn|first=Melissa|date=May 22, 2018|work=Wall Street Journal|access-date=May 23, 2018 |language=en-US |issn=0099-9660}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/05/22/us/usc-faculty-president-nikias.html |title=200 Professors Call for Ouster of U.S.C. President, Citing Lack of 'Moral Authority'|date=May 22, 2018|work=The New York Times |access-date=May 23, 2018|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/05/17/us/USC-gynecologist-young-women.html|title='Just the Grossest Thing': Women Recall Interactions With U.S.C. Doctor|date=May 17, 2018|work=The New York Times |access-date=May 23, 2018|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> He and the board of trustees agreed to an orderly transition to a new president on May 25, 2018, and he stepped down on August 7, 2018.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.insidehighered.com/news/2018/05/29/usc-president-will-step-down|title=USC president will step down|access-date=June 6, 2018|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/05/25/us/usc-nikias-tyndall.html|title=U.S.C. President Agrees to Step Down Over Scandal Involving Gynecologist|date=May 25, 2018|work=The New York Times|access-date=June 6, 2018|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> Following this, Nikias was named president emeritus and a life trustee of the university.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://alumni.usc.edu/wp-content/uploads/2018/08/BoTChair-Communication-080718.pdf |title=BoT Chair Communication 080718 |publisher=University of Southern California |year=2018 |accessdate=August 7, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Early life==\nNikias was born on the Mediterranean island of [[Cyprus]].<ref name=\"Nikias profile\">{{cite news |url=http://articles.latimes.com/2010/mar/12/local/la-me-usc-biobox12-2010mar12|title=Profile of USC's next president|date=March 12, 2010 |work=Los Angeles Times|accessdate=July 21, 2010}}</ref> There, he graduated with honors from the Famagusta Gymnasium, a school that emphasizes sciences, history, and Greco-Roman classics. He married his wife, Niki, in 1977,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.usc.edu/dept/pubrel/trojan_family/winter03/eng-3.html|title=The Climb of His Life|year=2003|publisher=Trojan Family Magazine|accessdate=April 23, 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131002131741/http://www.usc.edu/dept/pubrel/trojan_family/winter03/eng-3.html#|archive-date=October 2, 2013|url-status=dead}}</ref> and the couple have two daughters, Georgiana and Maria.<ref name=\"Nikias profile\"/> He received a degree in electrical and mechanical engineering from the [[National Technical University of Athens]] in 1977, and has an academic interest in Athenian drama and democracy.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.president.usc.edu/bio/|title=C. L. Max Nikias Biography|publisher=usc.edu|accessdate=April 23, 2013}}</ref> Nikias earned a master's degree in 1980 and a Ph.D in 1982 in electrical engineering at the [[University at Buffalo, The State University of New York|State University of New York at Buffalo]].<ref>{{cite thesis |last=Nikias |first= Chrysostomos Loizos|date= 1982|title= A new class of robust spectral estimation algorithms based on minimum covariance recursion error and their application in cardiac data analysis |degree=Ph.D. |publisher= State University of New York at Buffalo |url=http://dl.acm.org/citation.cfm?id=910320|access-date=August 21, 2016}}</ref> His predecessor as USC president, [[Steven Sample]], was likewise an electrical engineer, and served as president of SUNY-Buffalo from 1982 to 1991.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://about.usc.edu/presidentemeritus/|title=About USC \u2013 President Emeritus|accessdate=September 27, 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131002132554/http://about.usc.edu/presidentemeritus/|archive-date=October 2, 2013|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\n\n===Dean of the USC Viterbi School of Engineering (2001\u20132005)===\nFrom 2001 to 2005, Nikias served as dean of the [[USC Viterbi School of Engineering]], solidifying its position as a top-tier engineering school. He directed the expansion of the school's biomedical engineering enterprise and developed its distance-learning program into one of the largest in the country at that time. He oversaw the development of the school's Tutor Hall of Engineering. He also established key partnerships with corporations, among them [[Pratt & Whitney]], [[Airbus]], [[Boeing]], [[Chevron Corporation|Chevron]], and [[Northrop Grumman]], and led a fundraising campaign that brought in more than $250 million, capped by a $52 million school-naming gift from [[Andrew Viterbi|Andrew and Erna Viterbi]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://viterbi.usc.edu/about/viterbi/viterbi_press_release.htm|title=Cell phone pioneer endows Viterbi School of Engineering |publisher=viterbi.usc.edu|accessdate=April 5, 2012}}</ref>\n\n===USC provost (2005\u20132010)===\nFrom June 2005 to August 2010, Nikias served as USC's provost and chief academic officer. He was instrumental in bringing USC trustee [[Steven Spielberg|Steven Spielberg's]] [[USC Shoah Foundation Institute for Visual History and Education|Shoah Foundation Institute]] and its vast video archive of 55,000 testimonies of [[The Holocaust|Holocaust]] survivors to USC.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.usc.edu/uscnews/stories/11601.html|title=USC College to House Shoah Foundation|date=September 10, 2005|publisher=usc.edu|accessdate=April 5, 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111126115711/http://www.usc.edu/uscnews/stories/11601.html|archive-date=November 26, 2011|url-status=dead}}</ref> Nikias also established the university's Edward R. Roybal Institute on Aging, Stevens Center for Innovation, [http://china.usc.edu U.S.-China Institute],<ref>[http://china.usc.edu/ShowArticle.aspx?articleID=204 Nikias announcement] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140714163127/http://china.usc.edu/ShowArticle.aspx?articleID=204# |date=July 14, 2014 }} of the creation of the USC U.S.-China Institute; [http://china.usc.edu/ShowArticle.aspx?articleID=61 Nikias introductory remarks] at inaugural USC U.S.-China Institute conference.</ref> and Levan Institute for Humanities and Ethics. He launched [https://web.archive.org/web/20100620185435/http://www.usc.edu/dept/pubrel/visionsandvoices/ Visions and Voices], USC's campus-wide arts and humanities initiative, as well as a grant program to advance scholarship in the [[humanities]] and [[social science]]s.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.usc.edu/dept/pubrel/visionsandvoices/about.php|title=Visions and Voices: The Arts and Humanities Initiative|publisher=usc.edu|accessdate=September 20, 2010|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100826150957/http://www.usc.edu/dept/pubrel/visionsandvoices/about.php#|archive-date=August 26, 2010|url-status=dead}}</ref> Nikias spearheaded the integration of the [[Keck School of Medicine of USC]]'s faculty practice plans, oversaw the transfer of [[Los Angeles County+USC Medical Center|University Hospital]] and [[USC Norris Comprehensive Cancer Center|USC Norris Cancer Hospital]] from [[Tenet Healthcare Corporation]] to the university, and recruited a new leadership team for USC's medical enterprise.\n\n===USC president (2010\u20132018)===\nAs president, Nikias wrote frequently about a range of nationally significant topics, including the value of\u2014and access to\u2014higher education;<ref>{{cite web|url=https://agenda.weforum.org/2015/01/what-will-the-future-of-education-look-like/|title=What will the future of education look like?|date=January 24, 2015|publisher=World Economic Forum|accessdate=June 18, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/opinions/why-elite-universities-should-admit-more-community-college-grads/2014/10/23/b4dda968-4986-11e4-a046-120a8a855cca_story.html|title=Why elite universities should admit more community college grads|date=October 23, 2014 |work=Washington Post|accessdate=June 18, 2015}}</ref> the future of online education;<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.president.usc.edu/online-education-revolution-hype-reality/|title=Online Education Revolution \u2013 Hype and Reality|date=October 15, 2013|publisher=usc.edu|accessdate=June 18, 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150618203420/http://www.president.usc.edu/online-education-revolution-hype-reality/|archive-date=June 18, 2015|url-status=dead}}</ref> the continued importance of the arts and humanities; the art of leadership through the classics; and the role of elite research universities, particularly as economic drivers.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.president.usc.edu/all-roads-lead-to-southern-california-2012/|title=All Roads Lead to Southern California|date=March 21, 2012|publisher=usc.edu|accessdate=June 18, 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150618203423/http://www.president.usc.edu/all-roads-lead-to-southern-california-2012/|archive-date=June 18, 2015|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nIn 2011, Nikias announced a $6 billion fundraising campaign, which\u2014at the time of its launch\u2014was the largest in the history of higher education.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://articles.latimes.com/2011/aug/28/local/la-me-usc-funds-20110828|title=USC to pursue record-breaking donation total|date=August 28, 2011|work=Los Angeles Times|accessdate=June 18, 2015}}</ref> In six and a half years, USC's campaign has already surpassed the $6 billion mark\u201418 months ahead of schedule\u2014bringing to the university, on the average, $900 million per year. The fundraising campaign has been extended for five more years until 2021.<ref>{{cite web|title=USC Is Raising Money So Fast, It Just Moved the Goalpost|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/usc-is-raising-money-so-fast-it-just-moved-the-goalpost-1487190600|accessdate=May 2, 2017}}</ref> ''The Chronicle of Higher Education'' has called Nikias a \"prodigious fundraiser.\"<ref>{{cite journal|url=http://chronicle.com/article/As-Its-Popular-President/64532/|title=As Its Popular President Retires, USC Eyes An Encore |date=March 7, 2010|journal=The Chronicle of Higher Education|accessdate=April 5, 2012|last1=Keller |first1=Josh }}</ref>\n\nNikias brought the nation's largest literary festival, the [[Los Angeles Times Festival of Books|''Los Angeles Times'' Festival of Books]], to USC.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://articles.latimes.com/2010/sep/23/local/la-me-0923-book-festival-20100923|title=Times Festival of Books will move to USC|date=September 23, 2010|work=Los Angeles Times|accessdate=June 18, 2015}}</ref> In addition, under his leadership, the university embarked on a major capital construction initiative that already includes Wallis Annenberg Hall for [[USC Annenberg School for Communication and Journalism|journalism]], the [[USC Michelson Center for Convergent Bioscience]], Dauterive Hall for social sciences, Fertitta Hall for business, the Kaufman International Dance Center, the McKay Center for athletics, Uytengsu Aquatics Center, the Engemann Student Health Center, a new [[USC School of Cinematic Arts|Cinematic Arts]] building, and the University Club at Stoops, as well as the Soto Building, Currie Residential Hall,<ref>{{cite web |url=https://news.usc.edu/103561/uscs-health-sciences-campus-getting-major-revamp/|title=Health Sciences Campus getting major revamp|date=July 5, 2016}}</ref> and Norris Consultation Center on the [[Campus of the University of Southern California#Health Sciences Campus|Health Sciences Campus]], and beautification projects for both of USC's campuses. The most prominent project, though, is the USC Village, a 1.3 million square-foot center of student residential colleges, that opened in 2017, entirely reimagining the university's landscape.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.latimes.com/local/education/la-me-usc-village-20140915-story.html|title=USC unveiling plans for $650-million housing, retail complex|date=September 15, 2014|work=Los Angeles Times|accessdate=June 18, 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn recognition of his efforts to renew USC's [[USC Trojans|athletic heritage]], ''The New York Times'' selected Nikias as one of a small number of national figures \"who make sports' little corner of the world a better place.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2010/11/25/sports/25anderson.html?_r=0|title=Moments to Savor from the Sports World|date=November 24, 2010 |work=The New York Times|accessdate=April 5, 2012}}</ref>\n\n===Research===\nOver his two-decade career as an active scholar, Nikias gained acclaim for his research in the fields of digital signal processing and communications, digital media systems, and [[biomedicine]]. Some of his other research interests have included [[radar]] and [[sonar]] technologies.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://ee.usc.edu/faculty_staff/faculty_directory/nikias.htm|title=USC Ming Hsieh Department of Electrical Engineering: Chrysostomos L. Nikias|publisher=ee.usc.edu|accessdate=September 20, 2010}}</ref> He has consulted with corporations and the [[federal government of the United States|U.S. government]]. He is the author of more than 275 journal articles and conference papers, three textbooks, and eight patents.\n\n== Transition ==\nIn May 2018, Nikias and the USC board of trustees agreed to an orderly transition to a new president, following a sex abuse scandal regarding USC's student health center's gynecologist and questions{{From whom?|date=August 2018}} about how the university handled it.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.insidehighered.com/news/2018/05/29/usc-president-will-step-down |title=USC president will step down|publisher=|accessdate=June 2, 2018}}</ref>\n\nOver 200 tenured USC professors called for the resignation of Nikias, saying that he had \"lost the moral authority to lead.\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/hundreds-of-usc-professors-call-for-presidents-ouster-1527024102|title=Hundreds of USC Professors Call for President's Ouster|last=Korn|first=Melissa|date=May 22, 2018|work=Wall Street Journal|access-date=May 22, 2018 |language=en-US|issn=0099-9660}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.latimes.com/local/lanow/la-me-ln-usc-faculty-petition-nikias-20180522-story.html|title=200 USC professors demand Nikias step down; trustees express 'full confidence' in president |last=Hamilton |first=Harriet Ryan, Sarah Parvini, Matt|website=latimes.com|access-date=May 22, 2018|date=May 22, 2018 }}</ref> There were concerns over how the university dealt with sexual misconduct allegations against a longtime student health center gynecologist George Tyndall.<ref name=\"LAT 2018-12-12\">{{cite news|url=https://www.latimes.com/local/lanow/la-me-ln-usc-business-school-dean-trustees-20181212-story.html|title=USC trustees back president's ouster of business school dean over handling of harassment cases|newspaper=[[Los Angeles Times]]|first1=Harriet |last1=Ryan|first2=Matt|last2=Hamilton|date=December 13, 2018|access-date=December 16, 2018}}</ref> The allegations are that for decades, Tyndall conducted improper pelvic exams on female students, especially students from [[China]], many of whom were seeing a gynecologist for the first time, and made sexually and racially inappropriate comments.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/05/17/us/USC-gynecologist-young-women.html|title='Just the Grossest Thing': Women Recall Interactions With U.S.C. Doctor|access-date=May 22, 2018|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.scmp.com/news/world/united-states-canada/article/3011851/secret-files-dr-george-tyndall-gynaecologist-usc|title=Secret files on doctor who 'preyed on young Asian students'|date=2019-05-26|website=South China Morning Post|language=en|access-date=2019-10-06}}</ref> \n\nIn a letter to USC's Board of Trustees, a group of faculty members wrote that they had come together to \"express our outrage and disappointment over the mounting evidence of President Nikias' failure to protect our students, our staff, and our colleagues from repeated and pervasive sexual harassment and misconduct.\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://ktla.com/2018/05/22/faculty-members-call-for-usc-president-to-step-down-in-wake-of-gynecologist-scandal/ |title=Faculty Members Call for USC President to Step Down in Wake of Gynecologist Scandal|date=May 22, 2018|work=KTLA|access-date=May 22, 2018|language=en-US}}</ref> In a letter to the USC community, Nikias expressed sympathy and compassion for the students and acknowledged the university community's distress.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://studenthealthresources.usc.edu/message-from-president-nikias-to-the-usc-community-may-18-2018/|title=Message from President Nikias to the USC Community|date=May 18, 2018}}</ref> Before agreeing to step down as president, he presented an in-depth plan for changing the campus culture, revisiting the university's core values, and restructuring the university's operations.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://actionplan.usc.edu/|title=USC Action Plan|date=May 22, 2018}}</ref>\n\nAfter Nikias stepped down in August 2018, Rick Caruso, chair of the USC board of trustees, said: \"As he has always done, Max is taking this action in what he believes to be in the best interest of the university following controversies that have arisen from the unfortunate and unacceptable acts of others. From our investigations, which are not yet completed, we have found absolutely no wrong doing on Max's part.\"<ref name=\"transition\"/>\n\n==Awards and honors==\nNikias is a member of the [[National Academy of Engineering]],<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.nae.edu/MembersSection/Directory20412/31047.aspx|title=Dr. Chrysostomos L. Nikias|website=NAE Website|accessdate=June 2, 2018}}</ref> a fellow of the [[American Academy of Arts and Sciences]],<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.amacad.org/content/news/pressReleases.aspx?pr=206|title=American Academy of Arts and Sciences Inducts 233rd Class of Members|publisher=American Academy of Arts and Sciences |accessdate=August 19, 2015}}</ref> a charter fellow of the [[National Academy of Inventors]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.academyofinventors.org/search-fellows.asp?Cursor=2&QueryItem=%25&GO=N&qSort=%25 |title=Search Fellows - National Academy of Inventors|website=www.academyofinventors.org|accessdate=June 2, 2018}}</ref> an associate member of the [[Academy of Athens (modern)|Academy of Athens]], a life fellow of the [[Institute of Electrical and Electronics Engineers]], and a fellow of the [[American Association for the Advancement of Science]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://membercentral.aaas.org/fellows|title=Archived copy|accessdate=July 20, 2014|url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140727124856/http://membercentral.aaas.org/fellows |archivedate=July 27, 2014}}</ref> Among numerous other honors, he has received the IEEE Simon Ramo Medal,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ieee.org/about/awards/bios/ramo_recipients.html|title=IEEE Simon Ramo Medal Recipients|website=www.ieee.org |accessdate=June 2, 2018}}</ref> an Academic Leadership Award from Carnegie Corporation of New York,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.latimes.com/local/education/la-me-ln-usc-award-20150924-story.html|title=USC President C. L. Max Nikias gets national award with $500,000 for campus|work=Los Angeles Times|date=September 24, 2015}}</ref> the Ellis Island Medal of Honor,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.neco.org/medal-of-honor/2016-medalists|title=2016 Ellis Island Medal of Honor Recipients|url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160608220224/http://www.neco.org/medal-of-honor/2016-medalists|archivedate=June 8, 2016}}</ref> the Woodrow Wilson Center's Award for Public Service,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.usc.edu/82758/usc-president-nikias-receives-woodrow-wilson-award-for-public-service/|title=USC President Nikias receives Woodrow Wilson Award for Public Service - USC News|website=news.usc.edu|accessdate=June 2, 2018|date=June 14, 2015}}</ref> UNICEF's Spirit of Compassion Award, as well as the [[University at Buffalo, The State University of New York|State University of New York at Buffalo's]] Distinguished Alumni Award and Clifford C. Furnas Memorial Award.<ref>{{cite web  |url=http://www.buffalo.edu/UBT/UBT-archives/volume26number3/alumni_news/achievementawards.html |title=UB Today: Alumni News |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170928060405/http://www.buffalo.edu/UBT/UBT-archives/volume26number3/alumni_news/achievementawards.html |archive-date=September 28, 2017 |accessdate=August 7, 2018}}</ref> He also received honorary doctorates from [[Hebrew Union College-Jewish Institute of Religion]];<ref>{{cite web |url=http://huc.edu/news/article/2011/cl-max-nikias-phd-president-university-of-southern-california-brreceived-honorary-doctor-of-humane-letters-from-brhebrew-union-college-jewish-institute-of-religion|title=C.L. Max Nikias, Ph.D., President, University of Southern California, :Received Honorary Doctor of Humane Letters from :Hebrew Union College-Jewish Institute of Religion |accessdate=June 2, 2018}}</ref> his alma mater, the [[National Technical University of Athens]];<ref>{{cite web |url=https://news.usc.edu/82238/nikiases-wrap-up-europe-trip-with-warm-reception-in-athens/|title=Nikiases wrap up Europe trip with warm reception in Athens - USC News|website=news.usc.edu|accessdate=June 2, 2018|date=May 30, 2015}}</ref> the [[University of Cyprus]];<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.kios.ucy.ac.cy/index.php/13-about-us/advisory-board/25-chrysostomos-l-max-nikias.html|title=Chrysostomos L. Max Nikias |publisher=KIOS CoE|accessdate=May 29, 2018}}</ref> University of Crete; University of Piraeus; and University of Strathclyde.<ref>{{cite web|title=USC President Nikias receives honorary degree from Scottish university|url=http://news.usc.edu/124374/usc-president-nikias-receives-honorary-degree-from-scottish-university/|website=USC News|date=June 27, 2017}}</ref> Nikias was awarded the Aristeia medal, the Republic of Cyprus' highest honor in the letters, arts, and sciences. In addition, he received the USC Black Alumni Association's Thomas Kilgore Service Award,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://viterbi.usc.edu/admission/professionalprograms/usc-forum-india/panelists/c-l-max-nikias.htm |title=Viterbi School of Engineering - C. L. Max Nikias |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304031311/https://viterbi.usc.edu/admission/professionalprograms/usc-forum-india/panelists/c-l-max-nikias.htm |archive-date=March 4, 2016 |accessdate=August 7, 2018}}</ref> the Los Angeles Police Museum's Jack Webb Award,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://mynewsla.com/education/2014/09/23/usc-president-honored-jack-webb-award/|title=USC President Honored With Jack Webb Award - MyNewsLA.com|date=September 23, 2014|accessdate=June 2, 2018}}</ref> and earned a commendation for cutting-edge research from the [[Governor of California|governor]] of [[California]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ccst.us/ccstinfo/board/bios/nikias.php |title=CCST Board Member C. L. Max Nikias|website=www.ccst.us |accessdate=June 2, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nNikias lived on the [[Palos Verdes]] Peninsula, an area southwest of Los Angeles, with his wife and two daughters. Following his inauguration as president of USC, he and his family moved to [[San Marino, California|San Marino]], located closer to both USC campuses.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://articles.latimes.com/2010/oct/14/local/la-me-adv-nikias-20101014|title=Many see a clean slate in Friday's inauguration of USC president|date=October 14, 2010|work=Los Angeles Times|accessdate=September 27, 2013}}</ref>\n\n==Publications==\n*Nikias, C. L and Shao, M. ''Signal processing with alpha-stable distributions and applications.'' New York: Wiley, c1995. xiii, 168 p. : ill. ; 25&nbsp;cm. {{ISBN|0-471-10647-X}}\n*Nikias, C. L. and Petropulu, A. P. ''Higher-order spectra analysis: a nonlinear signal processing framework.'' Englewood Cliffs, N.J. : PTR Prentice Hall, c1993. xxii, 537 p. : ill. ; 25&nbsp;cm. {{ISBN|0-13-678210-8}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://presidentemeritus.usc.edu USC President Emeritus biography]\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-aca}}\n{{succession box\n| before=[[Steven B. Sample]]\n| title=11th [[President of the University of Southern California]]\n| years=August 3, 2010 \u2013 August 7, 2018\n| after=[[Wanda Austin]] (interim)\n}}\n{{s-end}}\n{{USC presidents}}\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Nikias, C. L. Max}}\n[[Category:1952 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Presidents of the University of Southern California]]\n[[Category:American electrical engineers]]\n[[Category:University of Connecticut faculty]]\n[[Category:Northeastern University faculty]]\n[[Category:National Technical University of Athens alumni]]\n[[Category:University at Buffalo alumni]]\n[[Category:Fellow Members of the IEEE]]\n[[Category:People from Famagusta District]]\n[[Category:Cypriot emigrants to the United States]]\n[[Category:People from Palos Verdes, California]]\n[[Category:Engineers from California]]\n[[Category:Foreign Members of the Russian Academy of Sciences]]\n", "name_user": "AE0495", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eCareer", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/C._L._Max_Nikias"}
{"title_page": "Nest", "text_new": "{{short description|Place of refuge for animals}}\n{{other uses}}\n[[File:Yelagiri bird's nest.jpg|thumb|right|The elaborate [[bird nest]] of a [[Baya weaver]]]]\n[[File:A Night Heron building a nest.JPG|thumb|A [[Black-crowned night heron|night heron]] building a nest.]]\n[[File:Swans with nest and eggs at Lake Constanze.jpg|thumb|[[Swan]]s with nest and eggs at [[Lake Constance]]]]\nA '''nest''' is a structure built by certain animals to hold [[Egg (biology)|eggs]], offspring, and, occasionally, the animal itself.  Although nests are most closely associated with [[bird]]s, members of all classes of [[vertebrate]]s and some [[invertebrate]]s construct nests.  They may be composed of [[life|organic]] material such as [[twig]]s, [[grass]], and [[leaf|leaves]], or may be a simple depression in the ground, or a hole in a [[Rock (geology)|rock]], [[tree]], or [[building]]. Human-made materials, such as [[String (structure)|string]], [[plastic]], [[cloth]], or [[paper]], may also be used. Nests can be found in all types of [[habitat]].\n\nNest building is driven by a [[biological]] urge known as the [[nesting instinct]] in birds and mammals. Generally each species has a distinctive style of nest.  Nest complexity is roughly correlated with the level of parental care by adults.  Nest building is considered a key adaptive advantage among birds, and they exhibit the most variation in their nests ranging from simple holes in the ground to elaborate [[communal nests]] hosting hundreds of individuals.  Nests of [[prairie dogs]] and several [[social insects]] can host millions of individuals.\n\n==Nest building==\n===Purposes of nesting===\n====Structural purposes====\nNest building is often driven by a biological urge in [[pregnant]] animals to protect one's offspring known as the [[nesting instinct]].  Animals build nests to protect their [[egg (biology)|eggs]], their offspring, or themselves from danger. The simplest nest structures are adapted to hide eggs from [[predator]]s, shield them from the sun or other environmental factors, or simply keep them from being scattered in [[ocean currents]]. In some cases, nests also help provide [[safety in numbers]] for egg-laying animals.<ref name=SDNMH>{{cite web|title=Nests and Nest-building Animals|author=Tom Dem\u00e9r\u00e9|author2=Bradford D. Hollingsworth|publisher=San Diego Natural History Museum|date=Spring 2002|url=http://www.sdnhm.org/archive/research/herpetology/NestBuilding.pdf|accessdate=August 19, 2013|format=pdf}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Pandion haliaetus -Belize -building nest-8.jpg|thumb|left|A pair of [[osprey]]s building a nest.]]\n\n====Social purposes====\nMany nest builders provide parental care to their young, while others simply lay their eggs and leave. [[Brooding]] (incubating eggs by sitting on them) is common among birds. In general, nest complexity increases in relation to the level of parental care provided.<ref name=SDNMH />  Nest building reinforces social behavior, allowing for larger populations in small spaces to the point of increasing the [[carrying capacity]] of an environment.  Insects that exhibit the most complex nest building also exhibit the greatest social structure.  Among mammals, the [[naked mole-rat]] displays a [[Caste (biology)|caste]] structure similar to the [[social insects]] while building extensive [[burrow]]s that house hundreds of individuals. <ref name=Hansell />\n\n===Usage of environment===\nVersatility in use of construction material may be an adaptive advantage (less energy used to gather materials) or a disadvantage (less ability to specialize construction).  The available evidence suggests that [[natural selection]] more often favors [[Generalist and specialist species|specialization over flexibility]] in nest construction.<ref name=Hansell />{{why?|date=August 2018}}\n\nAt the most basic level, there are only two types of nest building: sculpting and assembly.\n====Sculpting====\nSculpting is the process of removing material to achieve a desired outcome.  Most commonly this entails burrowing into the ground or plant matter to create a nesting site.  \n====Assembly====\nAssembly entails gathering, transporting, and arranging materials to create a novel structure.  Transportation has the greatest time and energy cost so animals are usually adapted to build with materials available in their immediate environment. \n\n===Building Materials===\n[[Plant matter]] is the most common construction material for nests. Other common materials include [[fur]] or [[feathers]], perhaps from the animal itself, [[mud]] or [[dirt]], [[fecal matter]], and specialized [[secretions]] from the animal's body. \n\n===Effects on environment===\nNest building can have a substantial impact on the environment in which animals live. The combined [[digging]] activity of [[termite]]s and [[mole-rat]]s in [[South Africa]] has created a \"mima prairie\" landscape marked by huge areas of flat land punctuated by mounds {{convert|30|m|ft}} wide and {{convert|2|m|ft}} high. Similar structures exist in the [[United States]], created by [[pocket gopher]]s, and [[Argentina]], rodents of the genus ''[[Ctenomys]]''.  \n\n====Lasting effects====\nNests constructed by [[megapode]] birds have been mistaken for [[anthropological]] features by professionals, due to their exceptional height ({{convert|10|m|ft|disp=x| [|]}}) and abundance (hundreds in a single location).<ref name=Hansell />\n\n==Nest builders==\n[[File:Natural Beehive and Honeycombs.jpg|thumb|Hundreds of honeybees gather on their honeycomb nest.]]\nNest architecture may be as useful for distinguishing species as the animals' physical appearance. Species identified through such means are called ''ethospecies''. This is especially common in wasps and termites, but also can apply to birds. In most animals, there is some variation in nest construction between individuals. Whether these differences are driven by genetics or learned behavior is unknown.<ref name=Hansell />\n\nWith the exception of a few tunneling mammals, nest builders exhibit no specialized anatomy, instead making use of body parts primarily used for other purposes. This is possibly due to the sporadic nature of nest building, minimizing the selective pressures of anatomy used for nest building.<ref name=Hansell />\n\n===Birds===\n{{main|Bird nest}}\n\nIn general, birds are the most skilled nest builders, although not all species of birds build nests, some laying their [[egg (biology)|eggs]] directly onto rock ledges or bare soil without first modifying the area.  Complex nest building is considered to be one of the key adaptive advantages of birds.<ref name=SDNMH />  Nests help regulate temperature and reduce predation risks, thus increasing the chance that offspring live to adulthood.<ref name=Hansell />\n\nBird nests vary from simple depressions in the ground known as scrapes to largely unstructured collections of branches to elaborately woven pendants or spheres.  The [[megapode]]s, one of the few groups who do not directly brood their young, incubate their young in a mound of decomposing vegetation.  One species, ''[[Macrocephalon maleo]]'', uses volcanic sand warmed by geothermal heat to keep its eggs warm.<ref name=SDNMH />  Among the simple nest builders are [[falcon]]s, [[owl]]s, and many [[shorebird]]s.  The [[Ploceidae|weavers]] exhibit perhaps the most elaborate nests, complete with strands of grass tied into knots.  Most bird nests lie somewhere in the middle, with the majority building cup-shaped nests using some combination of mud, twigs and leaves, and feathers.  Some birds, such [[flamingo]]s and [[swifts]], use saliva to help hold their nest together.  The [[edible-nest swiftlet]] uses saliva alone to construct their nests.<ref name=Britannica />  The [[rufous hornero]] nest is composed entirely of mud and feces, which is placed on tree branches to allow the sun to harden it into a usable structure.<ref name=PopMech /> The [[tailorbird]]s stitch together leaves to provide cover for their nest sites.<ref name=SDNMH />\n\n[[File:Webervogelnst Auoblodge.JPG|thumb|left|A single nesting colony of the sociable weaver may house hundreds of individuals]]\nThe [[sociable weaver]] builds large communal nests in which many individual nests reside.  They divide the nest using walls of grass placed atop a base of large sticks.  At the entrances to the nest, sharp sticks are placed to ward off intruders.<ref name=PopMech /> A single communal site can measure {{convert|2|m|ft}} in height and {{convert|8|m|ft}} in width.  As many as 300 mating pairs may reside in the structure.<ref name=populous>{{cite web|title=Most populous bird's nest|work=Guinness World Records|url=http://www.guinnessworldrecords.com/world-records/12000/most-populous-bird%E2%80%99s-nest|accessdate=August 20, 2013|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140821031439/http://www.guinnessworldrecords.com/world-records/12000/most-populous-bird%E2%80%99s-nest|archivedate=August 21, 2014}}</ref>  Other birds often built their own nests on top of Weaver nest sites.<ref name=PopMech />\n\nSome birds build nests in [[tree]]s, some (such as [[vulture]]s, [[eagle]]s, and many [[seabird]]s) will build them on rocky ledges, and others nest on the ground or in [[burrow]]s.<ref name=Britannica />  Each species has a characteristic nest style, but few are particular about where they build their nests.  Most species will choose whatever site in their environment best protects their nest, taking into account the nest's style.  Several species will build on a cactus whenever possible.  The [[bushtit]] and [[Bullock's oriole]] will suspend their nests from the tips of slender branches.<ref name=SDNMH />  The [[oropendola]]s take hanging nests to the extreme, constructing pouches up to {{convert|1.8|m|ft}} tall using hanging vines as their base.<ref name=SDNMH /><ref name=PopMech />  The hanging nest is attached to thin tree branches, discouraging predation.<ref name=PopMech />  Other species seek out crevices, using buildings or birdhouses when tree holes are not available.<ref name=SDNMH />\n\nTypical bird nests range from {{convert|2|cm|in}} in size ([[hummingbird]]s) to {{convert|2|m|ft}} ([[eagle]]s) in diameter.<ref name=Britannica />  The largest nest on record was made by a pair of [[bald eagles]].  It was {{convert|2.9|m|ft}} in diameter, {{convert|6|m|ft}} deep and was estimated to weigh more than {{convert|2|t|lb}}.<ref name=largest>{{cite web|title=Largest bird's nest|work=Guinness World Records|url=http://www.guinnessworldrecords.com/world-records/10000/largest-birds-nest|accessdate=August 20, 2013}}</ref>  The lightest bird nests may weigh only a few grams.<ref name=Britannica />  Incubation mounds of the [[mallee fowl]] can reach heights of {{convert|4.57|m|ft}} and widths of {{convert|10.6|m|ft}}.  It is estimated the animal uses as much as {{convert|300|t|lb}} of material in its construction.<ref name= populous />  The extinct ''[[Sylviornis neocaledoniae]]'' may have constructed nesting mounds {{convert|50|m|ft}} in diameter.<ref name=Hansell />\n\n===Mammals===\n{{See also|Nest-building in primates|Nest-building in domestic pigs}}\n\nMany species of small mammals such as [[rodent]]s, [[rabbit]]s, and [[ground squirrel]]s dig [[burrow]]s into the ground to protect themselves and their young.<ref name=\"inquiry\"/>  [[Prairie dog]]s build an elaborate system of tunnels which can span large stretches of land.  One such structure, called a town, spanned {{convert|25000|sqmi|km2}} and held an estimated 400 million individuals.  Their homes are adapted to withstand large (above-ground) temperature variation, floods, and fire.  Their young are raised in the deepest chambers where the temperature is the most stable.<ref name=PopMech />\n\nMany mammals, including [[raccoon]]s and [[skunk]]s, seek natural cavities in the ground or in trees to build their nests.  Raccoons, and other rodents, use leaves to build nest underground and in trees. [[Tree squirrel]]s build their nests ([[drey]]s) in trees, while [[vole]]s nest in tall grass.<ref name=\"inquiry\">{{cite web|title=Mammal Nests and Burrows|work=Kids' Inquiry of Diverse Species|publisher=University of Michigan|url=http://www.biokids.umich.edu/guides/tracks_and_sign/build/mammalnests/|accessdate=August 20, 2013|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131203002842/http://www.biokids.umich.edu/guides/tracks_and_sign/build/mammalnests/|archivedate=December 3, 2013}}</ref>  In some species, the nest serve as homes for adults while in others they are used to raise young.  The [[duck-billed platypus]] and the [[echidna]] lay eggs in nests.<ref name=Britannica />\n\n[[Gorilla]]s build fresh nests daily out of leaves and other vegetation in which they sleep at night.  They sometimes also build nests during the day for resting in.  The smaller species of gorilla build their nests in trees, while the larger are confined to the ground.  Nests of the [[western gorilla]], the largest species, measure about {{convert|1|m|ft}} in diameter.<ref>{{cite web|title=Largest mammal to build a nest|work=Guinness World Records|url=http://www.guinnessworldrecords.com/records-10000/largest-mammal-to-build-a-nest/|accessdate=August 20, 2013}}</ref>\n\n===Amphibians===\n[[File:Spawn hatching.JPG|thumb|[[Paradise fish]] begin to hatch from a bubble nest.]]\nSome species of frog build nests ranging from simple to modest complexity.<ref name=Britannica />  Many stream-dwelling frogs lay their eggs in a gelatinous mass which they attach to underwater vegetation.  The jelly structure prevents the eggs from washing away.<ref name=SDNMH />\n\n===Fish===\nFish engage in nest building activities ranging from simply scooping out sediment to building enclosed structures out of plant matter.  Male [[stickleback]]s produce a special enzyme in their kidneys that they use to bind plants together.<ref name=Britannica />\n\n===Reptiles===\nThe [[American alligator]] is known for its parenting skills.  They build large nests of mud and vegetation on river banks or vegetation mats.  The female digs a hole in the center to lay her eggs, covers them, and then guards them for two months until they hatch. When eggs start to hatch, she breaks open the nest which has hardened over time and leads the young to the water where she continues to care for them for another year.  Alligators are very particular about their nesting sites and will abandon a site if things go wrong.<ref name=SDNMH />\n\n[[Cobra]]s use leaves and other debris to build nests in which they lay eggs that both sexes guard.  They carry the vegetation to the nest site by kinking their necks.<ref name=Britannica />  [[Sea turtle]]s dig a hole in the sand above the high tide line in which they lay their eggs.  They then cover the soft eggs to protect them from the sun and predators and leave.<ref name=SDNMH />\n\n===Dinosaurs===\n{{see also|Dinosaur egg}}\n\nFrom the fossil record, it is known that many, or perhaps all, [[dinosaur]]s laid eggs.  Paleontologists have identified a number of features that allow them to distinguish a nesting site from a random clustering of eggs.  Those include regular clustering patterns, the co-occurrence of whole eggs with broken eggs and/or hatchlings, and the occurrence of physical features such as evidence of excavation.<ref name=SDNMH />\n\n[[File:Maiasaura Nest Model.001 - Natural History Museum of London.JPG|thumb|left|''Maiasaura'' probably exhibited great amounts of parental care.]]\nThe ''[[Oviraptor]]'' nests of [[Mongolia]] are perhaps the most famous case of dinosaur nesting.  One specimen was found fossilized atop a nest in a brooding posture, proving the animal had been poorly named (Oviraptor means \"egg taker\").<ref name=SDNMH />\n\nA site known as [[Egg Mountain]] in [[Montana]] provides exceptional evidence of dinosaur nesting behavior.  The site features dozens of nests each with 20 or more eggs belonging to the ''[[Maiasaura]]''.  Juvenile teeth at the site exhibit signs of wear, while the leg bones are not developed enough to walk.  This allowed scientists to conclude that the species provided extensive parental care for its young. It is likely the species covered its nests with sand and vegetation to keep them warm and nested in colonies for increased protection.<ref name=SDNMH />\n\n===Insects===\n[[Social insects]], including most species of [[ant]]s, [[bee]]s, [[termite]]s, and [[wasp]]s, are nest builders.  Their often elaborate nests may be found above or below ground.  Features often include ventilation systems and separate chambers for the queen, her eggs, and developing individuals.<ref name=Britannica>{{cite encyclopedia|title=nest|encyclopedia=Encyclop\u00e6dia Britannica|url=http://www.britannica.com/EBchecked/topic/409792/nest|accessdate=August 19, 2013|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130930094251/http://www.britannica.com/EBchecked/topic/409792/nest|archivedate=September 30, 2013}}</ref>\n\nBees and [[hornet]]s often seek out natural cavities in which to construct their nests, also known as hives, in which they store food and raise their young. Other species of bee and some wasps dig holes in the ground or chew through wood.<ref name=inquiry /> In the species ''[[Megachile rotundata]]'', for example, females construct tubular-shaped nests in rotting wood as well as small holes in the ground, creating, each cell made from circular disks cut from plant leaves using the bee's mandibles.<ref>{{Cite journal|title = Most bees live alone: No hives, no honey, but maybe help for crops|journal = Science News|date = 2007-01-06|issn = 1943-0930|pages = 11\u201313|volume = 171|issue = 1|doi = 10.1002/scin.2007.5591710110|language = en|first = Susan|last = Milius|df = }}</ref> Bee nests are founded upon the wax the secrete from their bodies, while those of wasps are dependent on their ability to turn plant water into paper using their saliva.<ref name=Hansell />  Nests often exhibit divided living, with eggs and food stores kept in distinct parts of the hive.<ref name=\"inquiry\"/>  [[Vespid wasp]]s build complex nests from paper-like material where they lay eggs in individual cells.  When the young hatch, their parents feed them chewed up larvae.  Different species exhibit different nest structures.  [[Paper wasp]] nesting consist of a single tier of cells, while [[yellow jacket]] nests can be many layers thick, reaching up to {{convert|30|cm|ft}} in diameter.<ref name=SDNMH />  Nesting strategies can be plastic, for instance the wasp ''[[Parischnogaster mellyi]]'' will significant vary its nest construction based on environmental conditions, and the wasp ''[[Mischocyttarus mexicanus]]'' is known to nest in groups or alone depending on the distribution of potential nest sites in the area.<ref name=Hansell /><ref name=\"Clouse 2001\">Clouse, R. (2001). \u201cSome effects of group size on the output of beginning nests of ''Mischocyttarus mexicanus'' (Hymenoptera: Vespidae).\u201d ''Florida Entomologist''. 84(3):418-424.</ref>  Nest sizes vary dramatically and the largest wasp nest on record measured {{convert|1.75|m|ft}} in diameter and was {{convert|3.7|m|ft}} tall.  Found in New Zealand, it was likely built by the [[German wasp]].<ref name=wasp>{{cite web|title=Largest wasp nest|work=Guinness World Records|url=http://www.guinnessworldrecords.com/records-10000/largest-wasp-nest/|accessdate=August 20, 2013|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130702031015/http://www.guinnessworldrecords.com/records-10000/largest-wasp-nest|archivedate=July 2, 2013}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Cathedral Termite Mound - brewbooks.jpg|thumb|Termite nests can extend {{convert|5|m|ft}} or more in the air.]]\nTermites build elaborate nests that span multiple generations and may last decades.<ref name=Hansell />  Using chewed wood, mud, and feces they build large mounds which may extend well into the air.<ref name=PopMech />  The largest nests, built by members of genus ''[[Amitermes]]'', stand nearly {{convert|7|m|ft}} tall with a similar circumference at the base, and host millions of individuals.<ref name=Hansell />  Termite mounds are constructed to allow for excellent air flow, regulating the mound temperature.  The mounds protect against drying and predation allowing many species to lose ancestral traits such as hard bodies, skin pigmentation, and good eyesight.  [[Magnetic termite]]s construct their nests with flattened sides along the North-South axis to ensure maximum warming during the winter, while exposing minimal surface area to the harshest mid-day sunshine.<ref name=Hansell>{{cite book|title=Bird Nests and Construction Behaviour|url=https://archive.org/details/birdnestsconstru0000hans|url-access=registration|author=Mike Hansell|year=2000|publisher=Cambridge University Press|isbn=978-0521460385}}</ref>  Other termite species use their nests to farm fungi.<ref name=PopMech />\n\nAnt nests feature an elaborate colony structure that may extend {{convert|2|m|ft}} or more underground.  As the structure gets further underground, individual chambers become farther and farther apart indicating that the ant is aware of its depth.  It is hypothesized that they accomplish this by sensing the level of [[carbon dioxide]] in the soil.<ref name=PopMech>{{cite web|title=8 Amazing Architects of the Animal Kingdom|author=Mary Beth Griggs|work=Popular Mechanics|url=http://www.popularmechanics.com/science/environment/8-amazing-architects-of-the-animal-kingdom|accessdate=August 22, 2013|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130813043232/http://www.popularmechanics.com/science/environment/8-amazing-architects-of-the-animal-kingdom|archivedate=August 13, 2013|date=2011-05-26}}</ref>  The [[leaf cutter ant]] builds a complex nest which can house 8 million individuals.  Its nests feature numerous chambers, most notably garden chambers where they farm fungus on leaves they harvest from the forest.<ref name=Hansell />\n\nSpecies such as the [[carpenter ant]] and the wasp ''[[Polistes exclamans]]'' build \"satellite nests\" - smaller nests near, but separate from, the main nest.<ref name=Strassman /><ref>{{cite web|title=Carpenter ants|year=2008|author=Jeff Hahn|author2=Colleen Cannon|author3=Mark Ascerno|publisher=University of Minnesota|url=http://www1.extension.umn.edu/garden/insects/find/carpenter-ants/|accessdate=August 20, 2013|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130910120951/http://www1.extension.umn.edu/garden/insects/find/carpenter-ants/|archivedate=September 10, 2013}}</ref> These satellite nests are used as an insurance against predators and [[parasites]]; if the original nest is attacked, surviving members can move the satellite nest.<ref name=Strassman>{{Cite journal|author=Joan E. Strassman|year=1981|title=Evolutionary implications of early male and satellite nest production in ''Polistes exclamans'' colony cycles|journal=[[Behavioral Ecology and Sociobiology]]|volume=8|issue=1|pages=55\u201364|doi=10.1007/BF00302844}}</ref> Other species such as the Black hover wasp, ''[[Parischnogaster alternata]],'' construct nests in clusters with the central core composed of older colonies surrounded by younger colonies.<ref>Landi, M., C. Coster-Longman, and S. Turillazzi. \"Are the Selfish Herd and the Dilution Effects Important in Promoting Nest Clustering in the Hover Wasp (Stenogastrinae Vespidae Hymenoptera)?\" Ethology Ecology & Evolution 14.4 (2002): 297-305. Web.</ref>\n\nThe Eastern carpenter bee, ''[[Eastern carpenter bee|Xylocopa virginica]],'' is unique in that individuals of that species build their nests in wood, bamboo culms, agave stalks, and other similar materials, although their preferred nesting material is pine or cedar lumber.  When digging the nests, they use the wood shavings scraped from the wall to create partitions within the tunnels.  The nests are usually round and have about 1-4 tunnels, each with multiple branches.  Because these materials are often useful for humans in construction, ''X. virgininica's'' nesting behavior presents the disadvantage of weakening wood in manmade structures.<ref>Balduf, W. V. (1962-05-01). \"Life of the Carpenter Bee, Xylocopa virginica (Linn.) (Xylocopidae, Hymenoptera)\". Annals of the Entomological Society of America 55 (3): 263\u2013271. doi:10.1093/aesa/55.3.263. ISSN 0013-8746.</ref>\n\n==Effects on other species==\nThe abundance of biological resources within the nest has led to a number of specialized predators.  The [[aardvark]] and the [[Tamandua|ant eater]] use long tongues to prey upon termite and ant nests.  Birds such as the [[European honey buzzard|honey buzzard]] specialize on wasp and bee nests, a resource also targeted by the [[tropical hornet]].  [[Symbiosis]], ranging from feeding on waste to [[obligate parasitism]], is common within the nest.  Ant nests alone support symbiotes spanning six classes of [[arthropod]]s which includes 35 families just from the [[beetle]]s.<ref name=Hansell />\n\n==Names of nests==\n* A [[badger]]'s nest is called a [[sett]].\n* A [[beaver]]'s nest is called a [[beaver lodge|lodge]].\n* An [[eagle]]'s nest is called an eyrie.\n* A [[pheasant]]'s nest is called a nide.\n* A [[rabbit]]'s nest is called a form.\n* A [[squirrel]]'s or [[Pseudocheiridae|ringtail possum]]'s nest is called a [[drey]].\n* A [[wasp]]'s nest is called a vespiary.\n\n==See also==\n* [[Oology]]\n* [[Bird's nest soup]]\n* [[Nest box]]\n* [[Tree house]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Nests}}\n{{EB1911 poster|Nest}}\n* [http://www.earthlife.net/birds/nests.html Birds as Builders of Homes]\n* {{Cite Americana|wstitle=Nidification| first=Ernest |last=Ingersoll |authorlink=Ernest Ingersoll}}\n* {{Cite Americana|wstitle=Fishes, Nest-making by|first=Ernest |last=Ingersoll}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Shelters built or used by animals]]\n[[Category:Poultry]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Place of refuge for animals}}\n{{other uses}}\n[[File:Yelagiri bird's nest.jpg|thumb|right|The elaborate [[bird nest]] of a [[Baya weaver]]]]\n[[File:A Night Heron building a nest.JPG|thumb|A [[Black-crowned night heron|night heron]] building a nest.]]\n[[File:Swans with nest and eggs at Lake Constanze.jpg|thumb|[[Swan]]s with nest and eggs at [[Lake Constance]]]]\nA '''nest''' is a structure built by certain animals to hold [[Egg (biology)|eggs]], offspring, and, occasionally, the animal itself.  Although nests are most closely associated with [[bird]]s, members of all classes of [[vertebrate]]s and some [[invertebrate]]s construct nests.  They may be composed of [[life|organic]] material such as [[twig]]s, [[grass]], and [[leaf|leaves]], or may be a simple depression in the ground, or a hole in a [[Rock (geology)|rock]], [[tree]], or [[building]]. Human-made materials, such as [[String (structure)|string]], [[plastic]], [[cloth]], or [[paper]], may also be used. Nests can be found in all types of [[habitat]].\n\nNest building is driven by a [[biological]] urge known as the [[nesting instinct]] in birds and mammals. Generally each species has a distinctive style of nest.  Nest complexity is roughly correlated with the level of parental care by adults.  Nest building is considered a key adaptive advantage among birds, and they exhibit the most variation in their nests ranging from simple holes in the ground to elaborate [[communal nests]] hosting hundreds of individuals.  Nests of [[prairie dogs]] and several [[social insects]] can host millions of individuals.\n\n==Nest building==\n===Purposes of nesting===\n====Structural purposes====\nNest building is often driven by a biological urge in [[pregnant]] animals to protect one's offspring known as the [[nesting instinct]].  Animals build nests to protect their [[egg (biology)|eggs]], their offspring, or themselves from danger. The simplest nest structures are adapted to hide eggs from [[predator]]s, shield them from the sun or other environmental factors, or simply keep them from being scattered in [[ocean currents]]. In some cases, nests also help provide [[safety in numbers]] for egg-laying animals.<ref name=SDNMH>{{cite web|title=Nests and Nest-building Animals|author=Tom Dem\u00e9r\u00e9|author2=Bradford D. Hollingsworth|publisher=San Diego Natural History Museum|date=Spring 2002|url=http://www.sdnhm.org/archive/research/herpetology/NestBuilding.pdf|accessdate=August 19, 2013|format=pdf}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Pandion haliaetus -Belize -building nest-8.jpg|thumb|left|A pair of [[osprey]]s building a nest.]]\n\n====Social purposes====\nMany nest builders provide parental care to their young, while others simply lay their eggs and leave. [[Brooding]] (incubating eggs by sitting on them) is common among birds. In general, nest complexity increases in relation to the level of parental care provided.<ref name=SDNMH />  Nest building reinforces social behavior, allowing for larger populations in small spaces to the point of increasing the [[carrying capacity]] of an environment.  Insects that exhibit the most complex nest building also exhibit the greatest social structure.  Among mammals, the [[naked mole-rat]] displays a [[Caste (biology)|caste]] structure similar to the [[social insects]] while building extensive [[burrow]]s that house hundreds of individuals. <ref name=Hansell />\n\n===Usage of environment===\nVersatility in use of construction material may be an adaptive advantage (less energy used to gather materials) or a disadvantage (less ability to specialize construction).  The available evidence suggests that [[natural selection]] more often favors [[Generalist and specialist species|specialization over flexibility]] in nest construction.<ref name=Hansell />{{why?|date=August 2018}}\n\nAt the most basic level, there are only two types of nest building: sculpting and assembly.\n====Sculpting====\nSculpting is the process of removing material to achieve a desired outcome.  Most commonly this entails burrowing into the ground or plant matter to create a nesting site.  \n====Assembly====\nAssembly entails gathering, transporting, and arranging materials to create a novel structure.  Transportation has the greatest time and energy cost so animals are usually adapted to build with materials available in their immediate environment. \n\n===Building Materials===\n[[Plant matter]] is the most common construction material for nests. Other common materials include [[fur]] or [[feathers]], perhaps from the animal itself, [[mud]] or [[dirt]], [[fecal matter]], and specialized [[secretions]] from the animal's body. \n\n===Effects on environment===\nNest building can have a substantial impact on the environment in which animals live. The combined [[digging]] activity of [[termite]]s and [[mole-rat]]s in [[South Africa]] has created a \"mima prairie\" landscape marked by huge areas of flat land punctuated by mounds {{convert|30|m|ft}} wide and {{convert|2|m|ft}} high. Similar structures exist in the [[United States]], created by [[pocket gopher]]s, and [[Argentina]], rodents of the genus ''[[Ctenomys]]''.  \n\n====Lasting effects====\nNests constructed by [[megapode]] birds have been mistaken for [[anthropological]] features by professionals, due to their exceptional height ({{convert|10|m|ft|disp=x| [|]}}) and abundance (hundreds in a single location).<ref name=Hansell />\n\n==Nest builders==\n[[File:Natural Beehive and Honeycombs.jpg|thumb|Hundreds of honeybees gather on their honeycomb nest.]]\nNest architecture may be as useful for distinguishing species as the animals' physical appearance. Species identified through such means are called ''ethospecies''. This is especially common in wasps and termites, but also can apply to birds. In most animals, there is some variation in nest construction between individuals. Whether these differences are driven by genetics or learned behavior is unknown.<ref name=Hansell />\n\nWith the exception of a few tunneling mammals, nest builders exhibit no specialized anatomy, instead making use of body parts primarily used for other purposes. This is possibly due to the sporadic nature of nest building, minimizing the selective pressures of anatomy used for nest building.<ref name=Hansell />\n\n===Birds===\n{{main|Bird nest}}\n\nIn general, birds are the most skilled nest builders, although not all species of birds build nests, some laying their [[egg (biology)|eggs]] directly onto rock ledges or bare soil without first modifying the area.  Complex nest building is considered to be one of the key adaptive advantages of birds.<ref name=SDNMH />  Nests help regulate temperature and reduce predation risks, thus increasing the chance that offspring live to adulthood.<ref name=Hansell />\n\nBird nests vary from simple depressions in the ground known as scrapes to largely unstructured collections of branches to elaborately woven pendants or spheres.  The [[megapode]]s, one of the few groups who do not directly brood their young, incubate their young in a mound of decomposing vegetation.  One species, ''[[Macrocephalon maleo]]'', uses volcanic sand warmed by geothermal heat to keep its eggs warm.<ref name=SDNMH />  Among the simple nest builders are [[falcon]]s, [[owl]]s, and many [[shorebird]]s.  The [[Ploceidae|weavers]] exhibit perhaps the most elaborate nests, complete with strands of grass tied into knots.  Most bird nests lie somewhere in the middle, with the majority building cup-shaped nests using some combination of mud, twigs and leaves, and feathers.  Some birds, such [[flamingo]]s and [[swifts]], use saliva to help hold their nest together.  The [[edible-nest swiftlet]] uses saliva alone to construct their nests.<ref name=Britannica />  The [[rufous hornero]] nest is composed entirely of mud and feces, which is placed on tree branches to allow the sun to harden it into a usable structure.<ref name=PopMech /> The [[tailorbird]]s stitch together leaves to provide cover for their nest sites.<ref name=SDNMH />\n\n[[File:Webervogelnst Auoblodge.JPG|thumb|left|A single nesting colony of the sociable weaver may house hundreds of individuals]]\nThe [[sociable weaver]] builds large communal nests in which many individual nests reside.  They divide the nest using walls of grass placed atop a base of large sticks.  At the entrances to the nest, sharp sticks are placed to ward off intruders.<ref name=PopMech /> A single communal site can measure {{convert|2|m|ft}} in height and {{convert|8|m|ft}} in width.  As many as 300 mating pairs may reside in the structure.<ref name=populous>{{cite web|title=Most populous bird's nest|work=Guinness World Records|url=http://www.guinnessworldrecords.com/world-records/12000/most-populous-bird%E2%80%99s-nest|accessdate=August 20, 2013|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140821031439/http://www.guinnessworldrecords.com/world-records/12000/most-populous-bird%E2%80%99s-nest|archivedate=August 21, 2014}}</ref>  Other birds often built their own nests on top of Weaver nest sites.<ref name=PopMech />\n\nSome birds build nests in [[tree]]s, some (such as [[vulture]]s, [[eagle]]s, and many [[seabird]]s) will build them on rocky ledges, and others nest on the ground or in [[burrow]]s.<ref name=Britannica />  Each species has a characteristic nest style, but few are particular about where they build their nests.  Most species will choose whatever site in their environment best protects their nest, taking into account the nest's style.  Several species will build on a cactus whenever possible.  The [[bushtit]] and [[Bullock's oriole]] will suspend their nests from the tips of slender branches.<ref name=SDNMH />  The [[oropendola]]s take hanging nests to the extreme, constructing pouches up to {{convert|1.8|m|ft}} tall using hanging vines as their base.<ref name=SDNMH /><ref name=PopMech />  The hanging nest is attached to thin tree branches, discouraging predation.<ref name=PopMech />  Other species seek out crevices, using buildings or birdhouses when tree holes are not available.<ref name=SDNMH />\n\nTypical bird nests range from {{convert|2|cm|in}} in size ([[hummingbird]]s) to {{convert|2|m|ft}} ([[eagle]]s) in diameter.<ref name=Britannica />  The largest nest on record was made by a pair of [[bald eagles]].  It was {{convert|2.9|m|ft}} in diameter, {{convert|6|m|ft}} deep and was estimated to weigh more than {{convert|2|t|lb}}.<ref name=largest>{{cite web|title=Largest bird's nest|work=Guinness World Records|url=http://www.guinnessworldrecords.com/world-records/10000/largest-birds-nest|accessdate=August 20, 2013}}</ref>  The lightest bird nests may weigh only a few grams.<ref name=Britannica />  Incubation mounds of the [[mallee fowl]] can reach heights of {{convert|4.57|m|ft}} and widths of {{convert|10.6|m|ft}}.  It is estimated the animal uses as much as {{convert|300|t|lb}} of material in its construction.<ref name= populous />  The extinct ''[[Sylviornis neocaledoniae]]'' may have constructed nesting mounds {{convert|50|m|ft}} in diameter.<ref name=Hansell />\n\n===Mammals===\n{{See also|Nest-building in primates|Nest-building in domestic pigs}}\n\nMany species of small mammals such as [[rodent]]s, [[rabbit]]s, and [[ground squirrel]]s dig [[burrow]]s into the ground to protect themselves and their young.<ref name=\"inquiry\"/>  [[Prairie dog]]s build an elaborate system of tunnels which can span large stretches of land.  One such structure, called a town, spanned {{convert|25000|sqmi|km2}} and held an estimate 400 million individuals.  Their homes are adapted to withstand large (above-ground) temperature variation, floods, and fire.  Their young are raised in the deepest chambers where the temperature is the most stable.<ref name=PopMech />\n\nMany mammals, including [[raccoon]]s and [[skunk]]s, seek natural cavities in the ground or in trees to build their nests.  Raccoons, and other rodents, use leaves to build nest underground and in trees. [[Tree squirrel]]s build their nests ([[drey]]s) in trees, while [[vole]]s nest in tall grass.<ref name=\"inquiry\">{{cite web|title=Mammal Nests and Burrows|work=Kids' Inquiry of Diverse Species|publisher=University of Michigan|url=http://www.biokids.umich.edu/guides/tracks_and_sign/build/mammalnests/|accessdate=August 20, 2013|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131203002842/http://www.biokids.umich.edu/guides/tracks_and_sign/build/mammalnests/|archivedate=December 3, 2013}}</ref>  In some species, the nest serve as homes for adults while in others they are used to raise young.  The [[duck-billed platypus]] and the [[echidna]] lay eggs in nests.<ref name=Britannica />\n\n[[Gorilla]]s build fresh nests daily out of leaves and other vegetation in which they sleep at night.  They sometimes also build nests during the day for resting in.  The smaller species of gorilla build their nests in trees, while the larger are confined to the ground.  Nests of the [[western gorilla]], the largest species, measure about {{convert|1|m|ft}} in diameter.<ref>{{cite web|title=Largest mammal to build a nest|work=Guinness World Records|url=http://www.guinnessworldrecords.com/records-10000/largest-mammal-to-build-a-nest/|accessdate=August 20, 2013}}</ref>\n\n===Amphibians===\n[[File:Spawn hatching.JPG|thumb|[[Paradise fish]] begin to hatch from a bubble nest.]]\nSome species of frog build nests ranging from simple to modest complexity.<ref name=Britannica />  Many stream-dwelling frogs lay their eggs in a gelatinous mass which they attach to underwater vegetation.  The jelly structure prevents the eggs from washing away.<ref name=SDNMH />\n\n===Fish===\nFish engage in nest building activities ranging from simply scooping out sediment to building enclosed structures out of plant matter.  Male [[stickleback]]s produce a special enzyme in their kidneys that they use to bind plants together.<ref name=Britannica />\n\n===Reptiles===\nThe [[American alligator]] is known for its parenting skills.  They build large nests of mud and vegetation on river banks or vegetation mats.  The female digs a hole in the center to lay her eggs, covers them, and then guards them for two months until they hatch. When eggs start to hatch, she breaks open the nest which has hardened over time and leads the young to the water where she continues to care for them for another year.  Alligators are very particular about their nesting sites and will abandon a site if things go wrong.<ref name=SDNMH />\n\n[[Cobra]]s use leaves and other debris to build nests in which they lay eggs that both sexes guard.  They carry the vegetation to the nest site by kinking their necks.<ref name=Britannica />  [[Sea turtle]]s dig a hole in the sand above the high tide line in which they lay their eggs.  They then cover the soft eggs to protect them from the sun and predators and leave.<ref name=SDNMH />\n\n===Dinosaurs===\n{{see also|Dinosaur egg}}\n\nFrom the fossil record, it is known that many, or perhaps all, [[dinosaur]]s laid eggs.  Paleontologists have identified a number of features that allow them to distinguish a nesting site from a random clustering of eggs.  Those include regular clustering patterns, the co-occurrence of whole eggs with broken eggs and/or hatchlings, and the occurrence of physical features such as evidence of excavation.<ref name=SDNMH />\n\n[[File:Maiasaura Nest Model.001 - Natural History Museum of London.JPG|thumb|left|''Maiasaura'' probably exhibited great amounts of parental care.]]\nThe ''[[Oviraptor]]'' nests of [[Mongolia]] are perhaps the most famous case of dinosaur nesting.  One specimen was found fossilized atop a nest in a brooding posture, proving the animal had been poorly named (Oviraptor means \"egg taker\").<ref name=SDNMH />\n\nA site known as [[Egg Mountain]] in [[Montana]] provides exceptional evidence of dinosaur nesting behavior.  The site features dozens of nests each with 20 or more eggs belonging to the ''[[Maiasaura]]''.  Juvenile teeth at the site exhibit signs of wear, while the leg bones are not developed enough to walk.  This allowed scientists to conclude that the species provided extensive parental care for its young. It is likely the species covered its nests with sand and vegetation to keep them warm and nested in colonies for increased protection.<ref name=SDNMH />\n\n===Insects===\n[[Social insects]], including most species of [[ant]]s, [[bee]]s, [[termite]]s, and [[wasp]]s, are nest builders.  Their often elaborate nests may be found above or below ground.  Features often include ventilation systems and separate chambers for the queen, her eggs, and developing individuals.<ref name=Britannica>{{cite encyclopedia|title=nest|encyclopedia=Encyclop\u00e6dia Britannica|url=http://www.britannica.com/EBchecked/topic/409792/nest|accessdate=August 19, 2013|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130930094251/http://www.britannica.com/EBchecked/topic/409792/nest|archivedate=September 30, 2013}}</ref>\n\nBees and [[hornet]]s often seek out natural cavities in which to construct their nests, also known as hives, in which they store food and raise their young. Other species of bee and some wasps dig holes in the ground or chew through wood.<ref name=inquiry /> In the species ''[[Megachile rotundata]]'', for example, females construct tubular-shaped nests in rotting wood as well as small holes in the ground, creating, each cell made from circular disks cut from plant leaves using the bee's mandibles.<ref>{{Cite journal|title = Most bees live alone: No hives, no honey, but maybe help for crops|journal = Science News|date = 2007-01-06|issn = 1943-0930|pages = 11\u201313|volume = 171|issue = 1|doi = 10.1002/scin.2007.5591710110|language = en|first = Susan|last = Milius|df = }}</ref> Bee nests are founded upon the wax the secrete from their bodies, while those of wasps are dependent on their ability to turn plant water into paper using their saliva.<ref name=Hansell />  Nests often exhibit divided living, with eggs and food stores kept in distinct parts of the hive.<ref name=\"inquiry\"/>  [[Vespid wasp]]s build complex nests from paper-like material where they lay eggs in individual cells.  When the young hatch, their parents feed them chewed up larvae.  Different species exhibit different nest structures.  [[Paper wasp]] nesting consist of a single tier of cells, while [[yellow jacket]] nests can be many layers thick, reaching up to {{convert|30|cm|ft}} in diameter.<ref name=SDNMH />  Nesting strategies can be plastic, for instance the wasp ''[[Parischnogaster mellyi]]'' will significant vary its nest construction based on environmental conditions, and the wasp ''[[Mischocyttarus mexicanus]]'' is known to nest in groups or alone depending on the distribution of potential nest sites in the area.<ref name=Hansell /><ref name=\"Clouse 2001\">Clouse, R. (2001). \u201cSome effects of group size on the output of beginning nests of ''Mischocyttarus mexicanus'' (Hymenoptera: Vespidae).\u201d ''Florida Entomologist''. 84(3):418-424.</ref>  Nest sizes vary dramatically and the largest wasp nest on record measured {{convert|1.75|m|ft}} in diameter and was {{convert|3.7|m|ft}} tall.  Found in New Zealand, it was likely built by the [[German wasp]].<ref name=wasp>{{cite web|title=Largest wasp nest|work=Guinness World Records|url=http://www.guinnessworldrecords.com/records-10000/largest-wasp-nest/|accessdate=August 20, 2013|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130702031015/http://www.guinnessworldrecords.com/records-10000/largest-wasp-nest|archivedate=July 2, 2013}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Cathedral Termite Mound - brewbooks.jpg|thumb|Termite nests can extend {{convert|5|m|ft}} or more in the air.]]\nTermites build elaborate nests that span multiple generations and may last decades.<ref name=Hansell />  Using chewed wood, mud, and feces they build large mounds which may extend well into the air.<ref name=PopMech />  The largest nests, built by members of genus ''[[Amitermes]]'', stand nearly {{convert|7|m|ft}} tall with a similar circumference at the base, and host millions of individuals.<ref name=Hansell />  Termite mounds are constructed to allow for excellent air flow, regulating the mound temperature.  The mounds protect against drying and predation allowing many species to lose ancestral traits such as hard bodies, skin pigmentation, and good eyesight.  [[Magnetic termite]]s construct their nests with flattened sides along the North-South axis to ensure maximum warming during the winter, while exposing minimal surface area to the harshest mid-day sunshine.<ref name=Hansell>{{cite book|title=Bird Nests and Construction Behaviour|url=https://archive.org/details/birdnestsconstru0000hans|url-access=registration|author=Mike Hansell|year=2000|publisher=Cambridge University Press|isbn=978-0521460385}}</ref>  Other termite species use their nests to farm fungi.<ref name=PopMech />\n\nAnt nests feature an elaborate colony structure that may extend {{convert|2|m|ft}} or more underground.  As the structure gets further underground, individual chambers become farther and farther apart indicating that the ant is aware of its depth.  It is hypothesized that they accomplish this by sensing the level of [[carbon dioxide]] in the soil.<ref name=PopMech>{{cite web|title=8 Amazing Architects of the Animal Kingdom|author=Mary Beth Griggs|work=Popular Mechanics|url=http://www.popularmechanics.com/science/environment/8-amazing-architects-of-the-animal-kingdom|accessdate=August 22, 2013|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130813043232/http://www.popularmechanics.com/science/environment/8-amazing-architects-of-the-animal-kingdom|archivedate=August 13, 2013|date=2011-05-26}}</ref>  The [[leaf cutter ant]] builds a complex nest which can house 8 million individuals.  Its nests feature numerous chambers, most notably garden chambers where they farm fungus on leaves they harvest from the forest.<ref name=Hansell />\n\nSpecies such as the [[carpenter ant]] and the wasp ''[[Polistes exclamans]]'' build \"satellite nests\" - smaller nests near, but separate from, the main nest.<ref name=Strassman /><ref>{{cite web|title=Carpenter ants|year=2008|author=Jeff Hahn|author2=Colleen Cannon|author3=Mark Ascerno|publisher=University of Minnesota|url=http://www1.extension.umn.edu/garden/insects/find/carpenter-ants/|accessdate=August 20, 2013|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130910120951/http://www1.extension.umn.edu/garden/insects/find/carpenter-ants/|archivedate=September 10, 2013}}</ref> These satellite nests are used as an insurance against predators and [[parasites]]; if the original nest is attacked, surviving members can move the satellite nest.<ref name=Strassman>{{Cite journal|author=Joan E. Strassman|year=1981|title=Evolutionary implications of early male and satellite nest production in ''Polistes exclamans'' colony cycles|journal=[[Behavioral Ecology and Sociobiology]]|volume=8|issue=1|pages=55\u201364|doi=10.1007/BF00302844}}</ref> Other species such as the Black hover wasp, ''[[Parischnogaster alternata]],'' construct nests in clusters with the central core composed of older colonies surrounded by younger colonies.<ref>Landi, M., C. Coster-Longman, and S. Turillazzi. \"Are the Selfish Herd and the Dilution Effects Important in Promoting Nest Clustering in the Hover Wasp (Stenogastrinae Vespidae Hymenoptera)?\" Ethology Ecology & Evolution 14.4 (2002): 297-305. Web.</ref>\n\nThe Eastern carpenter bee, ''[[Eastern carpenter bee|Xylocopa virginica]],'' is unique in that individuals of that species build their nests in wood, bamboo culms, agave stalks, and other similar materials, although their preferred nesting material is pine or cedar lumber.  When digging the nests, they use the wood shavings scraped from the wall to create partitions within the tunnels.  The nests are usually round and have about 1-4 tunnels, each with multiple branches.  Because these materials are often useful for humans in construction, ''X. virgininica's'' nesting behavior presents the disadvantage of weakening wood in manmade structures.<ref>Balduf, W. V. (1962-05-01). \"Life of the Carpenter Bee, Xylocopa virginica (Linn.) (Xylocopidae, Hymenoptera)\". Annals of the Entomological Society of America 55 (3): 263\u2013271. doi:10.1093/aesa/55.3.263. ISSN 0013-8746.</ref>\n\n==Effects on other species==\nThe abundance of biological resources within the nest has led to a number of specialized predators.  The [[aardvark]] and the [[Tamandua|ant eater]] use long tongues to prey upon termite and ant nests.  Birds such as the [[European honey buzzard|honey buzzard]] specialize on wasp and bee nests, a resource also targeted by the [[tropical hornet]].  [[Symbiosis]], ranging from feeding on waste to [[obligate parasitism]], is common within the nest.  Ant nests alone support symbiotes spanning six classes of [[arthropod]]s which includes 35 families just from the [[beetle]]s.<ref name=Hansell />\n\n==Names of nests==\n* A [[badger]]'s nest is called a [[sett]].\n* A [[beaver]]'s nest is called a [[beaver lodge|lodge]].\n* An [[eagle]]'s nest is called an eyrie.\n* A [[pheasant]]'s nest is called a nide.\n* A [[rabbit]]'s nest is called a form.\n* A [[squirrel]]'s or [[Pseudocheiridae|ringtail possum]]'s nest is called a [[drey]].\n* A [[wasp]]'s nest is called a vespiary.\n\n==See also==\n* [[Oology]]\n* [[Bird's nest soup]]\n* [[Nest box]]\n* [[Tree house]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Nests}}\n{{EB1911 poster|Nest}}\n* [http://www.earthlife.net/birds/nests.html Birds as Builders of Homes]\n* {{Cite Americana|wstitle=Nidification| first=Ernest |last=Ingersoll |authorlink=Ernest Ingersoll}}\n* {{Cite Americana|wstitle=Fishes, Nest-making by|first=Ernest |last=Ingersoll}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Shelters built or used by animals]]\n[[Category:Poultry]]\n", "name_user": "Longchess", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eMammals:spelling", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Nest"}
{"title_page": "Samanpur", "text_new": "{{Infobox settlement\n<!--See the table at Infobox settlement for all fields and descriptions of usage-->\n<!-- Basic info  -->\n|name                   = Samanpur\n|other_name             =\n|native_name            = \u0938\u092e\u093e\u0928\u092a\u0941\u0930\n|nickname               =\n|settlement_type        = [[Village development committee (Nepal)|Village development committee]]\n|motto                  =\n<!-- images and maps  -->\n|image_skyline          =\n|image_caption          =\n|image_flag             =\n|image_seal             =\n|image_map              = <!-- NepalRautahatDistrictmap.png -->\n|mapsize                = 300px\n|map_caption            = Map of the village development committees in Rautahat District\n|pushpin_map            = Nepal\n|pushpin_label_position = bottom\n|pushpin_mapsize        = 300\n|pushpin_map_caption    = Location in Nepal\n<!-- Location -->\n|subdivision_type       = Country\n|subdivision_name       = {{flag|Nepal}}\n|subdivision_type1      = [[Zones of Nepal|Zone]]\n|subdivision_name1      = [[Narayani Zone]]\n|subdivision_type2      = [[Districts of Nepal|District]]\n|subdivision_name2      = [[Rautahat District]]\n|<!-- Politics -->\n|government_footnotes   =\n|government_type        =\n|leader_title           =\n|leader_name            =\n|leader_title1          = <!-- for places with, say, both a mayor and a city manager -->\n|leader_name1           =\n|established_title      = <!-- Settled -->\n|established_date       =\n<!-- Area    -->\n|unit_pref                =  <!--Enter: Imperial, if Imperial (metric) is desired-->\n|area_footnotes           =\n|area_total_km2           = <!-- ALL fields dealing with a measurements are subject to automatic unit conversion-->\n<!-- Population   -->\n|population_as_of               = 1991\n|population_footnotes           =\n|population_note                =\n|population_total               = 5352\n|population_density_km2         = auto\n|population_blank1_title        = Ethnicities\n<!-- General information  -->\n|timezone               = [[Nepal Time]]\n|utc_offset             = +5:45\n|timezone_DST           =\n|utc_offset_DST         =\n|coordinates            = {{coord|26.98|85.39|type:adm2nd_region:NP_source:unmaps-enwiki|display=inline,title}}\n|elevation_footnotes    = <!--for references: use <ref> </ref> tags-->\n|elevation_m            =\n<!-- Area/postal codes & others -->\n|postal_code_type       =  <!-- enter ZIP code, Postcode, Post code, Postal code... -->\n|postal_code            =\n|area_code              =\n|blank_name             =\n|blank_info             =\n|website                =\n|footnotes              = \n}}\n\n'''Samanpur''' was a [[Village development committee (Nepal)|village development committee]] in [[Rautahat District]] in the [[Narayani Zone]] of south-eastern [[Nepal]].\n\nJust before [[2017 Nepalese local elections]], it was merged with other 5 [[Village development committee (Nepal)|Village development committee]]s  Gamhariya, Sangrampur, Bahuwa Madanpur, Dharampur and Bariyarpur to form [[Gadhimai Municipality, Nepal|Gadhimai Municipality]].<ref>[http://gadhimaimun.gov.np/ ''Gadhimai Municipality'', \"Merging of VDCs\"], 2017</ref>\n\nAt the time of the [[1991 Nepal census]], it had a population of 5352 people living in 982 individual households.<ref>{{Cite web| url=http://www.digitalhimalaya.com/collections/nepalcensus/form.php?selection=1|title=Nepal Census 2001|work=Nepal's Village Development Committees|publisher=[[Digital Himalaya]]|accessdate=29 November 2008 }}</ref>\n\n==References==\n<references />\n\n{{Rautahat District}}\n\n[[Category:Populated places in Rautahat District]]\n\n\n{{Province2NP-geo-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox settlement\n<!--See the table at Infobox settlement for all fields and descriptions of usage-->\n<!-- Basic info  -->\n|name                   = Samanpur\n|other_name             =\n|native_name            = \u0938\u092e\u09